<1ST_LINE>r w PM-UPI     09-15 0419</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-UPI,0429</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>UPI `Alive And Kicking,' Looks To Profit Next Year</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ROBERT M. ANDREWS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   United Press International is ``alive and
kicking'' and expects to turn a modest profit in the third quarter
of 1989, says UPI president Paul Steinle.
   Steinle also announced that UPI has reached agreement to provide
financial and stock market information from Standard & Poor's Corp.
for its newspaper clients.
   ``I am happy to tell you ... that UPI is alive and well and
kicking,'' Steinle told a news conference at the National Press
Club on Wednesday.
   Reviewing the first six months since he took over day-to-day
operation of the news service from Mexican newspaper publisher
Mario Vazquez Rana in February, Steinle said the new UPI management
team is on schedule with initiatives designed to reverse operating
losses that totaled $18 million last year.
   Steinle said UPI has slashed administrative costs by more than
$10 million, reorganized its business operations and raised between
$8 million and $10 million toward its goal of $15 million in
capital funds from outside ``institutional investors,'' including
some British lenders.
   He said UPI has reached a one-year agreement with the Wire
Service Guild, plans to open a fourth new domestic news bureau soon
and is hiring employees for a new regional business report being
launched in October.
   Net staff layoffs have been held to less than the 150 employees
planned when UPI's ``turnaround business plan'' was announced on
March 30, he said. The UPI staff now totals about 1,150 employees
worldwide, he said.
   Steinle said loss of UPI subscribers since the end of 1987 has
produced a drop of $3 million to $5 million in estimated annual
revenues of about $70 million. He said some other newspapers have
signed contracts but he declined to identify them.
   He said ``reaction is favorable'' to a new UPI marketing
strategy of selling 11 individually priced news services separately
to its newspaper subscribers. The list will be expanded to 23
products in the future, he said.
   Steinle said UPI expects to post another, much smaller operating
loss this year and show a ``small profit'' in the July-September
quarter of 1989. He refused to give dollar estimates, but last
March he and UPI chairman Earl W. Brian projected a $100,000
third-quarter profit next year.
   Steinle estimated that the non-media share of UPI's estimated
$70 million in annual revenues will grow from about $3 million last
year to between $15 million and $18 million in the next five years.
</TEXT>
