<FILEID>AP-NR-09-15-88 0018EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Libya-Economy     09-15 0860</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Libya-Economy,0887</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Libyans Enjoys Fruits of Freer Economy</HEAD>
<HEAD>An AP Extra</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDITOR'S NOTE </NOTE>
<TEXT>
   The writer just returned from an 11-day visit to
Libya, her third this year.
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>By FRANCES D'EMILIO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TRIPOLI, Libya (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Libya's new entrepreneurs gather at the
bus depot until there's at least five or six of them, pile into old
Peugeot station wagons used as a taxis _ and rumble off to Tunisia.
   They are taking advantage of a recent relaxation of economic and
travel restrictions.
   After a 95-mile drive to the border, they can buy Japanese
radios, televisions, furniture or other goods difficult to find in
Libya: batteries, watches, polo shirts.
   They also might do some selling. Many Libyans buy up at
subsidized prices whatever they can find in the poorly-stocked
state supermarkets and sell to Tunisians at a profit.
   In a speech to the nation on Sept. 1, the 19th anniversary of
his seizing power in a coup, Moammar Gadhafi said Libyans could
become ``bourgeois,'' as long as they don't accumulate wealth by
exploiting others. A few days earlier, he declared that black
markets were fine because ``it's what the people want,'' though the
revolution rejects capitalism.
   As recently as two years ago, what the people wanted seemed to
count little.
   Following dramatic drops in crude oil prices in mid-decade,
Libya decided to concentrate its shrinking income on the oil
industry and the military. It left foreign companies with hundreds
of millions of dollars in unpaid bills and stopped virtually all
imports of consumer goods.
   Shoppers waited on bread lines and scoured shelves in vain for
eggs and cheese. Soap powder, toilet paper and toothpaste were
scarce, even on the black market.
   Such shortages didn't sit well with Libyans, who under Gadhafi
had grown accustomed to one of Africa's highest standards of
living, estimated at $6,000 per capita by the Middle East Economic
Digest.
   Newspapers carried letters from unhappy Libyans. Consumers stood
up and complained at local meetings of Basic People's Congresses,
the grass-roots governing bodies.
   Making matters worse was Gadhafi's 1985 order expelling tens of
thousands of foreign workers. Under the revolutionary system,
Libyans are forbidden to work for other Libyans, except for
relatives or in profit-sharing jobs in industry. Suddenly, farms
had no Tunisian workers; hotels, no Moroccan waiters.
   Most foreign businessmen and diplomats, who spoke on condition
of anonymity for fear of reprisal, say that Gadhafi became worried
about his popularity, especially after the United States bombed the
cities of Tripoli and Benghazi in April 1986 to retaliate for what
Washington called his support of terrorists.
   Last October, the border between Tunisia and Libya was reopened,
allowing workers to return. A few months later, Gadhafi liberalized
trade between the two countries.
   The colonel was obtensibly in quest of unity with his North
African neighbors, but economic needs, too, loomed large in the
rapprochement.
   In March, Libyan authorities quietly allowed small businesses to
import some goods for sale. Until then, what imports were permitted
arrived through giant state companies. Gadhafi recently criticized
these firms as corrupt, saying their employees often kept the
goods, especially coveted car parts, for themselves and friends.
   Tunisians now stream into Libya, their cars loaded with
foreign-made cigarettes, appliances and clothing. At Tripoli's
``souk,'' or traditional outdoor market, they elbow for space to
hawk their wares in streets that were virtually empty of shoppers a
year ago.
   There have been other changes.
   ``Before, we had to sell everything to the government and wait
sometimes 20 days or a month for payment,'' said a cloth maker in
his shop in Tripoli's main souk. ``Now everyone comes to the market
to buy _ at 11 a.m., it's so crowded you can't even move,'' he says.
   Down the block, a man cooks omelettes at an outdoor table and
stuffs them into rolls for hungry shoppers. Two elderly women
shrouded in white spread out a mat on the ground and sell
barrettes, cologne and imported hand lotion. Arabic music blares
from a speaker on one table, where tapes by popular Western
performers like Madonna and Sting are also for sale.
   Some items are still in short supply. Chicken seems to be
everywhere, but veal and beef are hard to find.
   Still, the goods in the souk put to shame the so-called
supersouks, the state-run supermarkets the government had hoped
would put an end to private enterprise.
   One day this month, grocery shelves of one supermarket were bare
of meat. There was little but soap bars, locally produced honey,
imported powdered milk, and a counter filled with 4.5 pound
packages of Finnish Edam cheese.
   Some Libyans, like one 64-year-old taxi driver, are cautious
about their economic future. He said he and his 16 children would
like to open their own business but that he won't invest his
savings until satisfied that Gadhafi won't pull in the reins on the
freer economy.
   Meanwhile, the nation itself has joined in the wheeling and
dealing. Keen on generating an income apart from pumping oil, Libya
has invested in a chain of gasoline stations in Italy, Libya's
largest trading partner. It is also reportedly looking into opening
petrochemical plants in Europe.
</TEXT>
