<1ST_LINE>r a PM-Supermen     09-15 0247</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Supermen,0257</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Two Men Lift Car Off Pinned Woman</HEAD>
<DATELINE>REDDING, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Superman wasn't available to rescue Terry
Rickerd when her car rolled onto her chest, but two bystanders
performed a mighty good imitation of the missing Man of Steel.
   Gary Robinson, 49, of Redding, and John Maclellan, 35, of nearby
French Gulch, lifted Rickerd's Pontiac 6000 sedan and freed her
Tuesday at the gasoline pumps of Robinson's convenience store, said
police officer Rich Schneck.
   She was treated at Mercy Medical Center in Redding and released.
   ``He doesn't look like he could lift a fly swatter, but he's a
heck of a lot stronger than he looks,'' Wendy Wright, an employee
at the store, said of Robinson, who owns the Oasis AM-PM
Mini-Market.
   ``I guess in an emergency situation like that your adrenaline
just gets going,'' Miss Wright said.
   Police said Rickerd drove in to buy gasoline, but couldn't pull
up to the pumps because other cars were in the way. She put the car
in neutral and climbed out, carrying her 15-month-old son.
   Suddenly, the car started to roll. She tried to get back in to
stop it, but was knocked to the ground by the door and the car
rolled on her.
   The little boy rolled free and was uninjured.
   ``Gary came inside and said he and this guy John had lifted up
the car and she got out,'' Wright said. ``He was shaking so bad he
couldn't even write out our paychecks.''
</TEXT>
