<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Lesotho-Glance     09-15 0264</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Lesotho-Glance,0272</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Lesotho at a Glance</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Pope-Odyssey, PM-Lesotho-Hostages</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Facts and figures about Lesotho:
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   THE LAND _ Lesotho, entirely inside the borders of South Africa,
is a mountainous kingdom covering 11,720 square miles, roughly the
size of Maryland.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   THE PEOPLE _ Virtually all of Lesotho's approximately 1.6
million people are from the indigenous Basotho tribe. Roughly 70
percent of the people are Christian, about 45 percent of them Roman
Catholics. English and Sesotho are the official languages. Maseru,
with about 100,000 people, is the capital and largest city. Roughly
one-half of the adult male labor force works as migrant laborers in
South African mines. About 55 percent of the people are literate.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   THE ECONOMY _ At present, the country's most lucrative natural
resource is water. It has signed an agreement with South Africa to
sell water from the massive, multimillion-dollar Lesotho Highlands
Water project, construction of which has just begun. Only 13
percent of the land is able to be cultivated and 20 percent of the
country's food must be imported. Some small-scale mining and
manufacturing exist.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   HISTORY _ Formerly known as Basutoland, Lesotho was the scene of
fighting between the Basotho and white Afrikaner settlers until
Britain took responsibility for the country and made it a
protectorate in 1984. It became independent on Oct. 4, 1966. In
January 1986, military officers overthew the long-ruling, leftist
prime minister, Leabua Jonathan, whose relations with South Africa
had become increasingly strained. The military council remains in
control, and administers the government in consultation with King
Moshoeshoe II.
</TEXT>
