<FILEID>AP-NR-09-15-88 0105EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w PM-TaintedBlood Bjt   09-15 0647</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Tainted Blood, Bjt,610</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Red Cross Releases Results of Internal Review and Agreement With
FDA</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CRISPIN Y. CAMPBELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An internal review of the Red Cross's blood
service regions indicates that more than 2,400 blood products were
released improperly over a six-month period _ 518 of them without
complete testing for deadly diseases.
   ``The review found no indication that any Red Cross center
issued blood for transfusion that had a confirmed positive test for
AIDS or hepatitis B,'' said Dr. S. Gerald Sandler of Red Cross
blood services told a news conference Wednesday.
   Despite this, he noted that the 518 blood products had been
issued before all record checks or testing had been completed.
``That information was not known at the time of their release, and
the products should not have been released,'' Sandler said.
   Dr. Ernst R. Jaffe, chairman of the organization's Blood Service
Committee, meanwhile, announced that the Red Cross, in compliance
with the recommendations of its review board, signed a voluntary
agreement with the Food and Drug Administration to help avoid such
errors in the future.
   ``Less than a year ago, Red Cross discovered that the increase
in the number of tests conducted and blood samples quarantined also
increased the potential for human error,'' he said.
   Following the release of improperly tested blood products at
facilities in Washington, D.C., earlier this year, the Red Cross
committed itself to ``a national zero error goal and launched a
nationwide review'' to determine the extent of these mistakes and
to develop ways to reduce their potential, Jaffe said.
   The investigation revealed that of 6 million blood products,
576,426 were quarantined or destroyed properly, while 2,420 were
released improperly, including the 518 released before all testing
was completed, he said. The six-month period when this occurred was
September 1987 to March 1988.
   ``Most mistakes involved donations that tested negative for
AIDS, but for various reasons were not in compliance with Red Cross
or FDA directives that require such donations to be quarantined
and-or destroyed,'' Victor W. Schmitt, vice president of Red Cross
blood services, said in a statement.
   ``An example given is the situation in which a donor who
received previous false-positive test results gives blood again.
FDA and Red Cross require that any subsequent donations be
quarantined and-or destroyed, even when they test negative for AIDS
and hepatitis B.''
   In the cases in which improperly tested blood products had been
released, Sandler said the donors were contacted for retesting to
assure that no tainted blood had been transmitted.
   The review found that 88 percent of the mistaken releases were
concentrated in four Red Cross regions: the Carolinas region based
in Charlotte, N.C.; the Midwest region based in Omaha, Neb.; the
Missouri-Illinois region based in St. Louis; and the Tidewater
region based in Norfolk, Va.
   The survey also found that serious deviations from FDA and Red
Cross directives occurred in five regions: the Midwest Region; the
Missouri-Illinois region; the Carolinas region; the Tennessee
Valley region based in Nashville; and the Northeastern New York
region based in Albany, N.Y.
   Meanwhile, 26 of the 56 Red Cross centers were found not to have
released any blood products improperly, another 20 centers had
fewer than 10 improper releases each, with eight of those having
only one erroneous release apiece.
   Corrective measures being implemented by the Red Cross include:
   _The suspension or replacement of top medical administrative
personnel.
   _The institution of a new national clearance system for plasma
that will recheck each unit prior to processing.
   _Ongoing evaluation and development of improvement in computer
systems.
   _Retraining staff in FDA practices and Red Cross standards, as
well as specific procedures for laboratory and computer operations.
   _Completing a review of regional standard operating procedures
with the FDA and initiating a further comprehensive review of all
operating procedures in order to update and advise regions of the
requirements.
</TEXT>
