<FILEID>AP-NR-09-15-88 0119EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w PM-AirlineComputers     09-15 0567</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Airline Computers,560</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Study Says Airline Computer Reservation Systems Cut Competition</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ALAN FRAM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Some of the nation's largest airlines have an
unfair competitive advantage because they own the computer
reservation systems that travel agents use to book passengers, a
congressional report says.
   The General Accouting Office study, released Wednesday,
concluded that the Department of Transportation should try to
correct the ``anti-competitive features'' of the reservation
systems. The GAO is Congress' investigative agency.
   Chairman Norman Mineta, D-Calif., whose House aviation
subcommittee held a hearing on the report, criticized the
Transportation Department for not acting sooner.
   ``The department appears to be unwilling to take any action'' on
computer reservation systems ``without substantial prodding and
adverse publicity,'' he said.
   The computer systems which the nation's travel agents use to
reserve seats on flights _ as well as rental cars and lodging _ are
owned by some of the nation's largest airlines. Each system's owner
earns money by collecting a fee from the airline on which a seat is
selected, and by charging travel agents an annual subscription fee
for use of the computer.
   American Airlines owns the SABRE system, which dominates the
market by garnering 43 percent of the country's computer
reservation system revenues. United Airline's Apollo system has 32
percent of the market; PARS, owned by Trans World Airlines and
Northwest Airlines, has 10 percent; Texas Air Corp.'s System One
has 10 percent; and Delta Airline's DATAS II has 5 percent.
   Until the government banned the practice in November 1984,
airlines owning computer reservation systems tended to list their
own flights first on the display screens, making it more likely
that they would sell more tickets.
   But the report cited statistics demonstrating that airlines
which own computer reservation systems continue to have ``an
artificial competitive advantage.''
   The GAO cited a May 1988 Transportation Department study
estimating that airlines which own computer reservation systems
increase their revenues between 9 percent and 40 percent over what
they would have earned without the computers.
   The DOT report also said the booking fees charged by the owners
of the two largest reservation systems _ about $1.84 per flight _
are about double the costs the owners incur.
   ``Competing airlines, who pay the booking fees, have little
alternative to paying those fees if they wish to remain competitive
in the air travel business,'' GAO concluded.
   The GAO study estimated that in 1986, SABRE transferred $343
million to American Airlines from other carriers in fees and lost
bookings; Apollo transferred $303 million; System One $84 million;
PARS $67 million; and DATAS II $46 million.
   ``These transfers ... reduce competition in the industry by
artificially imposing a cost penalty on some carriers and
subsidizing others,'' the GAO report said.
   The study also said it is difficult for rival airlines to start
new computer reservation systems because the contracts travel
agents sign typically last five years, and involve penalties for
termination.
   Robert L. Pettit, the transportation department's associate
deputy secretary, said the agency wants to ``proceed cautiously
before adopting any regulation that would reduce the vendors'
incentives to upgrade or market their systems or would lead to
higher costs for participating airlines or subscribers.''
   American Airlines spokesman John Hotard, speaking from the
company's offices in Fort Worth, Texas, said the systems operate
fairly.
   ``We think the marketplace should be the arena in which this
battle is fought,'' he said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
