<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Japan-Earthquake     09-15 0242</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Japan-Earthquake,0247</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Two Strong Earthquakes Rock Northern Japan</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Two strong earthquakes hit Japan's northernmost
main island of Hokkaido Thursday, a meteorological agency said.
There were no reports of injury or damage.
   The first earthquake struck at 9:27 a.m. (8:27 p.m. EDT
Wednesday) and was centered off the coast of Hokkaido's eastern
port city of Nemuro, at a depth of about 30 miles, said Sotoharu
Taniguchi, a seismologist at the Sapporo District Meteorological
Observatory.
   He said a reading on the Richter scale was not available, but
added that it registered a 3 on the Japanese scale of 7 in Nemuro,
608 miles northwest of Tokyo.
   The epicenter of the second temblor, which registered a 5 on the
Richter and hit at 5:11 a.m. (4:11 p.m. EDT Wednesday), was located
in the southern part of the Hidaka mountain range at a depth of
about 42 miles, Taniguchi said.
   He added that the two quakes were unrelated and the epicenters
were about 120 miles apart.
   A tremor measuring 3 on the Japanese scale can shake buildings,
while a 4 will topple vases. The scale measures the intensity of an
earthquake at a particular location and is not convertible to the
Richter scale.
   The Richter scale measures the magnitude of a quake according to
ground motion as recorded on seismographs. An earthquake of 5 on
the Richter is considered ``very strong'' and a 6 ``severe,''
capable of widespread damage near the epicenter.
</TEXT>
