<FILEID>AP-NR-09-15-88 0122EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w PM-Japan-Trade     09-15 0607</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Japan-Trade,610</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Rice Industry Calls for Action to End Japanese Barriers</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MIKE ROBINSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Rice producer and processor groups are calling
on the government for a major campaign to end Japanese trade
barriers, including retaliation if nothing else works.
   ``The time has come for the government of Japan to take the
steps necessary for us to compete'' in the Japanese market, Sen.
David Pryor, D-Ark., told a news conference Wednesday at which the
request was announced.
   Rice producer groups petitioned U.S. Trade Representative
Clayton K. Yeutter for assistance on grounds that Japanese refusal
to permit rice imports represents an unfair trade barrier.
   Yeutter must decide within 45 days whether to proceed with the
case. The next step would be negotiation with Japan and, if that
failed, a request for relief under the 97-nation General Agreement
on Tariffs and Trade, a Geneva-based body that sets and monitors
international trade rules.
   Failure in that effort would trigger retaliatory action after
two years under the new trade law approved by Congress and signed
by President Reagan this summer.
   The president of Japan's 5.5 million member Central Union of
Agricultural Cooperatives, Mitsugu Horiuchi, reacted to the U.S.
industry's action by saying the petition ``could have a serious
influence on the political and economic relations between Japan and
the United States.''
   The move ``distorts a harmonious agricultural trade climate
between Japan and the U.S. in which the United States has a
substantial trade surplus,'' said the head of the farm
organization, which is known as the Zenchu.
   His statement was released in Washington by Zenchu spokesman
Bill Dabaghi, who said Japan already has made ``enormous strides''
in opening its agricultural markets by concluding beef and citrus
agreements with the United States this year.
   The Zenchu spokesman said the U.S. rice industry had acted
irresponsibly in raising the issue at the time of a presidential
campaign and ``hyperventilating it.'' He said opening the Japanese
rice market to American imports would be a disaster for that
nation's farmers.
   Japan has been the largest foreign buyer of American farm
products for more than two decades. Last year, it bought $5.5
billion worth and the total for 1988 is forecast at $6.9 million.
   Many of these purchases consist of corn and other feed grains
not grown in large quantities, if at all, in Japan. It has set up
rigid curbs on rice imports to protect its farmers from foreign
competition.
   Large-scale, high-tech American farming methods produce rice at
far below the Japanese cost levels. If all trade restraints were
swept away, American growers could be expected to command a
substantial share of the Japanese market in short order.
   Industry officials said rice priced at $300 a ton in the United
States would cost $2,500 a ton in Japan.
   They told the news conference, however, that they have no
intention of trying to wipe out Japanese rice farming.
   ``We are not looking for an opportunity to flood the Japanese
market,'' said J. Stephen Gabbert, president of the Rice Millers
Association. The group filed the trade petition in a joint effort
with the Rice Council for Market Development, a growers group.
   The petition seeks to gain 2.5 percent of the Japanese rice
market in the first of a four-year phase-in and expand to 10
percent, or 1 million tons, by the fourth year.
   Senators from rice-producing states were on hand to push the
petition, with Sen. Pete Wilson, R-Calif., declaring the industry
had tried to get the Japanese to import American rice voluntarily.
   ``As always the response has been a virtual stone wall,'' said
Wilson. ``And that is not good enough.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
