<1ST_LINE>r p PM-KennedyProfile     09-15 0401</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Kennedy Profile,0412</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Tradition, Religious Strength Leads Young Kennedy To Political
Path</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Also in Thursday AMs report.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By KIMBERLY M. SHEARIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PROVIDENCE, R.I. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Pictures of Kennedys, living and dead,
line the walls and decorate the tables of Patrick Kennedy's living
room.
   ``I've been given a name, and I think there's a certain
responsibility that goes hand-in-hand with that name,'' he once
said. ``It would be easier to sit back and enjoy all the things
I've been given.''
   Kennedy, 21, a Providence College junior and son of Sen. Edward
M. Kennedy, D-Mass., achieved his goal of becoming a state
representative Wednesday night, defeating five-term incumbent John
Skeffington with 57 percent of the vote.
   For two years, as a member of the Young Democrats, he has worked
with and talked to neighbors in the Mount Pleasant neighborhood of
northwest Providence.
   He is noncommittal about how long he will serve. His face merely
lights up when a questioner asks about any desires to follow the
rest of his family to Congress.
   His cousin, Joseph Kennedy Jr. of Boston, has represented
Cambridge, Mass., in Congress since 1986. Another cousin, Kathleen
Kennedy Townsend of Maryland, ran unsuccessfully for Congress the
same year.
   Kennedy's brother, Edward M. Kennedy Jr., and sister, Kara
Kennedy, Patrick's, are running their father's senatorial
re-election campaign this year.
   His late grandfather, Joseph Kennedy Sr. was the former U.S.
ambassaor to England.
   Slain President John F. Kennedy, Patrick's uncle, was a
Massachusetts representative and senator before winning the
nation's highest office in 1960. Robert Kennedy, former attorney
general and U.S. senator from New York, was running for president
when he was assassinated in 1968.
   Kennedy campaigned for better and more affordable health care,
better care for the elderly and a crime-free community. A campaign
breakfast Sunday, attended by his father, brother and about 500
supporters, showed that he seems to have a significant following
among the elderly.
   His campaign manager, Chris Nocera, mentioned that once, Kennedy
was talking to two elderly women who were quite distraught. He
consoled the women and told them to pray on the rosary, Nocera said.
   The religious strength, Kennedy said, is as much a part of him
as the Kennedy name and tradition. His grandmother, 98-year-old
Rose Kennedy, taught him to have his religious faith above all else
and if nothing else.
   ``They can't take that away from you,'' Kennedy said.
</TEXT>
