<1ST_LINE>r p PM-Dukakis-Ads     09-15 0462</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Dukakis-Ads,460</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dukakis Has New Ads on Leadership, Crime; New Man at Helm</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Political Rdp Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN KING</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Michael Dukakis, his stance on crime under a
new advertising attack from George Bush, is responding with a crime
ad of his own this week and also is airing a new commercial
promoting his leadership record.
   The new ads come at a time when the Dukakis advertising team is
taking on a new look, with the executive in charge of John Hancock
Insurance Co.'s communications efforts tapped to join the campaign
and coordinate its advertising efforts.
   The new Dukakis crime commercial, called ``Tough,'' will make
its debut later this week, according to Dukakis aides. It will
attempt to counter a new Bush commercial attacking Dukakis for
supporting a Massachusetts furlough program that, until amended
earlier this year, allowed passes to be approved for convicted
murderers sentenced to no-parole terms.
   The Bush ad began airing this week in California and Texas.
   ``Which candidate for president can you really count on to be
tough on crime?'' the announcer in the Bush ad asks. ``George
Bush.''
   Dukakis' crime ad discusses crime-related statistics during his
tenure as Massachusetts governor, including a 13 percent drop in
the state's crime rate over the past four years, a significant
increase in convictions and jailings of drug dealers and a 20
percent increase in the number of police in state law enforcement
agencies.
   ``Leadership. It's getting real results,'' the announcer in the
Dukakis ad concludes.
   The other new Dukakis ad, ``Responsibility,'' began its
nationwide airing Wednesday night.
   It also stresses the theme of leadership _ a line of attack
Dukakis has been using against Bush in recent campaign appearances.
   ``Michael Dukakis balanced 10 budgets in a row and still cut
taxes five times,'' the announcer in the 30-second
``Responsibility'' ad says.
   The ad also refers to the rate of personal income growth in
Massachusetts, which is twice the national average, and the
governor's successful effort to win passage of the first state law
guaranteeing health insurance to virtually all workers.
   ``That's why America's governors, both Democrat and Republican,
voted Michael Dukakis the most effective governor in the nation,''
the announcer says.
   Dukakis campaign aides declined to say how much the campaign was
spending on the new round of ads, to be supplemented by a new
commerical paid for by the Democratic National Committee.
   The naming of John Hancock's David D'Allesandro to head the
Dukakis ad team was characterized by several Dukakis aides as a key
move in an effort to bring more direction to advertising strategy.
   The move was orchestrated by John Sasso, the Dukakis confidant
who recently returned as vice chairman of the Democratic campaign,
said Dukakis media adviser Francis O'Brien.
</TEXT>
