<1ST_LINE>r p PM-Bentsen-Notebook     09-15 0658</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Bentsen-Notebook,650</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Bentsen Finds a Bit of His Past on Hangar Wall</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Political Rdp Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By STEVEN KOMAROW</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>HARLINGEN, Texas (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Democratic vice presidential candidate
Lloyd Bentsen found a piece of his past here, in the form of a
chunk of a B-24 bomber mounted on a hangar wall.
   Bentsen, in a campaign speech Wednesday at the Confederate Air
Force, reflected repeatedly on how the collection of restored World
War II planes brought back memories.
   Bentsen flew 34 missions in the War in Europe. Although there
were no B-24s on hand when he visited the CAF, there was a Vultee
BT-13 trainer, the same type the Texas senator used when he was
learning to fly.
   Shedding his suit coat for a leather jacket in the moist Texas
heat, the 67-year-old Bentsen climbed into the cockpit and fired it
up, waving from the open canopy as the wind from the prop blew back
his hair.
   ``I lost my favorite picture of my wife, and my wallet, flying
one of these things upside down with the canopy open in Alabama,''
he recalled.
   Bentsen then toured the hangar where several planes were in
various stages of restoration. Mounted on the wall were the sides
of old bombers carefully cut to preserve the cheesecake art work
that graced their flanks.
   Pin-up girls in various stages of undress had titles such as
``Night Mission,''``Surprise Attack'' and ``Target for Tonight.''
Asked what was on the side of his plane, Bentsen replied that he
was a squadron leader and often changed planes. ``One of them was
`Double Trouble.' Others I don't want to name,'' he chuckled.
   Bentsen strolled across the hangar to where the display
continued. And it stopped him dead in his tracks.
   There it was, right near ``Night Mission.''
   ``Double Trouble'' is a painting of twin nude, buxom women in a
swan-dive from the sky, their heads and shoulders back and
propellers spinning from their thrust-out chests.
   ``Well, I'll be damned,'' he said.
   Could it be from the same plane that Bentsen flew more than 43
years ago?
   ``It looks familiar,'' he said sheepishly.
   Later on his campaign plane, Bentsen said he couldn't be sure it
was the same one, but he was glad his wife, B.A., was campaigning
elsewhere at the time.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>___</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   Studying the crowds at political events isn't a very scientific
measure of how a candidate is doing. But it's a lot more
entertaining than political polls.
   Sometimes the reaction is more news than the candidate _ such as
when Bentsen was booed by the Veterans of Foreign Wars when he
mentioned the name of his running mate, Democratic presidential
nominee Michael Dukakis.
   Other times on the Bentsen campaign, the heckling and protest
signs seem less ominous and can be downright funny.
   ``Who the Hayle is Quayle?'' protested a placard-waving Iowan
when Bentsen spoke in Amana last week.
   Students at Virginia Tech from both sides of the political
spectrum came to hear him speak. It was hard to tell the fans from
the foes.
   ``Bimbo and Lloyd _ Go for the Gold,'' as one sign read, seemed
to imply indiscretions. But it was a compliment _ ``Bimbo'' being a
Virginia Tech star athlete on his way to the Olympics.
   ``Lloyd _ Dude,'' was a favorite of young Democrats while
``Avoid the Lloyd'' was brandished by the GOP troops. ``Political
Science Club Welcomes Sen. Bentsen'' was a sign that upheld
tradition.
   The audience at a rally near Detroit repeatedly called for
Bentsen to kiss his wife, B.A., while they snapped pictures. The
courtly Texan obliged, but Mrs. Bentsen confided later: ``He just
wanted to run from the room.''
   In the middle of a speech in San Diego, Bentsen was giving his
stock stump speech attacking President Reagan's veto of the trade
bill.
   ``And do you know why he vetoed that bill?'' he asked
rhetorically, pausing.
   ``Because he's a bum,'' shouted someone in the crowd.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
