<1ST_LINE>r a PM-Quayle-Guard CORRECTIVE   09-15 0193</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Quayle-Guard, CORRECTIVE,0194</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>Eds: Members who used a0681, Quayle-Guard 6th Ld; a0689,
Convention Roundup 5th Ld, both under New Orleans datelines, or
a0684, Quayle-Commander, Indianapolis dateline, all moved on August
18, are asked to use the following story:</NOTE>
<DATELINE>INDIANAPOLIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Wendell C. Phillippi, a retired major
general in the Indiana National Guard, has stated that he made one
telephone call to one person in behalf of the 1969 enlistment of
Sen. Dan Quayle, now the Republican nominee for vice president.
   The Associated Press reported on Aug. 18 that Phillippi had made
multiple calls in connection with Quayle's effort to join the
Guard. The Indianapolis News carried a story on Aug. 18 reporting
that Phillippi said he had called on his multitude of friends in
the Guard when Quayle sought enlistment.
   Later AP stories on Aug. 18 quoted Phillippi as saying that he
made only one call.
   In 1969, Phillippi was managing editor of The Indianapolis News.
The late Eugene C. Pulliam, Quayle's grandfather, was publisher of
the News. Phillippi had been commanding general of the 38th
Division, Indiana National Guard. He had retired from the Guard
prior to the Quayle enlistment.
