<1ST_LINE>r p PM-AdvantageBush     09-15 0765</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Advantage Bush,750</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Polls: Advantage Bush, But Beware The Uncertain Electorate</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Political Rdp Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GARY LANGER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Polls inaugurating the fall presidential race
give the early advantage to George Bush, indicating he has seized
the agenda in the campaign's final stretch. But his lead, pollsters
warn, is tenuous.
   Surveys this week found Bush delineating key issues and boxing
Michael Dukakis into a defensive corner. Some put the race at a
tie; two polls found an eight-point Bush lead. On the issues,
analysts said, Bush was stronger.
   ``Bush has control of the agenda and he is setting the tone of
the campaign, at least for now,'' Kathleen A. Frankovic, pollster
for CBS News, said Wednesday. ``His attacks are hurting Dukakis.''
   But Frankovic and others said the very factors that allowed Bush
to turn the tables on Dukakis make his current lead precarious:
Voters' choices remain unusually tentative, making rapid changes
possible.
   ``It's all very volatile. It's still to be won or lost,'' said
Humphrey Taylor, president of Louis Harris & Associates. ``Even if
Bush was to go 10 or 12 points ahead, it would not mean he is
certain to win by any means.''
   Taylor cited two chief reasons: Voters are less tightly
constrained by party loyalty than ever before, and neither Bush nor
Dukakis has engendered either strong attachments or strong
antipathy.
   One measure was a Gallup poll this week that found just 38
percent of the voters with a strong preference for either
candidate. At this time in 1984, by contrast, 49 percent had strong
feelings for the nominees.
   And in this week's CBS News-New York Times poll, ``almost 40
percent of the voters are undecided or say their minds could still
change,'' Frankovic said. ``That's a lot of people.''
   Although Bush led Dukakis by eight points in the CBS-Times and
Gallup polls, the share of voters saying they strongly supported
the Republican was down in Gallup's survey, from 27 percent last
month to 21 percent now.
   ``He has widened the gap, but he has widened the gap with soft
support,'' said Larry Hugick, political pollster for the Gallup
Organization. ``So even though he has a wider lead over Dukakis, he
hasn't built a solid lead.''
   Unsettled opinions can make polls results more sensitive to
differing survey techniques. Los Angeles Times, CNN-USA Today and
Roper Organization polls released this week found statistical dead
heats, and the latest poll, an ABC News-Washington Post survey
conducted Sept. 7 through Tuesday, put the race at 48 percent for
Dukakis to 45 percent for Bush, another dead heat based on a margin
of error of 3 percent.
   More significant than any numerical advantage were gauges
indicating Bush has taken control of campaign issues. He outscored
Dukakis on defense and foreign policy, gained with the Pledge of
Allegiance issue, challenged the Democrat on the environment and
even won on competence, an issue Dukakis had sought to make his own.
   ``What we see in these latest surveys is a consequence of
relatively extensive campaigning by Bush ... and therefore more
press coverage,'' said Michael Traugott, another Gallup pollster.
``He has had success in elevating his visibility and in also
structuring the agenda discussed in the media.''
   Bush's approach in some cases has reached beyond the media to
the voters. An example is his criticism of Dukakis for vetoing a
bill requiring teachers to lead pupils in the Pledge. Three in 10
voters in the Gallup poll said they liked Dukakis less for his
handling of the issue, and the CBS-Times poll also found support
for Bush's position.
   Bush also showed gains with his ideological assault on Dukakis:
Only 15 percent in the CBS-Times poll called themselves liberals,
the lowest share in more than a decade, while 37 percent called
Dukakis a liberal.
   The Gallup poll found that Bush's support was based more on
policy agreement and less on party loyalty than was Dukakis',
another sign that Bush's message has worked to greater effect. And
the polls gave Dukakis his highest unfavorable ratings of the
campaign.
   Although the surveys indicated a reversal of fortunes for
Dukakis, who led by as many as 18 points less than two months ago,
pollsters stressed that the race could swing again _ either on
tactical moves or on events such as the debates scheduled for next
month.
   ``Bush has the edge, but there is plenty of volatility here,''
said Hugick, the Gallup pollster. ``Until we see a firming up of
the vote, we have to be very cautious about reading too much into
that lead.''
</TEXT>
