<FILEID>AP-NR-09-15-88 0021EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u i PM-Pope-Odyssey Bjt   09-15 0725</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Pope-Odyssey, Bjt,0747</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Pope's Day Brings Unscheduled Adventures</HEAD>
<HEAD>An AP Extra</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DENNIS REDMONT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MASERU, Lesotho (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Thanks to a rainstorm, two broken radio
beacons and a pilot who didn't want to take chances, Pope John Paul
II got a glimpse of the one country he was trying to avoid during
his tour of southern Africa.
   In his next unplanned adventure Wednesday, the 68-year-old
pontiff was escorted by soldiers and police on an improvised
270-mile drive from South Africa to Lesotho, where a bus hostage
drama was unfolding at the site of the high point of his pilgrimage.
   The pope's strange odyssey began 75 minutes after takeoff from
Gaborone, Botswana, when the Air Zimbabwe Boeing 707 taking him to
tiny Lesotho, an enclave surrounded by South Africa, gave up
efforts to land at the airport in Maseru.
   Circling and bumping in clouds so thick they covered the
wingtips, the airliner, carrying reporters and the papal party,
veered west at 7,600 feet over Maseru and climbed back to cruising
altitude.
   ``It's Johannesburg,'' announced Vatican spokesman Joaquin
Navarro, walking to the back of the plane.
   ``In the not too distant future,'' Navarro added jokingly,
making a change in the advance text of a papal speech in which the
pontiff said he was looking forward to visiting South Africa soon.
   In the prepared address, which was to have been delivered
Wednesday afternoon in Lesotho, the pope said he was confident that
``all those in a position of responsibility will continue to
promote a climate that will make such a visit truly fruitful for
all the people of South Africa.''
   The pope is a vocal opponent of South Africa's policies of
apartheid, under which the country's black majority has no say in
national affairs.
   Navarro said the pope, who was reading a book of philosophy when
informed of the flight change, smiled and remarked: ``This was not
on the schedule.''
   After nearly two hours, the plane landed at Jan Smuts Airport
outside Joahnnesburg, and Capt. Robin Cartwright, a Zimbabwean,
provided an explanation over the loudspeaker.
   Cartwright said he found out after takeoff that the two radio
beacons at Maseru airport were out of order. Any descent without
instrument assistance to the airport, situated in a bowl surrounded
by mountains of 3,000-4,000 feet, would have been perilous, he said.
   The pilot had told reporters the night before that he had never
landed at Maseru.
   Cartwright said he first considered Maputo, the capital of
Mozambique, which the pope will visit Friday, as well as Manzini,
in Swaziland, but both were also plagued by bad weather.
   The Gaborone airport was reporting worsening weather, and the
only airport with safe landing facilities nearby, as the fuel level
was dropping, was Johannesburg, he said.
   In the meantime, South African officials, who in August had
unsuccessfully suggested the pope celebrate a Mass during a
``technical stopover'' at Jan Smuts midway through the five-nation
trip, quickly moved into action.
   Security forces with telescopic rifles and machine guns
surrounded the Boeing 707. Foreign Minister Pik Botha rushed from
Pretoria to the plane for a formal greeting and a tea-sipping
briefing with the pope in the VIP lounge to discuss the evolving
hijack drama in Lesotho.
   In a noticeable departure from custom, John Paul did not kiss
the ground in Johannesburg, and he made no public statements there.
   After less than three hours in Johannesburg, authorities had
rounded up a dark bullet-proof limousine, three buses and six
white-and-orange traffic police cars with flashing lights and
sirens for the 270-mile drive to Lesotho.
   Helicopters whirred over the convoy while roads and highways
were sealed off by soldiers or police along the way in an
astonishing display of military organization as the convoy first
skirted the skyscrapers of Johannesburg, then sped through the
prairies of the Orange Free State.
   After dark, the convoy crossed a narrow bridge over the Caledeon
River into Lesotho, and John Paul was greeted by hundreds of people
wrapped in traditional multicolored blankets, ululating in
high-pitched shrieks of welcome.
   The pope arrived in Maseru just 20 minutes before police stormed
a bus loaded with nuns and other pilgrims that had been hijacked by
gunmen who demanded to meet John Paul and Lesotho's king.
   Authorities said three hijackers and a hostage were killed in
the action, which ended a two-day hostage crisis.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
