<1ST_LINE>r a AM-SlumlordCapture     09-15 0280</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Slumlord Capture,0287</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Slumlord Arrested In New Jersey</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Fugitive slumlord Vijaynand Sharma was
arrested in New Jersey on Wednesday after he fled to avoid fines
and a jail term for 112 counts of health, building and safety code
violations at his tenements, officials said.
   Sharma, 42, of Inglewood, was arrested by FBI agents in Cherry
Hill, N.J., said Los Angeles FBI special agent Jim Neilson.
   The notorious slumlord, whose tenants complained of vermin
infestation, faulty plumbing, exposed electrical wiring and
inoperable fire hoses, waived extradition and is expected to be
returned to Los Angeles as soon as possible, said Deputy City
Attorney Stephanie Sautner.
   Sharma was charged with unlawful flight to avoid prosecution on
Feb. 1 and U.S. Magistrate Volney Brown in Los Angeles issued a
federal fugitive warrant.
   He was also sought for failure to appear for sentencing and a
probation violation in connection with a December 1987 fire at one
of his buildings. He violated parole when he failed to fix fire
safety equipment.
   The warrants carried a total of $2.9 million bail.
   Ms. Sautner said Sharma faces a jail term of nearly two years on
current charges. City Attorney James Hahn said Sharma faces
prosecution in eight other slum cases.
   Sharma has lived in the United States for the past two decades.
He was convicted Nov. 19, 1987 on a 112-count conviction in what
was called the city's biggest prosecution on slum conditions.
   He disappeared some time after Dec. 21, 1987 when he was freed
on bail so he could appeal a 90-day jail term imposed in one of
several cases of violations at his 18 dilapidated apartment
buildings and residential hotels.
</TEXT>
