<FILEID>AP-NR-09-15-88 0152EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w PM-RioGrandePollution     09-15 0330</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Rio Grande Pollution,330</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Legislation To Clean Up Rio Grande One Step Away From
Congressional Passage</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JENNIFER DIXON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The sponsor of legislation authorizing the
United States to negotiate with Mexico over cleaning up the Rio
Grande says he's optimistic the Mexican government will support
stopping the large-scale dumping of raw sewage.
   The bill cleared the Senate Foreign Relations Committee on
Wednesday. If passed by the full Senate without amendment it would
go to President Reagan for his signature.
   Rep. E. ``Kika'' de la Garza, D-Texas, author of the bill _
which passed the House last fall _ said he met with officials in
Mexico a week ago and they assured him of their cooperation.
   His counterparts in Mexico ``expressed an interest and will be
recommending positive action on an agreement to both the incoming
and outgoing presidents. As soon as passage, I hope within 60 days
to have ready for presentation (a cleanup proposal) to the
president of Mexico. Hopefully Nuevo Laredo will be the first
project,'' de la Garza said.
   Under the bill, the State Department, acting through the head of
the U.S. International Boundary Water Commission, would negotiate
with Mexican officials to find ways to clean up the Rio Grande and
make recommendations on building treatment facilities.
   Sen. Lloyd Bentsen, D-Texas, said 25 million gallons of raw
sewage is dumped daily into the Rio Grande at Nuevo Laredo, across
the border from Laredo, Texas.
   ``The large volume of raw sewage, garbage and industrial wastes
routinely dumped into the river has so polluted the Rio Grande that
it will take unusual and substantial efforts to sanitize it,''
Bentsen said in a statement.
   ``The most distressing problem is that every day, at several
points along the border, tens of millions of gallons of raw,
untreated sewage is dumped into the river,'' Bentsen said.
   Sen. Phil Gramm, R-Texas, called the bill ``a solid first step''
although he had sought a more comprehensive approach.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880915-0026 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-09-15-88 0156EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w PM-FBI-CISPES     09-15 0572</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-FBI-CISPES,560</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Sessions Pledges Tougher Controls On Terrorism Probes</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PETE YOST</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   FBI Director William Sessions says top bureau
officials will face disciplinary action if there are more abuses of
the kinds that occurred in a terrorism probe of opponents of the
Reagan administration's Central American policy.
   Sessions disciplined six lower- and mid-level bureau personnel
Wednesday. But he told the Senate Intelligence Committee that
``under the procedures that were ... in place at the time,''
higher-level officials ``had no reasonable way to know'' the bureau
was collecting information on administration opponents whose
activities had nothing to do with terrorism.
   During the probe of the Committee in Solidarity with the People
of El Salvador, ``there was no requirement that higher level
officials be advised when certain investigative activities ... were
being used,'' said Sessions.
   He said the activities include surveillances at public rallies
and attendance at meetings.
   In the future, he said, higher-level officials will be required
to determine whether a particular investigation merits the use of
techniques that have the potential for infringing on constitutional
rights.
   Sources familiar with the action by Sessions identified five of
those being disciplined as Gary Penrith, deputy assistant director
of the FBI's intelligence division and former assistant special
agent in charge of the Dallas FBI office; Stanley Klein, special
agent in charge of the New Haven, Conn., office and former head of
the terrorism section at FBI headquarters; George Van Balen, chief
of the international terrorism-global unit at FBI headquarters in
Washington; Ronald Davenport, a supervisory special agent in the
Washington headquarters; and Parks Stearns, a supervisory special
agent in Dallas. Another supervisory agent in Washington also was
disciplined.
   Sessions said that under revamped procedures, in the future ``I
would think'' high-level personnel would face discipline if similar
problems arise.
   The investigation of allegations that leaders of a group in the
United States were supporting terrorism in Central America was
unnecessarily broadened in October 1983 to encompass all 180
chapters of the Committee in Solidarity with the People of El
Salvador, Sessions testified.
   He said there were 178 spin-off investigations from the CISPES
probe focusing on nine other groups and 169 people. The CISPES
investigation and spin-off probes ended in June 1985, a year after
the bureau concluded that its main informant in the case, Frank
Varelli, was unreliable.
   ``The CISPES investigation was an aberration ... an unfortunate
aligning of mistakes in judgment at several levels that
cumulatively led to an investigation of which the FBI is not
proud,'' Sessions said.
   ``There was no reason to believe that all CISPES members
nationwide knew of or had any involvement in support of El
Salvadoran or U.S. terrorists,'' testified Sessions. The decision
to widen the investigation ``was made at a comparatively low level
and ... supervisory personnel at FBI headquarters who should have
reviewed and analyzed this decision and appreciated its
significance failed to do so.''
   He called for a redrafting of the attorney general's guidelines
on international terrorism investigations, which he said don't
describe the extent to which leaders and rank-and-file members of
groups in the United States may be investigated.
   He said that in the CISPES probe ``the most critical area
requiring attention was how to conduct investigation of groups
where legitimate First Amendment activities were being undertaken
by the rank-and-file members.''
   Sessions instructed additional training for agents on how to
deal with activities protected by the First Amendment.
</TEXT>
