<1ST_LINE>r a AM-Weapons-Indictment     09-15 0240</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Weapons-Indictment,0249</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Army Officer Charged With Theft of 201 Guns</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NASHVILLE, Tenn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An Army officer formerly responsible for
procuring guns for his unit was charged Wednesday with stealing 201
rifles, shotguns and handguns, according to a federal indictment
men.
   Maj. Michael Lynn Smith, 42, stole weapons worth $60,000 between
1981 and 1983, apparently for his gun collection, said U.S.
Attorney Joe Brown.
   The weapons include .44 Magnum revolvers, .22-caliber rifles,
9-millimeter pistols, 20-gauge shotguns, Remington bolt-action
rifles and various rifles with scopes, Brown said.
   Smith is chief of the family support division at Fort Campbell,
on the Kentucky border near Clarksville.
   He faces up to 20 years in prison if convicted on the five-count
indictment handed down by a federal grand jury.
   The indictment accuses Smith of stealing the guns during his
1981-84 tour of duty as an adjutant to the Intelligence Support
Activity, a Virginia military support unit.
   Smith allegedly made out false vouchers for the money spent on
firearms and kept those not delivered to the unit. Brown said the
statute of limitations has run out on charging Smith with
submitting false documents.
   Brown said Smith agreed to report to U.S. marshals in Nashville
this week.
   The charges against Smith include interstate transportation of
stolen goods, because he allegedly took 201 weapons with him when
he was transferred to Fort Campbell in 1986.
   He also faces charges of possessing a silencer and retaining
stolen goods.
</TEXT>
