<2ND_LINE>PM-Lites,0368</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>On The Light Side</HEAD>
<DATELINE>COOKEVILLE, Tenn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Mary Mills mailed in a cashier's check
to pay an $85 speeding ticket, but it was made out for a tad too
much.
   Like $1,000,085.
   When the Morristown woman bought the check from the Third
National Bank of Morristown, she apparently didn't notice that it
read ``1000085 and 00 cents.''
   ``I called the bank and asked them if they wanted me to send
that check back to them,'' Putnam County Circuit Court Clerk Lewis
Coomer said Tuesday. ``And the woman I talked to said yes they
certainly did. And she also said, `And if you decide you're going
out of town, stop and get us.'''
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>JACKSON, Miss. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Steak and potatoes is one of America's
most popular meals, but you wouldn't think so from the recipes of
the 62 top cooks in the 15th-annual National Beef Cookoff.
   ``No one is using potatoes, which is strange because meat and
potatoes are supposed to go together,'' said Sarah Lynn Quinn, who
is in charge of obtaining ingredients for next week's contest.
   ``We're buying plenty of tomatoes, though, and alfalfa sprouts,
dill pickles, avocados and every kind of lettuce you can imagine,''
she said Wednesday. ``We're buying about 10 to 15 pounds of
onions.''
   The contest runs Monday through Thursday, and the public is
invited to watch the cooks in action Thursday. A $5,000 award will
go to the first-place winner in each of three categories _
conventional, barbecue and microwave _ with a $10,000 bonus for the
best overall recipe.
   Last year's overall winner was Patricia Yee of California, who
won for her warm beef and black-eye pea salad.
   The contest is sponsored by several beef industry groups to
promote the use of beef.
   Quinn said she has been kept busy chasing down sometimes
frustrating ingredient demands by the competitors.
   ``One contestant wants orange chrysanthemums,'' she said. ``We
thought it was a flower. We found every color, but we couldn't find
orange ones. It turns out it's a garnish you make out of an orange.
We had the grocery store man looking everywhere.''
</TEXT>
