<FILEID>AP-NR-09-15-88 0217EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-Hurricane-Frank     09-15 0527</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Hurricane-Frank,0542</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Neil Frank Still The Eye Of the Storm, But From TV Station</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Hurricane Gilbert, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MICHAEL L. GRACZYK</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>HOUSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Neil Frank, one of the nation's best known
hurricane experts, is getting his first in-person taste of a big
Atlantic storm as powerful Hurricane Gilbert neared Texas.
   But instead of his nearly constant appearances on all the
television networks from the National Hurricane Center in Coral
Cables, Fla., Frank is delivering his storm forecasts from the
studios of Houston television station KHOU.
   ``I'm not going to compete with them,'' he said Wednesday of his
former colleagues at the Hurricane Center. ``Not with all the
resources they have. It's a different operation. We're a
communication operation. They're a research operation.''
   Frank, whose distinctive flat-top haircut and exuberant sharp
voice made him familiar to millions of people along the Atlantic
and Gulf coasts, left the Hurricane Center about a year ago after
25 years in Florida and moved to Houston television.
   Although Frank is left with only several monitors, a computer
screen and a wall full of weather charts, he doesn't see his
absence from the Florida headquarters as an intense disadvantage.
   ``I can second-guess most of what they're doing and thinking,''
he said of the Hurricane Center. That comes from 25 years of
experience. I know what they're looking at, but I don't see all the
details and the models they're looking at.''
   Frank said he can still show viewers dramatic satellite views of
Gilbert and put the storm in motion.
   ``But when you come to forecasting, we're not doing a lot better
than when I went to the Hurricane Center 25 years ago,'' he said.
``It's fairly easy to communicate. But forecasting is a whole other
dilemma.''
   Ironically, if the eye of Hurricane Gilbert came ashore at
Houston and Galveston, it would be the first time Frank has been in
the middle of an Atlantic hurricane. While a forecaster in the Air
Force and stationed on Okinawa, he went through three Pacific
typhoons in 1956-57. But while in Florida, he never took a direct
hit.
   He remembers the first typhoon because he jumped in his car at
the end of his shift to go home.
   ``The first thing that happened, I turned on my windshield
wipers and they blew off,'' he said, laughing.
   Despite his new job, Frank remains in demand for his expertise.
His first commitment, however, is the station, then the CBS
network, of which KHOU is an affiliate.
   ``If we can satisfy other commitments, then we're doing so,'' he
said.
   Nevertheless, the station has received scores of calls asking
for Frank's thoughts on Gilbert, which he calls the worst storm
he's ever seen. The calls are so incessant, the news department's
executive producer is acting as Frank's agent during the storm so
he can do his work.
   And where does Frank think Gilbert is going?
   ``If you want to bet, I'd bet the hurricane doesn't come over
our head,'' he said from Houston. ``The thing that makes me most
concerned is that people would want and really need more accurate
information than we can provide.''
</TEXT>
