<2ND_LINE>PM-Presidential Debates,340</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Second Presidential Debate in LA, Veep Face-off in Omaha</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ANNAPOLIS, Md. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Los Angeles will host the second debate
between Michael Dukakis and George Bush, and the vice presidential
candidates will hold their only debate Oct. 5 in Omaha, Dukakis
campaign officials said.
   The Los Angeles debate will be held Oct. 13 or Oct. 14,
depending on the major league baseball playoffs. A debate Sept. 25
in Winston-Salem, N.C., had previously been announced.
   The Dukakis officials also provided previously unresolved
details Wednesday on the format of the debates:
   _The 90-minute debates will include questioning by a moderator
and three panelists. There will be two minutes for answering each
question a candidate is asked, and one minute for the opponent to
add his opinion.
   _Each candidate will have two minutes for closing statements.
   _The candidates will be standing, as the Dukakis campaign had
wanted.
   Nebraska Gov. Kay Orr said the Bush campaign had informed her
that Omaha would host the vice presidential debate.
   One of the debates had originally been scheduled for Wednesday
night in Annapolis, the Maryland capital, and the Democratic
nominee taunted Bush for refusing to agree to a debate then.
   Bush officials had sought to limit the number of debates, even
though the Annapolis encounter had been scheduled by a bipartisan
commission.
   ``If George Bush isn't ready today after more than seven and a
half years as vice president of this country, how can we expect him
to be ready on January 20, 1989?'' Dukakis asked. ``Lloyd Bentsen
and I are ready.''
   Bush, in Fresno, Calif., said ``I'm looking forward to it.''
   He said he hopes to ``keep talking about what the issues are,
trying to pin him down, find out where he is today and keep telling
what positive message about where this country is going and where I
want to lead.''
   ``That's the big thing,'' he said.
   Bentsen said debating Quayle would give both an opportunity ``to
compare our records of experience and accomplishment in the U.S.
Senate.''
</TEXT>
