<FILEID>AP-NR-09-15-88 0225EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i PM-OlympicFriendliness     09-15 0495</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Olympic Friendliness,0514</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Foreign Visitors Spawn New Olympic Fad</HEAD>
<HEAD>An AP EXTRA</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KELLY TUNNEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SEOUL, South Korea (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A new species has surfaced recently in
South Korea: the Olympic visitor. Regardless of its size, color or
demeanor, it has evoked a new fad among South Koreans: Olympic
friendliness.
   ``Welcome to Korea'' says a young man at a bus stop.
   ``Can I help you?'' asks a businessman on his way to work.
   ``Thank you for coming to Korea,'' says a restaurant owner.
   Schoolgirls on the subway giggle and one says ``Where you
from.'' A reply elicts excited conversation in Korean.
   A man on the subway, peeking over the shoulder of a foreigner
writing a Korean name, points to the word and says ``Put in letter
`k.''' The man smiles, pleased with his contribution. ``Welcome to
Korea,'' he says.
   ``Excuse me'' says a smiling policeman, asking a foreigner to
stop for traffic.
   As recently as a few weeks ago, such happenings would have been
unusual. Never, it seems, have so many South Koreas smiled so often
at foreigners and said ``Welcome to Korea.''
   South Koreans are usually reluctant to speak to strangers and
foreigners, and by upbringing they shy away from initiating
conversation without proper introductions.
   ``In anonymous public situations, other people are treated as
though they simply do not exist,'' writes local columnist Edward W.
Poitras. Chong, the word for warm emotion, is reserved for those
one knows, not strangers.
   To speak to a foreigner _ not to mention in a language in which
one might not be proficient _ takes enormous effort. But as members
of an authoritarian society, South Koreans are quick to follow
direction.
   They have been told over and over again that hosting the Olympic
Games, which begin Saturday, is the country's most important
achievement and that it's urgent that all citizens cooperate in
making Olympic visitors feel at home.
   In recent weeks the government, Olympic organizers, radio and
television announcers and local neighborhood associations have
stepped up efforts to urge citizens to initiate contact with
foreign visitors.
   ``We are reminded that foreigners think it's okay to speak
first,'' said a student. ``We are reminded that foreigners like to
hear `Welcome to Korea.' ''
   A spokeswoman for the Korean Broadcasting Company says that
although there are no special programs on being kind to foreigners
many of the announcers on Olympic television and radio programs
urge citizens to exude friendliness.
   ``Announcers are encouraging people to be more positive about
foreigners,'' says Lee Jung-won of KBS. ``They don't want to push
the public because that might have a negative reaction. It's more
like a suggestion.''
   The rival MBC network has broadcast English language lessons
since last January. Listeners are reminded that even a few words
makes foreign visitors feel welcome.
   Kim Seung-ho, a spokesman for the Seoul Olympic organizers said
there had been no program training people to be friendly. But he
says there has been ``encouragement, indirectly.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880915-0040 </DOCNO>
