<1ST_LINE>r a BC-Philharmonic     09-15 0382</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Philharmonic,0396</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Stern Plays with NY Philharmonic for 100th Time</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDs: No PMs Planned</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By MARY CAMPBELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Violinist Isaac Stern was guest soloist with the
New York Philharmonic for the 100th time on the night the
Philharmonic opened its 1988-89 season in Avery Fisher Hall.
   But Wednesday's concert concentrated on fine music and didn't
allow that milestone _ or the audience dressed for a party
afterwards _ to turn the evening into a mere event.
   Stern played Beethoven's ``Concerto for Violin and Orchestra.''
As that music speaks to a listener's soul, it is obvious once again
why Beethoven's music has endured and is so often played.
   Stern was hitting each tone right in its center. His entrance in
the piece was high and pure and later solo parts held pure, sweet
pianissimo. The New York Philharmonic audience, even those who pay
gala benefit prices and may not often attend again during the
regular concert season, knows that the etiquette is not to clap
between movements. However, the audience roundly applauded Stern
after the first movement.
   As the music went on, Stern played a firm, though delicate in
volume, thread of sound. And he made his pianissimo silver notes
sound warm.
   The orchestra, which returned last weekend from playing 16
sold-out concerts in 13 cities in 11 European countries, sounded
fresh on the season's opening night. After last season ended, the
Philharmonic played in Russia. Mrs. Neal Gilliatt, chairman of the
opening-night gala, conceived the banquet and dance afterwards as a
welcome home for the musicians and music director Zubin Mehta.
Decor in the party tent was meant to evoke Central Park, with
twinkling lights in trees.
   Mehta opened the program with Schubert's ``Rosamunde Overture.''
This overture begins with broad strokes, of which Mehta took full
advantage, and later sings with gaity. The orchestra played with
eagerness and clarity throughout.
   After intermission, the orchestra played orchestral music from
Wagner's ``Gotterdammerung.'' This was very grand and emotional,
fitting the opera. Applause was lavish and Mehta conducted an
encore, ``The Ride of the Walkures'' from Wagner's ``Die Walkure.''
Although this music makes an opera goer want to hear a Wagnerian
soprano sing with it, the concert ended on an exuberant mood,
upbeat for the season to come.
 
</TEXT>
