Africa as a ``terrorist state'' in its platform, but he would not
utter those words as he stood on the porch of the embassy.
   Instead, he spoke of hopeful signs in South Africa's foreign and
domestic policies.
   ``In the last few weeks some things have happened that are in
the right direction, and they must be encouraged,'' said Jackson,
adding that he was encouraged by South Africa's decision to
withdraw from Angola and by the elections in Namibia.
   ``But of course, the heart of the matter remains: Apartheid must
end,'' he said.
   Koornhof said after the meeting, ``I hope that the conciliatory
note that you have noticed here today will not be lost on the
American people, neither on the South African people.''
   Before his meeting at the South African Embassy, Jackson told a
meeting of black owners of radio and television stations to back
drives to register more black and Hispanic voters.
   ``You rise as the power rises,'' Jackson said. ``Who else but
you has the interest or the capacity to create voter fever?''
