<1ST_LINE>r a PM-YoungWife     09-15 0285</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Young Wife,0293</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Previously Barred, Wife Can Now Live With Husband 60 Days Per Year</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MONROE, N.J. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A 46-year-old woman barred from living in a
retirement community with her husband can now be ``a guest in her
own home,'' but only for 60 days a year, according to a court
settlement.
   An agreement signed by Middlesex County Superior Court Judge
John E. Bachman allows Mary Ann Romer to be treated as an owner and
non-resident of the Rossmoor condominium association.
   The agreement allows Mrs. Romer to buy property with her
60-year-old husband, Theodore, but restricts her from living with
him for more than 60 days a year until she reaches the community's
minimum residency age of 48, said her attorney, Samuel H. Davis.
   ``She is entitled to all the rights and privileges of any person
who is not a resident,'' Davis said Wednesday.
   Leonard J. Coates, an attorney for the association, said the
settlement means ``she can be a guest in her own home.''
   The dispute began in November when the Romers decided to buy a
unit at the 3,500-resident complex.
   Mrs. Romer was denied membership because of her age. Her
husband, who is semi-retired, was denied membership because he was
married to a woman younger than 48, Coates said.
   Coates said the couple bought the unit anyway, leading the
association to sue them charging that the purchase violated its
rules. A township ordinance mandates that residents of retirement
communities be 48 years of age or older, Coates said.
   The Romers will use the apartment on weekends since they
maintain a permanent residence in New York City, Davis said.
``They've made many friends over there and they enjoy the place,''
he said.
</TEXT>
