<FILEID>AP-NR-09-15-88 0230EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w PM-Food-Africa     09-15 0505</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Food-Africa,500</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Technology Called Key To Solving Africa's Farm Ills</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DON KENDALL</BYLINE>
<HEAD>AP Farm Writer</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The solution to Africa's vast and complex food
problems will require the heavy use of farming technologies adapted
to local methods, says the Office of Technology Assessment, a
non-partisan research agency of Congress.
   Existing ways of farming, which can vary greatly across the
continent, should be made more productive, the OTA said Wednesday.
It is this ``low-resource agriculture'' that offers the best hope
of producing enough food to keep pace with a growing population.
   The agency said in its report to Congress that ``building on
existing low-resource systems used in African farming, herding and
fishing'' would work better than trying to replace those methods.
   ``African agriculture faces a major challenge in the next few
decades,'' the report said. ``It will need to double production to
keep pace with a growing population and provide an adequate source
of household income to purchase additional food.''
   The report said it is uncertain whether technology exists to fit
Africa's food problems and whether it can transform low-resource
agriculture. But the report said it is clear ``some technologies
and practices do exist'' and could be used to improve African
agriculture.
   The study was requested by a number of Senate and House
committees involved in hunger, science and agriculture. The report
concentrated on that part of Africa south of the Sahara Desert, a
region where food and population problems are most acute.
   Rep. Mickey Leland, D-Texas, chairman of the House Select
Committee on Hunger, said the OTA report was ``a clear and sharp
picture of the importance of low-resource agriculture in
Sub-Saharan Africa and the vital necessity of directly assisting
the poor African farmer in increasing crop production'' to combat
chronic hunger.
   Sen. Claiborne Pell, D-R.I., said the study shows that ``the
lesson of the 1980s is that we can no longer afford the trade-off
between short-term agricultural production increases and long-term
ecological degradation.'' New methods of agricultural development
are needed if Africa is to achieve ``a modicum of self-sufficiency
in its food systems,'' he said.
   The OTA report said African agriculture, for the most part, has
effectively adapted to meet changing conditions. But never has the
pressure been so great.
   ``Paramount is the pressure created by rapidly growing
populations and the consequent demands on the land,'' the report
said. ``The African continent has the most rapidly growing
population in the world _ 2.9 percent per year in 1988. Even if
this rate slows slightly as expected, the continent will have
triple its current population to feed within just 40 years.''
   With intensified land use, erosion, deforestation and other
abuses, yields have declined, the report said. Per capita food
production and income, along with nutritional levels, are dropping
in most areas.
   ``From the late 1960s to the late 1970s, Africa changed from a
net exporter of staple foods to a net importer,'' the report said.
``In 1986, the value of exports in 22 countries was not sufficient
to pay for imports.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880915-0044 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-09-15-88 0230EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-BingeEaters     09-15 0302</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Binge Eaters,0309</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Binge Eaters May Have Defect in Hormone Controlling Appetite</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Abnormally low amounts of a hormone that controls
appetite may play a role in bulimia, the cycles of binge eating and
purging suffered by some young women, a study published today
concludes.
   The preliminary report found that some people with the disorder
make unusually small amounts of cholecystokinin, a hormone produced
by the intestines that makes people feel full, or sated, after a
meal.
   ``We conclude that patients with bulimia do not have normal
satiety and have impaired secretion of cholecystokinin in response
to a meal,'' the researchers wrote in the New England Journal of
Medicine.
   Between 1 percent and 4 percent of young adult American women
and a much smaller number of men are believed to have the disorder.
Victims tend to eat large quantities of food, then purposely purge
themselves with vomiting or laxatives.
   Other studies have shown that anti-depression medicine is an
effective way to curb binge eating, and the latest research found
that the drugs also seem to increase levels of the appetite hormone
after a meal.
   However, the researchers cautioned that further study will be
necessary to see if correcting the apparent hormonal abnormality is
important in controlling bulimia.
   The study by Drs. Thomas D. Geracioti Jr. of the National
Institute of Mental Health and Rodger A. Liddle of the University
of California, San Francisco, compared the hormone levels after
eating in 14 women with bulimia to 10 healthy volunteers.
   In an accompanying editorial, Drs. David B. Herzog and Paul M.
Copeland of Massachusetts General Hospital cautioned that it is
premature to conclude that low hormone levels make people
susceptible to binge eating.
   But they added, ``Investigating bulimia nervosa from the
perspective of defective satiety offers a promising avenue of
research.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
