<DOCNO> AP880915-0045 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-09-15-88 0232EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-Laser-Fusion     09-15 0314</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Laser-Fusion,0323</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Lasers Squeeze Nuclear Fuel to Record Density, Gain for Fusion
Power</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MALCOLM RITTER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Science Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Scientists reported today they have compressed
nuclear fuel to record densities by bombarding it with two dozen
laser beams, a step in developing a new kind of nuclear power
technology.
   But still higher densities will be needed to trigger a nuclear
reaction called fusion, the process that powers the Sun,
researchers wrote in the British journal Nature.
   Fusion releases energy as the nucleus, or core, of one hydrogen
atom fuses with another. Today's nuclear plants use another
reaction, fission, in which uranium atoms are split to release the
energy that holds them together.
   The new experiments focused on an approach to fusion called
inertial confinement.
   Researchers used glass pellets only two to three times the width
of a human hair. The pellets contained the nuclear fuel, a frozen
mix of two forms of hydrogen called deuterium and tritium.
   Each pellet was bombarded by 24 laser beams. The energy heated
the skin of the pellets, causing part of it to blow off. That
provided a rocket-like thrust toward the center of the pellet from
all sides, squeezing the fuel to the high densities.
   The fuel reached average densities of 100 to 200 times that of
its liquid state, said Robert McCrory of the University of
Rochester, who reported the results with Rochester colleagues.
   To achieve fusion, researchers will have to produce densities
approaching 1,000 times that of the liquid state, the scientists
wrote. In a telephone interview, McCrory said an average of 500
times typically would be enough because portions of the pellet
probably would reach the higher mark.
   Robert Kauffman, a physicist at the Lawrence Livermore National
Laboratory in Livermore, Calif., called the report ``another step
on the way to scientifically demonstrating the feasibility'' and
potential of inertial confinement fusion.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880915-0046 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-09-15-88 0224EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-Names     09-15 0961</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Names,0997</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Names in The News</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto NY14</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Mick Jagger had a ``Peter Pan complex'' and
broke from the Rolling Stones to compete with younger musicians,
but now he's getting no satisfaction from his solo career, says
fellow Stone Keith Richards.
   ``Now he wants to put the Stones back together _ because there's
nowhere else to go,'' said Richards, who's about to release his own
solo effort, ``Talk is Cheap.''
   Richards, in an interview in the Oct. 6 Rolling Stone magazine,
said he never wanted to record without the Stones. But Jagger
thought he had outgrown the group when he turned solo in 1986.
   ``Mick kind of lost touch with the fact of how important the
Stones were for him,'' he said. ``He thought he could just hire
another Rolling Stones. ... And you can't. You can't hire that kind
of thing.''
   Jagger, he said, had a ``Peter Pan complex'' and was determined
to compete with younger musicians for space on the top 10.
   ``He's not living a happy life,'' said Richards. ``To me, that's
unacceptable. I've got to make him happy! To me, I've failed if I
can't eventually get my mate to feel good about himself.''
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>CHIPPEWA FALLS, Wis. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   David Letterman likes his new boots,
and Victor Mason says he had fun delivering them on national
television.
   ``It didn't bother me a bit,'' the Mason Shoe Co. president said
after presenting a pair of size 10{ dress boots, style No. 1197,
before a nationwide TV audience Tuesday on ``Late Night with David
Letterman.''
   ``I was amazed,'' Mason added. ``It was just like I was sitting
in my own living room. I'm a very quiet person, so I thought I
might be getting the jitters.''
   Letterman ordered the boots last month from Edd Hall, a visuals
coordinator for the show who became a Mason salesman through a mail
advertisement.
   The Chippewa Falls company conducts most of its business through
such ads which, Mason said, result in door-to-door sales and sales
to friends and relatives.
   ``Is there any way that from now on in the catalog we can refer
to these as Dave boots?'' Letterman asked as he slipped out of his
athletic shoes and into the new boots.
   ``I think we could, or we could put a star on it for you,''
Mason said.
