<1ST_LINE>r i PM-France-Pilot     09-15 0351</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-France-Pilot,0363</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Air France Fires Pilot Of Jet That Crashed In Air Show</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PARIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Air France says it has fired the pilot of the A320
Airbus jetliner that crashed during an air show in eastern France
in June, killing three passengers as hundreds of people watched.
   Michel Asseline, a senior pilot with Air France for eight years,
was fired Wednesday ``following a particularly grave failure for
which he was held responsible and which made his continued
employment with Air France impossible,'' a company spokesman said.
   The firing followed a recommendation by the Disciplinary Council
of France's Civil Aviation Authority that punitive action be taken
against Asseline and co-pilot Pierre Mazieres, an Air France pilot
for about two months at the time of the crash.
   The Council's action marked the first independent, official
conclusion that blamed the crash on pilot error.
   Air France said it would make a decision on the fate of Mazieres
before the end of the month, the spokesman said. He spoke on
condition of anonymity.
   Transport Minister Michel Delebarre was expected to make a
decision in the next few days on whether to revoke the two pilots'
commercial pilots licenses as recommended by the Council.
   Hundreds of spectators witnessed the accident at the
Mulhouse-Habsheim air show, one of the first domestic
demonstrations of the new plane, which went into service last
spring.
   Although three people died in the crash, 137 passengers and crew
escaped.
   The sophisticated aircraft is controlled by computers rather
than mechanical cables in a system known as ``fly-by-wire.''
   Airbus, the European consortium that manufactures the A320,
invested millions of dollars in its development. It has called the
A320 the fastest-selling plane in aviation history and has received
hundreds of orders from around the world.
   The day after the crash, French transport ministry officials
called a news conference to say the pilots were flying too slow and
low in violation of normal safety regulations. They said the plane
was not at fault.
   The pilots maintained they were unfairly blamed, and said the
plane had failed to respond quickly to attempts to raise it.
</TEXT>
