<HEAD>RETRANSMITTING to fix cycle designator</HEAD>
<HEAD>U.S. Says Libya Able To Produce Chemical Weapons</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The State Department says an intelligence
report that Libya is on the verge of producing chemical weapons is
``a particularly worrisome development'' in light of Libya's record
of state-sponsored terrorism.
   Department spokesman Charles Redman on Wednesday called on
nations that may be contributing to the Libyan program to halt
their aid. He said the kinds of materials used in chemical weapons
are available on the world market.
   Redman said the United States verified the alleged Libyan
activities only recently, but he provided no information on type of
weapons Libya is developing nor did he say how U.S. officials
learned of the operations.
   Redman noted that there were reports last year that Libya had
used chemical weapons in its war with Chad.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>___</HEAD>
<HEAD>Senate Panel Insists North Comply With 5-Month-Old Subpoena</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Senate Foreign Relations Committee is
insisting that fired White House aide Oliver L. North produce
hundreds of pages of classified diary pages the former Marine
lieutenant colonel has so far kept from the panel.
   The committee voted 11-8 on Wednesday to insist North comply
with a subpoena it issued five months ago.
   Sen. John Kerry, D-Mass., is seeking the full diaries for a
subcommittee investigating international narcotics trafficking
because of heavily censored references to narcotics he noticed in
copies of diaries obtained by the Iran-Contra committees.
   North, through his attorney Brendan L. Sullivan, has objected to
turning over the voluminous diaries. Kerry urged his colleagues to
pursue the papers, saying ``delay plays into the hands ... of those
who want to see all of this disappear.''
</TEXT>
<HEAD>___</HEAD>
<HEAD>House, Senate Agree On Compromise Military Construction Spending</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Congress has approved $8.8 billion in spending
for military construction projects in the year beginning Oct. 1.
   The appropriation came in separate votes hours apart Wednesday,
first in the House and then in the Senate, that sent the compromise
measure to President Reagan for his signature.
   The House-Senate agreement is an increase from the $8.3 billion
construction budget for the current fiscal year but is below the
$9.7 billion sought by Reagan.
   It includes $65 million for the final stage of construction of a
national test facility in Colorado for Reagan's Strategic Defense
Initiative, also known as Star Wars. Absent, however, is $31
million Reagan had sought for construction of a railroad-based
version of the MX nuclear-tipped missile.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>___</HEAD>
<HEAD>Mail to Great Britain Still Halted</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The U.S. Postal Service is still asking
Americans to withhold mail to Great Britain, even though mail
workers in that country have settled their strike.
   Mail to Britain was embargoed last week because of the strike,
and U.S. officials said they would return Britain-bound items to
the senders.
   Although an agreement to settle the strike was reached Monday, a
huge backlog of mail remains to be sorted and delivered there. U.S.
officials said Wednesday it may be at least a week before they
begin accepting mail addressed to the United Kingdom.
