<DOCNO> AP880915-0064 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-09-15-88 0606EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-BabiloniaOverdose     09-15 0468</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Babilonia Overdose,0483</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Olympic Skater Hospitalized after Pill Overdose</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JEFF WILSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Former Olympic ice skater Tai Babilonia,
unhappy about recent performances, was hospitalized nearly four
hours after taking a large number of pills in what was termed an
accidental overdose, police said.
   Her father denied it was a suicide attempt and her publicist
contradicted a police report account of the incident.
   Miss Babilonia was taken to Cedars-Sinai Medical Center and
released four hours later Wednesday in good condition, hospital
spokeswoman Paula Correia said.
   ``I talked to her and she seemed fine,'' said Miss Correia.
   The skater left the hospital with her mother, Cleo, and skating
partner Randy Gardner, the spokeswoman said, declining to discuss
what type of pills were involved or other details. Miss Babilonia's
publicist, Michael Levine, contradicted a police account of the
incident.
   A police spokesman, Bill Frio, said the 28-year-old skating star
had earlier called her manager, Nancy Rosenberg, saying she was
unhappy about her recent skating performances and had taken a large
number of pills.
   Her mother was notified and called paramedics, who picked the
skater up at the family home.
   ``We have to take an injury report in any situation like this,
but we are treating this as an accidental overdose'' despite Miss
Bablyonia's conversation with her manager, Frio said.
   The skater's father, retired Los Angeles police Detective
Constancio Babilonia, called police to say his daughter took the
pills accidentally and that it wasn't a suicide attempt, Detective
Bruce Janis said.
   Levine said Miss Babilonia ``was taken to Cedars-Sinai Medical
Center for treatment of severe stomach cramps due to a reaction to
a non-prescription medication.''
   ``I was one of two people that saw her. She looked like she had
gone two rounds with (heavyweight boxing champion) Mike Tyson.''
   He denied it was a suicide attempt, and said the police report
about the skater's conversation with her manager was wrong.
   ``Yes, her manager spoke to her this morning, but it was a very
routine conversation,'' Levine said.
   In 1979, Miss Babilonia and Gardner were crowned world figure
skating champions in Vienna, Austria, shattering the 14-year Soviet
domination of pairs skating. They were the first Americans in 29
years to capture the title.
   Gardner and Miss Babilonia were favored to win a gold medal in
mixed-pairs figure skating during the 1980 Winter Games in Lake
Placid, N.Y. But they had to drop out of the competition because
Gardner suffered a leg injury.
   After the failed Olympic bid, the duo signed on with the Ice
Capades and performed with show until 1983, said show spokesman Tom
Abramson. The couple also was featured guest stars at the Festival
on Ice, Knott's Berry Farms' Ice Spectacular and a summer Ice Show
in Lake Tahoe, and appeared in television commercials.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
