<2ND_LINE>PM-NATO Crash,0144</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>West German Jet Crashes, Two Crewmen Missing</HEAD>
<DATELINE>COPENHAGEN, Denmark (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A West German fighter-bomber stalled
and plunged into the sea off Denmark during NATO maneuvers, and its
two crewmen were missing, the alliance's command said today.
   The RF-4 Phantom jet crashed off southern Denmark into Greatbelt
Strait between the Baltic islands of Zealand and Funen, Defense
Command Headquarters said.
   The jet, out of the West German air force base of Leck, was
simulating an enemy attacker when it appeared to stall at an
altitude of about a half-mile, the command said.
   Danish navy vessels and rescue helicopters scoured the crash
site Wednesday, and West German forces took over the search today.
   A total of 18,000 troops from Denmark, West Germany and Britain
are participating in the one-week ``Bold Grouse'' maneuver, which
includes practice of amphibious landings.
</TEXT>
