<2ND_LINE>PM-Weatherpage Weather,0520</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Thunderstorms Lash Texas Panhandle; Apparent Tornado in Amarillo</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Severe thunderstorms unrelated to Hurricane Gilbert lashed the
Texas Panhandle today with strong winds and torrential rains and
spawned an apparent tornado in Amarillo.
   Hurricane Gilbert's outer reaches kept rain and thunderstorms
over southern Florida and the Keys. The hurricane moved off
Mexico's Yucatan Peninsula into the Gulf of Mexico, where its 120
mph winds were expected to strengthen, and a hurricane watch was
posted for the entire Texas coast.
   The Texas Panhandle storms dropped up to 5 inches of rain south
of Amarillo late Wednesday and today. The rain pushed Lake Bennett
over its shores and flooded roads around Amarillo with up to 5 feet
of water.
   The storms generated 60 mph gusts and produced golf-ball size
hail. About a dozen homes were damaged in southwest Amarillo where
residents reported sighting a tornado late Wednesday.
   Showers and a few thunderstorms also extended across western
Kansas and eastern Colorado into western Nebraska and over
northeast North Carolina. A band of showers extended from western
Missouri and eastern Kansas to eastern North Dakota.
   Today's forecast called for scattered showers and thunderstorms
over the eastern Gulf of Mexico region and Florida; showers and
thunderstorms over the northern and central Plains, the upper
Mississippi Valley, northwest Missouri and Oklahoma; and widely
scattered showers in northwest Washington state. The rest of the
country was predicted to have mostly sunny skies.
   Highs were forecast to be in the 50s over northern New England;
in the 60s along the Pacific Coast, the central Rockies, the
northern Plains, the upper Mississippi Valley and from the northern
Great Lakes to southern New England; in the 90s in southern
Florida, the lower Mississippi Valley, Texas and the inland
California valleys; and near 100 degrees in the desert Southwest.
Highs elsewhere were expected to be in the 70s and 80s.
   Early morning temperatures ranged from the 30s and 40s in the
Great Lakes, central and northern Plains and northern Rockies to
the 60s and 70s from the southern Plains and lower and middle
Mississippi Valley to the southern Atlantic Coast and lower 80s in
southern Florida.
   At 3 a.m. EDT, temperatures ranged from 35 degrees at Marquette,
Mich., to 83 degrees at Fort Lauderdale and West Palm Beach, Fla.
   Other reports:
   _East: Atlanta 76 fair; Boston 59 fair; Buffalo 50 fair;
Charleston, S.C. 75 fair; Cleveland 59 fair; Detroit 54 fair; Miami
83 partly cloudy; New York 65 fair; Philadelphia 62 fair;
Pittsburgh 57 fair; Portland, Me. 52 fair; Washington 64 fair.
   _Central: Bismarck 54 rain; Dallas-Fort Worth 73 cloudy; Denver
47 fair; Des Moines 64 rain; Indianapolis 61 fair; Kansas City 69
showers; Minneapolis-St. Paul 62 cloudy; Nashville 68 fair; New
Orleans 79 partly cloudy; St. Louis 70 fair.
   _West: Albuquerque 58 fair; Anchorage 42 fair; Las Vegas 69
fair; Los Angeles 62 fair; Phoenix 80 fair; Salt Lake City 49 fair;
San Diego 66 cloudy; San Francisco 54 fair; Seattle 52 fair.
   _Canada: Montreal 43 fair; Toronto 46 fair.
</TEXT>
