<2ND_LINE>PM-Dollar-Gold,0297</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dollar Little Changed, Gold Mixed</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The dollar traded steadily in thin European
trading today and dealers expected it would retain the gains from
the previous day's smaller-than-expected trade deficit.
   Gold prices were mixed.
   Foreign exchange dealers said market activity was light, partly
because of a national holiday in Japan, and there were no signs of
central bank intervention.
   They predicted the dollar would remain well-supported by gains
won Wednesday after the U.S. government announced a July trade
deficit of $9.53 billion, down from $13.22 billion in June. The
dollar rose sharply after the unexpectedly large narrowing of the
deficit was announced.
   Other dollar rates at midmorning, compared with late Wednesday:
   _1.8749 West German marks, down from 1.8783
   _1.5810 Swiss francs, down from 1.5835
   _6.3760 French francs, down from 6.3915
   _2.1144 Dutch guilders, down from 2.1155
   _1,399.75 Italian lire, up from 1,399.50
   _1.2240 Canadian dollars, up from 1.2223
   In London, one British pound cost $1.6785, more expensive for
buyers that late Wednesday's $1.6750.
   In Tokyo, financial markets were closed for Respect for the Aged
Day, a national holiday. In London, the dollar was quoted at 133.95
yen, down from late Wednesday's 134.55.
   Gold opened in London at a bid price of $421.40 a troy ounce,
and at midmorning the city's five major bullion dealers fixed a
recommended price of $421.50. Both bid prices were down from the
$421.75 bid late Wednesday.
   In Zurich, the bid price was $421.75, up slightly from $421.50
bid late Wednesday
   Earlier, in Hong Kong, gold remained unchanged today to close at
a bid $423.45.
   Silver was quoted in London at a bid price of $6.50 a troy
ounce, up from Wednesday's $6.53.
</TEXT>
