<DOCNO> AP880915-0073 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-09-15-88 0830EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-Local560     09-15 0445</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Local 560,0462</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Judge Bars Two Ex-Local 560 Execs From Running For Office</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DANIEL J. WAKIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEWARK, N.J. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A federal judge has barred the apparent
front-runner for president of a Teamsters local from seeking
office, ruling that his victory could restore mob influence to the
first union taken over by court-appointed trustee.
   ``Normally, the members should be free to elect incompetent,
unwise or even dishonest officials if they choose,'' U.S. District
Judge Dickinson R. Debevois said Wednesday. ``However, more than
mere competence, wisdom or honesty is involved here. There is
involved the question of the renewed subjugation of a major union
local to an organized crime group.''
   Ballots are to be mailed Nov. 4 and counted Dec. 6 in the first
contested election since the 1960s at Union City-based Teamsters
Local 560, which was placed in trusteeship in 1986 to rid it of
alleged control by members of the Gambino crime family.
   Local 560 trustee Edwin Stier is to step down after the
elections.
   The judge's ruling, which was sought by the government, was
aimed at Joseph Sheridan and Michael Sciarra, the favorite for
president of the 8,000-member local.
   ``We lost, but don't ask me why,'' an angry Sciarra said. ``I
think we're better off in Poland than in the United States of
America. It's supposed to be the United States of America, but I
don't think it is.''
   Sciarra was president and Sheridan vice president from 1984 to
1986 while the union appealed the trusteeship decision.
   The judge, relying partly on wiretaps of reputed mobsters, said
the government had shown illegalities under Sciarra, including the
continuation of sweetheart contracts, intimidation, Mafia efforts
to control union affairs, and the failure of Sciarra and Sheridan
to repudiate the local's dark history.
   Sciarra's attorney, Alan Zegas, called the ruling ``truly an
unwarranted intrusion'' into the election process and said he would
appeal.
   Zegas said it was wrong for the judge to act before the
election. If Sciarra won, the judge could then consider his
removal, Zegas argued.
   Debevoise said he had the power to act under the federal
Racketeer Influenced and Corrupt Organizations law, under which the
government brought suit to remove the union's executive board.
   ``The public interest in racketeer-free corporations and unions
overrides the interest of stockholders of corporations or members
of unions freely to select their officers,'' he wrote.
   Russell Viggiani, a candidate for Local 560 president, said the
ruling was a disappointment because it would cast a cloud over the
outcome.
   ``I'm hoping that after this election is over, the ticket that
is elected will have the support of the entire rank and file,'' he
said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880915-0074 </DOCNO>
