<1ST_LINE>u i PM-Hurricane-Resort     09-15 0462</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Hurricane-Resort,0479</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Hurricane Turns Cancun Vacations Into Nightmares</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Hurricane Gilbert, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CHRIS ANGELO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CANCUN, Mexico (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Hurricane Gilbert transformed this idyllic
Caribbean resort into a nightmare for thousands of stranded
tourists sheltered in cramped hotels and public buildings.
   ``Believe me, I will not come back here,'' said Pete Fournier of
Long Island, N.Y.
   His wife, Sheila, bemoaned their evacuation from the Villas
Playas Hotel. ``It had an ocean-front view, which is now washed
away,'' she said.
   Bringing winds of up to 218 mph when it hit this Yucatan coastal
city Wednesday morning, Gilbert forced about 6,000 tourists to
leave their beachside hotels and seek shelter, according to an
official with the National Civil Defense System.
   The official, who spoke on condition of anonymity, said 30,000
workers and residents also sought temporary shelter on the island
off the Yucatan peninsula, a popular vacation spot for Americans.
   Jennie Valdez, a U.S. consular representative in Cancun, said
she did not know how many tourists were in Cancun, but that 40,000
and 65,000 people visit the resort city each month.
   As the storm shattered windows, twisted utility poles and
flattened homes, about 150 tourists were crammed into a
20-by-50-foot room in Cancun's City Hall.
   Gilbert's fierce winds ripped police and radio antennas off the
roof above, and stiff palm fronds crashed into windows.
   However, some newlyweds took in stride the forced exchange of
beach-front views for boarded-up windows.
   ``The first two days were great,'' said Joseph Camuccio of
Philadelphia, who arrived in Cancun Sunday. He said he and his wife
had not eaten in 24 hours and were trying to figure out how to get
out of Cancun.
   Even as Gilbert closed in on Cancun, many residents resisted
attempts by authorities to move them to safer areas.
   ``There were people who did not want to leave,'' said an army
official who checked the area for stranded residents. ``It was
something new. They didn't know what a cyclone was.''
   He said most people, particularly those in low-lying areas,
changed their minds once the storm hit.
   Mexico's National Weather Service ordered the evacuation of
everyone living less than 15 feet above sea level and within 2,000
feet of the Caribbean coast.
   Some tourists said that winds made shrieking sounds at the
height of the storm. Others compared the noise to the pounding of
heavy surf.
   Broken windows in the commercial area of the tourist mecca
invited bands of young looters.
   ``They're looting all the stores,'' said Alfredo Moro Sanchez of
the state judicial police. About three or four people were
arrested, City Police Director Juan Manuel Arteaga said.
   City officials said Wednesday they knew of only two minor
injuries caused by the storm. They also reported five births during
the hurricane.
</TEXT>
