<1ST_LINE>r p PM-CaliforniaPoll     09-15 0365</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-California Poll,350</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Poll Shows California Voters Evenly Split on Presidential Race</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Political Rdp Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SAN FRANCISCO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Republican nominee George Bush has closed a
16-percentage point gap and is now running neck-and-neck with
Democrat Michael Dukakis in their battle to win California voters,
according to a new poll.
   The California Poll released on Thursday showed that Dukakis' 52
percent to 36 percent lead over Bush in late July had been reduced
to 46 percent to 45 percent, a tie within the poll's 4 percent
margin of error.
   ``It's a dead heat,'' said Bill Lacy, Bush's chief operative in
the state. ``We always thought that when people started comparing
the two candidates, George Bush would do very well.''
   Anthony Podesta, Dukakis' California campaign manager, said the
poll reflects GOP attempts to paint Dukakis as an ultraliberal
Democrat.
   The Republicans ``have thrown a lot of mud,'' Podesta said,
``but the bumper stickers of August won't be what decides the
outcome in November.''
   The new poll shows Dukakis leading in Northern California and
among women voters and minorities. Bush is ahead in Southern
California and among men and non-Hispanic white voters.
   ``It's a phenomenal reversal. I've never seen anything like
it,'' said poll director Mervin Field. He cautioned that ``people
can easily change their minds.''
   ``The voters began by looking at Bush and a lot didn't like what
they saw. But they also didn't have a fix on Dukakis,'' Field said.
``Now they've begun to look at Dukakis. He's been under attack by
the Bush people for several weeks, and he hasn't handled it well.''
   The latest California Poll shows Bush is supported by 83 percent
of the state's GOP voters. Support among Democrats has grown to 14
percent from 9 percent six weeks ago.
   Meanwhile, the Massachusetts governor's strong showing among
Democrats who voted for President Reagan in 1984 has eroded.
   Six weeks ago, so-called Reagan Democrats backed Dukakis over
Bush by 55 percent to 26 percent. The latest poll shows the
breakdown is 48 percent for Dukakis and 44 percent for Bush.
   The poll was based on telephone interviews with 674 registered
voters and was conducted between Sept. 6 and Sept. 12.
</TEXT>
