<FILEID>AP-NR-09-15-88 0932EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-DuneShacks     09-15 0400</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Dune Shacks,0410</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>State Commission Votes on Cape Dune Shack Issue</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN DIAMOND</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LINCOLN, Mass. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Rickety dune shacks on Cape Cod that
provided a retreat for artists and writers such as Eugene O'Neill
and Jack Kerouac belong on the National Register of Historic
Places, says a state commission.
   With the Massachusetts Historical Commission's unanimous
recommendation Wednesday, the register must decide whether to grant
historic status to the 18 shacks and list them along with Mount
Vernon and Monticello.
   A vocal group of supporters argues that the shacks are no less
significant to the state and the nation.
   ``Just as Thoreau taught us the value of living simply, so do
the cottages,'' said Julie Schecter, a member of a Cape Cod group
fighting to preserve the shacks. ``The cottages continue to let
people live in the same way that early dune dwellers lived.''
   Three shacks were razed recently, according to Gail Cohen, who
has lobbied for their preservation. The National Park Service
planned to tear down the remaining 18, arguing that they lack
architectural significance required of buildings placed on the
national register.
   The shacks are nestled in a two-mile strip of dunes in Truro and
Provincetown at the far end of the Cape. The Coast Guard built them
around the turn of the century of rough wood and salvage material.
   They were used as shelters from harsh coastal weather. In the
1920s, as Provincetown attracted artists and writers, they became
retreats. In 1961, with the creation of the Cape Cod National
Seashore, the shacks became part of the park service domain.
   Artist Joyce Johnson of Truro, who has painted in a dune shack
off and on for 15 years, told the commission it is no surprise to
her that so many writers have done their best work there.
   ``The sometimes overwhelming awareness of nature _ the wind,
sound of the sea, songs of birds _ allow the creative forces to
clarify and congeal in ideas that might take months in another
space,'' Johnson said.
   The final decision will be made in 45 days, according to Beth
Savage, an architectural historian from the register who will be
responsible for the decision.
   ``Architectural significance is only one way you get on the
register,'' Savage said. ``If the shacks played a significant role
in the history and development of the area, then sure, there's a
possibility.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
