<1ST_LINE>u i PM-Burma 2ndLd-Writethru a0543 09-15 0743</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Burma, 2nd Ld - Writethru, a0543,0760</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Opposition Leaders Appeal For Restraint After Increasingly
Militant Protests</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS penultimate graf, `Massive protests ...,' to CORRECT
date of deaths. PICKS up last graf, `On Aug. ...'</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By SEIN WIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>RANGOON, Burma (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Opposition leaders appealed today for
restraint by student activists seeking more violent means to topple
the authoritarian government of President Maung Maung.
   Tens of thousands of demonstrators again filled the streets of
Rangoon.
   Sources said one student group went to the U.S. Embassy on
Wednesday asking for weapons, and another group said it had 5,000
people ready to take up arms. An embassy official told the group
the United States could offer only moral support, said the sources,
who demanded anonymity.
   Some students have called for volunteers to undergo training in
military tactics.
   Tens of thousands of people, including several thousand high
school students, marched in the capital today. One estimate put the
total at 100,000.
   A one-legged man with a crutch led a group of about 50 ill-clad,
apparently homeless men carrying a banner that said: ``Pavement
Dwellers, Suicide Squad.''
   ``We are prepared to die for democracy. We have nothing to
lose,'' the middle-aged man told a reporter.
   The three main opposition leaders, former Brig. Gen. Aung Gyi,
former Defense Minister Tin Oo, and Aung San Suu Kyi, daughter of
independence leader Aung San, issued a joint statement condemning
violence.
   ``The people including the students should continue peaceful
demonstrations and general strikes steadfastly using the weapon of
moral courage, as was the original intention,'' it said. ``Violence
arising out of impatience and overzealousness and further bloodshed
should be avoided.''
   Street demonstrations have become increasingly militant in
recent days.
   ``You run or we will kill you!'' marchers shouted Wednesday,
jabbing fists in the air as they used more militant and threatening
slogans than before. ``If they don't fall, make them fall,'' they
chanted.
   More than 100,000 people marched that day through the streets of
Rangoon.
   The student-led street protests have forced one concession after
another from Maung Maung's one-party government in recent weeks,
but the opposition has persisted in demands an interim government
be immediately formed to supervise a general election. The
opposition, which is comprised of students, Buddhist monks,
government workers and others, also has called for an an end to the
party's repression and ruinous economic policies.
   Maung Maung's government announced last weekend it would end the
Burma Socialist Program Party's 26-year monopoly on power and hold
the first multiparty elections since 1960. The polling could be as
early as late October.
   But the three opposition leaders told the state-appointed
election commission Tuesday they would not accept any polling
organized by the current government. They said they would not
support or participate in such elections, and repeated their demand
for an interim government.
   Rangoon newspapers reported today that Capt. Sai Win Kyaw of the
22nd Light Infantry Brigade held a news conference the previous day
and charged the army had been exploited by the government. He
called on all members of the army to resign.
   At least 500 soldiers slipped out of their barracks Sept. 9 and
joined the demonstrators, and others are believed disallusioned
over the high living of senior officers while combat soldiers are
sent out to fight rebels with outdated weapons.
   Meanwhile, more than 90 people, including students and workers,
sat on bamboo mats on the pavement outside City Hall and began a
72-hour hunger strike at the spot where where the military shot
dead several demonstrators Aug. 8.
   They followed about 75 protesters who ended a 48-hour hunger
strike there in the morning, and more than 1,000 schoolchildren who
completed a 36-hour fast Monday night at the Rangoon General
Hospital compound.
   In beginning the series of hunger strikes, the opposition has
revived a tactic employed several decades ago in fighting British
colonial rule.
   The country's last multiparty elections, on Feb. 6, 1960, swept
former Prime Minister Nu to power over an army-backed party. He was
toppled in the 1962 coup led by Ne Win, who isolated the nation and
pursued rigid socialist policies that made resource-rich Burma one
of the world's poorest nations.
   Massive protests began after Ne Win resigned July 23 and the
party named hardliner Sein Lwin his successor. Sein Lwin resigned
17 days later after at least 112 people died during rioting in
Rangoon Aug. 8-12.
   On Aug. 19, Maung Maung became Burma's first civilian leader
since Nu.
</TEXT>
