<HEAD>Charges Dropped Against Woman Who Tried To Keep $100 Windfall</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MANCHESTER, Conn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Charges have been dropped against an
89-year-old woman who found $100 on a bus and tried to apply the
playground rule ``Finders, keepers.''
   Anna Philips of East Hartford was arrested Sept. 2 when she
refused to give a Connecticut Transit driver or Glastonbury police
the money found in an envelope on a bus seat on her way to cash her
Social Security check.
   The great-grandmother of 17 was charged with failure to perform
the duties of a finder under an obscure law that carries a fine of
$100 and 30 days in jail.
   Assistant State's Attorney Cornelius Shea announced in Superior
Court on Wednesday that the state wouldn't prosecute.
   ``The police are in possession of the money,'' he said. ``If the
owner doesn't come forward, the money will be given to the finder.''
   ``The ends of justice have been met,'' he said.
