<1ST_LINE>u a PM-SpaceShuttle 1stLd-Writethru a0482 09-15 0493</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Space Shuttle, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0482,0501</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Hurricane Delays Decision On Space Shuttle Launch Date</HEAD>
<HEAD>LEADS with three grafs to UPDATE with leak solved; PICKS UP 3rd
graf pvs, `Rear Adm. ...'</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Hurricane Gilbert, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By HOWARD BENEDICT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Aerospace Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CAPE CANAVERAL, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   NASA says it still hopes to launch
Discovery this month but is delaying setting a date because
Hurricane Gilbert could disrupt operations at the flight control
center in Houston.
   In making the announcement Wednesday, the space agency also
cited uncertainty about a small hydrogen leak detected in the space
shuttle's main engine propulsion system, a problem not considered
serious.
   Engineers solved that problem today, NASA said.
   Rear Adm. Richard Truly, NASA's associate administrator for
space flight, said Friday is the earliest a launch date would be
set. He said Sept. 26 is the earliest possible target for launching
Discovery and its five-man crew.
   The hurricane, which churned in the Gulf of Mexico today, was on
a course that could take it to the Texas coast near Houston. NASA's
Johnson Space Center is located south of Houston, 30 miles inland
from the gulf.
   ``We don't know where the hurricane is going, but we thought it
best to wait a day or so, or whatever it takes to make a
decision,'' Truly said.
   ``Even though Houston doesn't get hit, it is a threat to
Houston, and we have people there who have to turn attention to
their homes and families, just as other people along the Texas
coast are doing,'' Truly said.
   Once a shuttle is launched, the mission is controlled from the
Johnson center. Earlier storms in that area have caused flooding,
disrupting communications and computer operations at the center.
   Truly spoke to reporters at the conclusion of a two-day flight
readiness review during which more than 150 shuttle managers and
engineers and outside experts evaluated the shuttle's systems and
the preparedness of launch and flight control teams.
   Truly said he polled the 15 key NASA and contractor managers at
the conclusion of the review, ``and there wasn't a dissenting vote
to launch. ... We're in a very positive situation.''
   The review was to have established a firm launch date for the
first shuttle mission since Challenger exploded on Jan. 28, 1986,
killing the crew of seven. Officials were considering a date
between Sept. 26 and 29.
   Truly reported the only open technical issue was a tiny leak
detected in Discovery's engine propulsion system during a pressure
check last week. He said the exact location of the leak had not
been determined.
   ``We see a small leak. We don't believe it is serious. It's the
only unknown we have right now,'' said Forrest S. McCartney,
director of the National Aeronautics and Space Administration's
Kennedy Space Center.
   McCartney said engineers believe it might be in ground support
equipment and that they felt it would be easy to isolate and
correct without affecting a late September launch.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880915-0085 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-09-15-88 1017EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Papandreou     09-15 0275</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Papandreou,0283</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Premier Plans Divorce After Heart Surgery</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KERIN HOPE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ATHENS, Greece (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Premier Andreas Papandreou plans to
divorce his American-born wife, Margaret, when he returns to Greece
after undergoing heart surgery in London, the government said today.
   On Wednesday, the 69-year-old premier was pictured in Greek
newspapers strolling hand-in-hand with his 34-year-old girlfriend,
airline stewardess Dimitra Liani.
   Papandreou is awaiting surgery to replace a heart valve. No date
has been set for the operation at Harefield Hospital in London, but
his doctors say it probably will take place later this month.
   The Socialist premier flew to London three weeks ago for
treatment of a narrowing in the aorta, the main artery carrying
blood from the heart.
   Asked about a divorce, government spokesman Sotiris Kostopoulos
told Greek reporters ``when the premier returns the process of
dissolving his marriage will be set in motion.''
   Papandreou's doctors have said that if the operation is
successful he can return to Athens after a two-week recovery period
and resume work two months later.
   Mrs. Papandreou, 65, who heads a socialist feminist group, the
Women's Organization of Greece, made no immediate comment on the
divorce announcement.
   Papandreou married the former Margaret Chant of Elmhurst, Ill.,
in 1951, when he was teaching economics at the University of
Minnesota. They have four children and two grandchildren. Their
eldest son, George, 37, serves as minister of education in the
government.
   The spokesman did not say whether the premier plans to marry Ms.
Liani, who works for Greece's state-run carrier Olympic Airways.
Ms. Liani, the daughter of a Greek Army officer, is married to an
architect, Athanassios Kapopoulos.
</TEXT>
