<2ND_LINE>PM-Greenpeace Demo,0272</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Protesters Hang From Triborough Bridge</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Operators of a sludge-laden barge outsmarted 13
Greenpeace demonstrators who attempted to stop it by swinging from
ropes beneath the Triborough Bridge _ the vessel simply took
another route to sea to dump its load.
   The demonstrators tied up traffic on the bridge and the East
River before climbing back up shortly before 2 a.m. today, eight
hours after they lowered themselves from the span and unfurled a
huge banner reading, ``Stop Ocean Dumping Now.''
   Andrew Davis, spokesman for the worldwide ecological group, said
the protesters had hoped to block barges carrying treated sewage
sludge for dumping 106 miles at sea.
   They dangled some 100 feet above the water, forcing the Coast
Guard to stop all traffic from passing under the bridge, said Coast
Guard spokesman Joe Gibson.
   But the barge departed as scheduled shortly before midnight,
traveling north via Long Island Sound to the ocean instead of
south, said Lt. Cmdr. Larry Brooks.
   ``We couldn't let them transit under the bridge because of the
safety to these people,'' Brooks said. ``So they asked if it was OK
to take an alternative route and we thought it was perfectly
suitable.''
   Police Sgt. Ed Burns said 13 people who swung from the bridge
and 11 others who assisted were arrested and would be charged with
criminal trespass, disorderly conduct and obstructing governmental
administration, all misdemeanors.
   On Tuesday, five Greenpeace members were arrested after they
chained a dinghy to the rear of a sewage barge and a protester to a
mooring line, police said.
</TEXT>
