<1ST_LINE>u i PM-Israel-Hungary 1stLd-Writethru a0535 09-15 0576</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Israel-Hungary, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0535,0590</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>PRECEDE Jerusalem</HEAD>
<HEAD>Shamir's Visit Called Historic Milestone</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: UPDATES thruout with details of visit. No pickup.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By TEDDIE WEYR</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BUDAPEST, Hungary (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Israeli Prime Minister Yitzhak Shamir
said today that Israel and Hungary have agreed to gradually restore
diplomatic ties after a 21-year break and pledged close contacts
with central Europe's largest Jewish community.
   Shamir, on a private visit to Hungary, is making the first trip
by an Israeli prime minister to a Soviet bloc country other than
Romania since 1967.
   He is also the first Israeli government leader to visit Hungary
since the establishment of the Jewish state in 1948. His aide
Aviezer Pazner termed the two-day visit an ``important milestone''
for relations between Israel and the Soviet bloc, and said
diplomatic ties will be restored.
   On Wednesday, Shamir met with Communist Party leader and Premier
Karoly Grosz in the highest-level bilateral contact since all
Soviet bloc nations except Romania broke diplomatic ties with
Israel in 1967 over the Six Day War.
   Today, Shamir reported that Grosz favors ``close contact between
Israel and the Jewish community in Hungary.''
   ``Accordingly we will try to establish very close contacts,''
Shamir pledged in a lunchtime toast delivered in Hebrew to about a
dozen Jewish community leaders.
   Pazner said relations between Hungary and Israel are getting
closer and ``will result at some point in full diplomatic
relations.''
   He gave no timetable for establishing full diplomatic ties, but
said the two countries had ``reached the point when we feel the
moment of full normalization can't be too far away.''
   Pazner said there was no reason why ``Israel and Hungary and all
countries of the Socialist bloc shouldn't have normal relations.''
   Shamir's stay in Budapest was described as a private working
visit. But he met Grosz, Foreign Minister Peter Varkonyi and Deputy
Premier Jozsef Marjai.
   In September 1987, Hungary became the second Soviet bloc state
after Poland to renew low-level diplomatic relations with Israel.
Last March, economic interest sections were set up by both
countries at the Swedish Embassy in Tel Aviv and the Swiss Embassy
in Budapest.
   The movement toward renewed ties comes as Israel agreed to begin
assisting Hungary in the economic and industrial development
fields. nflation in Hungary already has reached 18 percent this
year and the country has a foreign debt of $18 billion.
   Grosz has introduced an austerity program to stimuate the
economy. In 1986, trade between Hungary and Israel totaled about
$22 million.
   The president of Hungary's state office for church affairs, Imre
Miklos, visited Israel earlier this month and Israel's Foreign
Minister Shimon Peres came to Budapest in May.
   Andras Losoenci, the president of Hungary's Jewish community,
which numbers about 80,000, said Shamir's visit to Budapest's main
synagogue, the largest in central Europe, was ``of historic
significance.''
   He recalled that 600,000 Hungarian Jews were killed by the Nazis
in World War II.
   ``It's difficult now not to think that if Israel was founded 50
years ago, and not 40, you would represent not 80,000 Jews but 1
million,'' Shamir told about a dozen Jewish community leaders in a
lunchtime toast.
   About 240,0000 Jews of Hungarian origin live in Israel.
   Shamir stopped at the synagogue and paid tribute to Raoul
Wallenberg, the Swedish diplomat who helped Hungarian Jews escape
the Holocaust and disappeared after being captured by the Soviets
in January 1945.
   Security was very tight during the brief visit to the memorial.
</TEXT>
