<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Israel     09-15 0391</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Israel,0407</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Israeli Troops Kill Palestinian Boy After Firebomb Attack</HEAD>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Israeli troops shot and killed an 11-year-old
Palestinian boy after Arab assailants hurled a firebomb at their
jeep in the occupied Gaza Strip, the army said today.
   Troops also shot and wounded four teen-agers, two seriously,
after a group of Palestinian young people threw stones at them in
Nablus, hospital officials said.
   Chief of Staff Lt. Gen. Dan Shomron announced violence in the
Israeli-occupied territories had declined in the past two weeks,
despite continuing clashes. He reported 612 cases of ``hostile
activity'' against Israeli targets, down from 1,019 in the previous
two weeks, according to the Davar newspaper.
   In Gaza City on Wednesday, assailants tossed a firebomb from the
Salah Edin mosque at troops on night patrol in a jeep, hitting the
patrol commander in the leg, the army and Arab reports said.
   An army spokesman said the Arab boy was killed when soldiers
opened fire in the direction of the firebomb. Hospital officials
said the boy was shot in the head.
   The fatality brought to 266 the number of Palestinians killed
since the Arab uprising began Dec. 8. Six Israelis also have died.
   In Nablus, an 18-year-old Palestinian was shot in the chest and
a 16-year-old in the stomach. Both were reported in serious
condition, hospital officials said. Two other teen-agers were
slightly wounded, they said.
   The army confirmed that troops shot and wounded three people
during a stone-throwing incident in the markeplace in Nablus and
was checking the report about the fourth casualty.
   In London, Israeli Foreign Minister Shimon Peres today
challenged Palestinian leader Yasser Arafat to ``make up his mind''
about whether he wants peace with Israel.
   He said Arafat's Palestine Liberation Organization was ``in a
confused state,'' torn between proponents of compromise with Israel
and those who wanted to destroy the Jewish state.
   At a news conference winding up a visit to Britain, Peres did
not spell out whether Israel now agreed to talk to the PLO and
accept an independent Palestinian state.
   Peres said Arafat's latest policy pronouncements, during a visit
last week to the European Parliament in Strasbourg, France, were
``an escape from the issue.''
   Arafat told the European Parliament's socialists that Jordan's
decision to cut its ties to the West Bank would pave the way for an
independent Palestinian state.
</TEXT>
