<HEAD>20 Named as Carnegie Heroes</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PITTSBURGH (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Twenty people in 14 states and two Canadian
provinces were honored as heroes today by the Carnegie Hero Fund
Commission.
   Two of the heroes died in performance of their acts, the
commission said.
   The commission was founded by industrialist Andrew Carnegie in
1904 to honor heroic acts performed by civilians in the United
States and Canada. It has honored 77 heroes this year and 7,258
since its inception.
   The heroes or their survivors, who received $2,500 cash and a
medal, were identified as:
   _Bruce Dobbs of Fairfax Station, Va.
   _Todd Allen Brill of Elkhart, Ind.
   _John E. Connor of Trenton, N.J.
   _Thomas William Luzak of Walton, Ky.
   _Arthur H.C. Ham of Arnprior, Ontario.
   _Guy A. Keally of Johnson City, Tenn.
   _Larry B. Pulai of Saskatoon, Saskatchewan.
   _Donna Marie Bell of Ingleside, Ill.
   _Hsien-li Chang of San Francisco.
   _Michael Allen of Conroe, Texas.
   _Connie Sue Gries of Evansville, Ind.
   _Berman P. Detty of Frankfort, Ohio.
   _Thomas C. Morris Jr. of Sugar Hill, Ga.
   _George A. Andrews of Fairfield, Calif.
   _Thomas J. Cathcart of Ellenville, N.Y.
   _Vernon W. Gist of England, Ark.
   _Richard C. Pool of England, Ark.
   _Fred A. Thomas Jr. of Wilkes-Barre, Pa.
   _The late James Michael Paradis of Chelsea, Mass.
   _The late Jeffrey G. Chipley of Estevan, Saskatchewan.
</TEXT>
