<1ST_LINE>r w PM-Deaver     09-15 0463</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Deaver,</2ND_LINE>
<BYLINE>By JAMES ROWLEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Michael K. Deaver's attorneys presented
evidence today that the former White House aide's judgment and
memory were impaired by alcoholism when questioned under oath about
his lobbying activities.
   The evidence that Deaver was an alcoholic ``at all times
relevant to this case'' was offered to give the ``court
understanding of the offense behavior for which Mr. Deaver was
convicted,'' defense attorney Randall J. Turk told U.S. District
Judge Thomas Penfield Jackson.
   The former deputy White House chief of staff and close friend of
President Reagan and his wife, Nancy, is scheduled to be sentenced
Sept. 23 for three counts of lying under oath about his lobbying
activities.
   He could receive up to five years and a $6,800 fine for each of
the three convictions.
   Testimony by doctors who treated Deaver for alcoholism shortly
after he left the White House in May, 1985, would show Deaver's
memory was impaired both by alcohol withdrawal sedatives he was
given while hospitalized for two days, Turk said.
   It was during this period that Deaver had telephone contacts
with Reagan administration officials about Trans World Airlines'
attempt to stop a takeover bid by financier Carl Icahn, according
to evidence at the trial.
   Deaver was found guilty, among other things, of saying he
couldn't recall any contacts with then-Transportation Secretary
Elizabeth Dole, her deputy, James Burnley and Roger Porter, a White
House aide.
   ``Possibly all of the three contacts took place while he was in
the hospital, while he was going through acute alcohol withdrawal
and while he was sedated,'' Turk said.
   The doctors would say that Deaver's subsequent ``failure to
recall what he was doing at the time was quite understandable.''
   But independent counsel Whitney North Seymour Jr. argued that
Deaver's treatment records would show ``there is nothing to support
any finding that his memory was impaired.''
   ``Mr. Deaver's ability to recall was absolutely functioning, it
was just that he decided to select what he wanted to recall,'' said
Seymour, who is expected to call a medical expert to rebut
testimony Deaver's lawyers plan to present during the two-day
proceeding.
   Turk said that Deaver had been an alcoholic for many years
before he sought treatment and that both his parents are recovering
alcoholics.
   Before he testified in May, 1986 before a House subcommittee,
Deaver took a Valium tablet that doctors say may have impaired his
memory when questioned about his lobbying activities, Turk said.
   Deaver was convicted of one count of lying to the House Energy
and Commerce investigations subcommittee. The other two perjury
convictions stem from statements he made to a grand jury that was
impaneled after Deaver requested an independent counsel to
investigate charges he violated conflict-of-interest laws by
lobbying former Reagan administration colleagues.
</TEXT>
