<1ST_LINE>r p BC-CampaignAbroad     09-15 0645</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Campaign Abroad,0678</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Foreign Press Comments on Bush-Dukakis Campaign</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDITOR'S NOTE </NOTE>
<TEXT>
   This is one of a series of periodic reports
compiled by Associated Press bureaus on how the U.S. presidential
election campaign is viewed abroad.
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Here is a sampling of commentary in foreign newspapers on the
presidential race between Democrat Michael Dukakis and Republican
George Bush:
</TEXT>
<HEAD>ITALY</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   _Washington correspondent Vittorio Zucconi in La Repubblica
(liberal) of Rome, Sept. 14: ``Just 50 days from the elections it
is still not clear which America _ isolationist, protectionist,
attacking or retreating _ President Bush or President Dukakis has
in mind.
   ``The answer ... is not in their words but in their actions.
Each is trying to conquer ... the same part of the voters. They are
both eyeing what once was called `the center' and today is defined
as the `Reagan Democrats'. ...
   ``Bush is afraid of being unmasked and seen as he really is, an
elitist and aristocratic Republican, not a reactionary one and far
away from the Reaganist populism. ...
   ``Dukakis doesn't dare to present himself as the `liberal' he
has always been, someone who believes in a reasoned but strong role
of the public hand in the economic and civic life of the nation.''
</TEXT>
<HEAD>AUSTRIA</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   _Monica Riedler writing in Die Presse (conservative) of Vienna,
Sept. 15: ``After weeks of discussions the two presidential
candidates, George Bush and Michael Dukakis, have agreed on holding
two TV debates, but now there is a dispute about whether the two of
them should debate standing or sitting.
   ``A ridiculous problem, but it's symptomatic of the current
election campaign in the U.S. in which real topics have hardly
played a role, while insults (have) much more.''
</TEXT>
<HEAD>WEST GERMANY</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   _Sueddeutsche Zeitung (independent) of Munich, Sept. 14:
``Dukakis is vulnerable to the Republican attack on his lack of
foreign policy experience. Dukakis has the bad luck not to have
been part of the broad public majority that supported the Reagan
administration's military interventions over the years. ...
   ``That is an admirable, but dangerous weakness. ... Indeed, his
notion that foreign policy should be carried out according to
international rules of the game has no sex appeal with the voters.
   ``The more America's role in the world is brought to the fore in
the campaign, the more points George Bush will collect.''
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   _Der Stern (left-leaning national news magazine), Sept. 12:
``George Bush has stepped out of Ronald Reagan's shadow. Reagan's
vice president is campaigning against his Democratic opponent with
self-confidence and media-consciousness.
   ``Mr. Bush has become much more aggressive and visible.''
</TEXT>
<HEAD>ISRAEL</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   _Yediot Ahronot (conservative) of Tel Aviv, Sept. 14: ``The
reason for the relatively small gap between the two candidates is
that the middle class, even though it is generally satisfied with
its situation, is nervous and concerned about the future.
   ``The real campaign is beginning only now. The television
campaign has not yet begun and the two television debates, between
Bush and Dukakis, and vice presidential candidates Bentsen and
Quayle, have yet to take place.
   Dukakis has a reputation for being a better debater (than Bush)
and Bentsen also seems to have an advantage over the younger
Quayle. The general feeling is that if anything happens to the
president, Bentsen is far more suited to take over than Quayle.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>UNITED ARAB EMIRATES</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   _Al-Ittihad (government-owned), Sept. 15: ``In the few months
and weeks that precede the American presidential elections,
everything is permitted the candidate, both Republican and
Democratic, and all demands of the Zionist lobby accepted since the
American-Jewish votes are one of the vital factors that determine
who will be the next U.S. president. ...
   ``Those who yield to the pressure of the Zionist lobby ... are
placing the interest of the Zionist entity above that of their own
country only for the sake of the Jewish votes.''
</TEXT>
