<FILEID>AP-NR-09-15-88 1159EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w PM-JudicialKfc     09-15 0348</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Judicial Kfc,240</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>New Judges Wanted, But Not Really Expected</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RICHARD CARELLI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Leaders of the federal government's judicial
branch said today they want Congress to create 73 new judgeships,
but a judicial spokesman said, ``The realities are that nothing
will happen during an election year.''
   The U.S. Judicial Conference, which sets policy for the nation's
federal courts, voted to request the new judgeships as a means of
eliminating backlogs and easing workloads, spokesman David Sellers
said.
   ``Case filings have increased,'' Sellers said, noting that the
last increase in the judicial workforce was in 1984 when Congress
authorized creation of 86 judgeships.
   The conference, 28 judges who act as a board of directors for
the federal courts, approved the judgeship request in a closed
meeting Wednesday.
   The request seeks 14 new appeals court judges and 59 trial
judges, but 22 of the trial judgeships would last only five years.
   The conference in 1986 sought 56 additional trial court judges
and 13 appeals court judges _ a proposal that went nowhere in
Congress.
   The request announced today represents an adjustment of the 1986
request.
   There currently are 158 appeals court judges and 548 trial
judges.
   Sellers said the Judicial Conference also approved spending
$70,000 to $90,000 on closed-circuit television cameras to monitor
``high risk'' trials.
   He said stationary cameras capable of scanning a courtroom will
be installed in 10 or 12 major cities. The cameras will provide a
video monitor feed to a marshal's office.
   The U.S. Marshals Service proposed the security measure.
   The conference also authorized a two-year experiment in making
videotapes the formal record of court proceedings.
   The experiment, to be conducted in six trial courts and two
appeals courts, is noteworthy because federal courts ban electronic
coverage of courtroom proceedings.
   Sellers said the experiment, patterned after a program already
in place in Kentucky state courts, is aimed at determining whether
videotapes should replace written records. During the experiment,
videotaping will supplement a stenographic record.
   Public access to the videotapes is ``something that has not been
determined yet,'' Sellers said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880915-0100 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-09-15-88 1144EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u p PM-Quayle 1stLd-Writethru a0478 09-15 0820</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Quayle, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0478,810</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Quayle Says Not Worried About Public's, Dukakis' Doubts</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Updates in top 8 grafs with news conference, picking up in
2nd graf pvs, The Republican; subs 5th graf pvs, The Indiana</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By EILEEN PUTMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>OKLAHOMA CITY (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Republican vice presidential nominee Dan
Quayle said today he was not worried about either Michael Dukakis'
comments or a new poll concerning doubts about his qualifications
for national office.
   ``I am delighted the governor of Massachusetts wants to talk
about my qualifications for being vice president as compared to his
qualifications for being president,'' Quayle said at a news
conference.
   ``He is the one who does not have the comprehension and
understanding of national security issues,'' Quayle said. ``I will
be delighted to compare my qualifications to his.''
   Asked about a new CBS-New York Times poll, in which just
one-third of the respondents said Quayle was qualified to be
president compared to three-fifths who said Democrat Lloyd Bentsen
was, Quayle said:
   ``We're going to continue to talk about the issues of the
campaign. ... In due time the American people are going to see the
real Dan Quayle.''
   The Indiana senator also indicated he was tired of hearing
Dukakis refer to him as J. Danforth Quayle, a tactic the governor
has adopted in recent days. The name, Quayle said, comes from a
friend of his family who was killed in World War II.
   ``That is my namesake. It is not a family name,'' Quayle said.
   One day earlier, Quayle denounced demonstrators at an event in
New Mexico and declared hoarsely after a spirited shouting match
with them: ``I'm just beginning to have fun.''
   The Republican vice presidential candidate's tactic appeared to
mark a change in campaign strategy. Though such protests have
occurred on many of his appearances, most of them have been ignored
or dismissed by the candidate.
   But the event Wednesday at the New Mexico state fair in
Albuquerque turned into a display of the senator's youthful
exuberance. His aides, who acknowledged that the senator had known
the protesters would be present, appeared delighted with the
results.
   ``He just decided to take them on,'' said David Prosperi,
Quayle's spokesman.
   The Indiana senator, who had his first press conference today
since Sept. 1, has had little spontaneous contact with the media
this week during his Midwestern campaign swing.
   Instead, his media events have been limited to the staged
rallies such as those Wednesday in New Mexico and Colorado.
   In Albuquerque, Quayle was serenaded by a pair of Mexican-garbed
balladeers and heralded by a mariache band before he rose to
address a rally of several hundred state fair goers.
   Dozens of people holding Dukakis signs began chanting: ``Go home
Quayle!'' in the most vociferous protests Quayle has faced recently.
   Some held signs reading, ``Quayle Stayed Home to Feather His
Nest'' and ``Quayle Ducked Vietnam,'' a reference to allegations
Quayle pulled strings to get into the National Guard and avoid
combat in Vietnam 20 years ago.
   ``As you listen to this babble over here, you can't help but
think of the Dukakis positions,'' Quayle told the crowd. ``They
have no positions. They're loud but they don't have any ideas.''
   As his supporters cheered, Quayle warmed to the theme, his voice
growing hoarser as he shouted over the chants: ``I'm just beginning
to have fun!''
   ``They have the freedom of speech but so do we and speak we
will,'' he said.
   He denounced the Democrats and their supporters as the ``party
of doom.''
   ``All they can do is say no,'' he said.
   Asked by reporters later if he thought he overreacted to the
crowd, Quayle said, ``No ... We had a good discussion. They have
their right to free speech and so do we.''
   At an earlier rally in Colorado Springs, Colo., Quayle also ran
into hecklers. He said they ``keep walking around in circles''
while ``we have a message to talk about.''
   Quayle's message this week has been to portray Dukakis as
wrongheaded on matters of defense and national security.
   He told a Denver audience that Wednesday's test-launching by the
Soviets of an SS-25 mobile intercontinental ballistic missile
showed the United States needs to develop mobile strategic
missiles, something he said would never happen under Dukakis.
   The Soviets have two mobile ICBM missiles, the SS-25 and the
SS-24.
   The United States does not have mobile intercontinental
ballistic missiles, although two such missiles _ the Midgetman and
the Rail Mobile MX _ have been under development. U.S.
intercontinental ballistic missiles presently are in concrete silos
buried in the ground.
   Dukakis ``is opposing modernization of our land-based missile
force, while the Soviets are already ahead of us,'' Quayle said.
   ``The governor has already stated that he opposes flight testing
of our missiles so even if he wanted to develop a deterrent, his
flight test ban would prevent us from ensuring that the system
would work,'' Quayle said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
