<FILEID>AP-NR-09-15-88 1217EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w PM-MannasasBattlefield     09-15 0426</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Mannasas Battlefield,410</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Senate Panel OKs Plan to Acquire Shopping Mall Site</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RICHARD KEIL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Senate panel today voted to seize a
development site adjacent to the Manassas National Battlefield Park
in suburban Virginia, rejecting several compromise plans that would
have acquired only part of the parcel.
   The Energy and Natural Resources Committee approved a measure
that would authorize Congress to acquire the entire 542-acre
William Center Development tract, close two heavily-traveled
commuter routes running through the Civil War battlefield and pay
up to $30 million for construction of new roads around the park.
   The measure, introduced by Sen. Dale Bumpers, D-Ark., and
identical to a bill that passed the House by a 307-98 vote last
month, prevailed over a compromise measure by Sen. John Warner,
R-Va., that would have acquired just 80 acres of the tract. Warner
claimed that his proposal would preserve the most important
historical aspects of the site at a cheaper price.
   However, Bumpers maintained that the entire tract was
historically significant.
   ``If we don't act to preserve that property, you can go down
there three weeks from now, and it will be gone, for all intents
and purposes,'' Bumpers said in reference to the frenetic building
pace developer John T. Hazel is carrying out on the property.
``It'll be a shopping mall.''
   Warner estimated that his measure would cost only $20 million,
while estimates for the Bumpers proposal are $60 million or higher.
Sen. J. Bennett Johnston, D-La., the committee chairman, said he
hoped the bill would reach the Senate floor by next week.
   One potential hangup for the legislation is that it has not gone
through the normal budget process, and could be subject to a
parliamentary challenge on the Senate floor. If such a challenge
arises, 60 votes will be needed to override the procedural question.
   In addition, President Reagan has already threatened to veto any
legislation similar to the Bumpers bill.
   Hazel is planning to build a 1.2 million square-foot shopping
mall, 1.7 million square feet of office space, and 560 homes
adjacent to the 4,200-acre park. Historians claim that the
development, which traffic experts say would generate 80,000 cars
per day, would ruin the historic integrity of the still-rustic
ground on which the First and Second Battles of Manassas were
fought.
   In addition, the development site includes a hill from which
Confederate Gen. Robert E. Lee commanded his troops in Second
Manassas. Historians also claim that Union and Confederate dead lie
in unmarked graves scattered throughout the development area.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
