<1ST_LINE>u p PM-DelawareRecount 2ndLd-Writethru a0585 09-15 0331</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Delaware Recount, 2nd Ld - Writethru, a0585,0334</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Woo Squeezes Out Win in Delaware's Senate Primary Race</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS with 8 grafs to UPDATE with candidates' comments today;
PICKS UP 7th graf pvs, `Beard, a ...'</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By THERESA HUMPHREY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW CASTLE, Del. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Lt. Gov. S.B. Woo squeezed out a 71-vote
victory today in a recount in Delaware's Democratic U.S. Senate
primary race, five days after a clerical error left his opponent
claiming to be the winner.
   Woo and his challenger, civil activist Samuel S. Beard,
requested the recount after it was discovered Monday that 2,800
more votes than were actually cast in Saturday's primary had been
credited to Beard.
   Beard had claimed victory after the polls closed, thinking he
had received 22,418 votes to Woo's 19,624.
   But a two-day recount completed early today gave Woo 20,225
votes to Beard's 20,154.
   Woo will challenge Republican U.S. Sen. William V. Roth Jr. in
November. Roth, who had no primary opponent, is seeking a fourth
term.
   ``I know I gave the most upbeat concession speech in the history
of American politics,'' Beard, referring to his remarks over the
weekend, said in conceding today.
   Woo said he lived up to his nickname of ``Landslide Woo,''
conferred after he won the race for lieutenant governor four years
ago by fewer than 500 votes.
   Woo, a 51-year-old physics professor at the University of
Delaware, was elected lieutenant governor in his first bid for
public office. He is the highest ranking Chinese-American in state
government in the United States.
   Beard, a 49-year-old millionaire who inherited his wealth, had
the backing of party loyalists and labor. He has served as chairman
for job creation commissions under the past four presidents.
   The 2,800-vote mistake occurred in a district in New Castle
County where about 280 Democrats are registered. Beard received 28
votes there, but a computer operator recorded the votes as 2,828 at
the county's department of elections, according to the county
elections director.
</TEXT>
