<1ST_LINE>r a PM-TrainDerailment     09-15 0180</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Train Derailment,0190</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Derailed Tankers Cause Respiratory Problems, Major Traffic Tie-Ups</HEAD>
<DATELINE>JACKSONVILLE, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Twenty-seven freight cars derailed in
a sparsely populated area early today, spilling a corrosive
chemical, and four police officers were taken to the hospital with
respiratory problems, authorities said.
   The 40-car train, which originated in New Orleans, was traveling
about 60 mph when it derailed, said CSX Corp. spokesman Lindsey
Leckie. Twenty-two of the derailed cars were loaded.
   One leaking car contained pulp mill liquor, a byproduct of pulp
mill operations; the other contained potassium hydroxide, a
corrosive chemical used in electroplating and the manufacture of
soap and varnish remover, officials said.
   The four officers were taken to area hospitals for tests.
   ``When we first came on the scene there was a lot of smoke and
all kinds of fumes coming out of there,'' said police Capt. J.C.
Green.
   Police said the cause of the 2 a.m. derailment was not known.
   CSX said propane would be transferred out of another derailed
car later today.
   Green said there were virtually no homes in the area.
</TEXT>
