<FILEID>AP-NR-09-15-88 1251EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-EasternMachinists     09-15 0249</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Eastern Machinists,0254</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Voting Begins On Contract Offer</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Eastern Airlines Machinists on Thursday began
voting on a contract offer seeking $161 million in wage cuts.
   Eastern is seeking cuts of 10 percent to 20 percent for
mechanics and sharper cuts for the less-skilled workers. A
maintenance worker with three years' seniority, for example, would
be cut from $13.47 an hour to $6.72 an hour. The offer would also
cut vacation time and other benefits.
   The company and its largest union have been in mediation since
January. Eastern wants the mediator to declare an impasse, leading
to a 30-day cooling-off period management said would spur a
settlement. The union believes the company wants a strike.
   The Machinists leadership scheduled the vote on the contract
offer to rebut management claims it doesn't represent rank-and-file
sentiments in negotiations. Management has said the contract vote
is another delaying tactic.
   The Machinists still represent nearly one-third of Eastern
employees, but the union and company estimate its current numbers
at about 9,000, possibly below that, because of layoffs, firings
and attrition. The union had 13,000 members when the Texas Air
Corp. took over two years ago.
   The members put their votes in sealed envelopes and turn them
into their union stewards, who will send them to union
headquarters, general Chairman Roy Anderson said.
   Workers at other company bases began voting Thursday, while
Miami-based union employees will vote Monday. The Machinists' union
office said the votes will be tallied here Sept. 23.
</TEXT>
