<FILEID>AP-NR-09-15-88 1253EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w PM-Hurricane-Aid 1stLd-Writethru a0485 09-15 0630</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Hurricane-Aid, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0485,620</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Pentagon, Private Groups Offering Help In Hurricane Areas</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: First 8 grafs new, picking up 2nd graf pvs, The American</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By JENNIFER DIXON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Trucks, equipment and personnel from two dozen
federal agencies are standing ready to respond along the Texas
coast if Hurricane Gilbert comes ashore there, officials said today.
   ``It's fair to say that we recognize that we face the greatest
weather threat we have ever faced in our part of the country. We
want to be certain our preparation is up to the challenge,'' Sen.
Phil Gramm, R-Texas, told a briefing at the Federal Emergency
Management Agency, which coordinates disaster assistance.
   Gramm and FEMA official Grant Peterson said the paperwork has
been prepared so that President Reagan can immediately declare a
disaster and set in motion relief efforts.
   ``We are taking the hurricane very, very seriously, as we would
urge all of the citizens in the area'' to do, Peterson said.
   Maj. Gen. J.D. Smith of the Defense Department said the Pentagon
has streamlined its procedures to ensure that ``this is not a
bureaucratic, slow-moving turtle.''
   Peterson said trucks at FEMA's Denton, Texas, regional
headquarters are loaded down with gear such as communications
equipment and electric generators and are prepared to move as soon
as needed.
   He and Gramm said federal agencies will be dispatching
Spanish-speaking personnel and Spanish-language forms and pamphlets
to help communication with the large Hispanic population along the
coast.
   Private groups were also joining in the relief effort.
   The American Red Cross said Wednesday it had begun sending
emergency supplies to four hurricane ``watch'' districts being
established at several Texas cities.
   The Red Cross said thousands of blankets, cots, comfort kits and
cleanup kits were on their way to Corpus Christi, Harlingen,
Houston and Beaumont, Texas. In addition, volunteers and staff
members have been sent to San Antonio, Texas, and Birmingham, Ala.
which have been established as staging areas for deployment after
the storm hits.
   Gramm said Wednesday that an undetermined number of active duty
military personnel and equipment, including trucks, helicopters and
bulldozers, would be sent from Fort Hood in Killeen, Texas, and
possibly Fort Bliss in El Paso, he said.
   Gramm also announced that the Army Corps of Engineers had opened
an emergency office in Galveston to handle flood control and
emergency construction along the coast.
   ``The idea is the better organized we are in advance of the
potential dangers of the hurricane, the less we will have in terms
of property damage and personal injury,'' he said.
   Separately, the Agency for International Development said the
United States was sending $396,000 worth of relief supplies to
Jamaica, including 360 rolls of plastic sheeting, 200 tents, 3,966
water jugs, 18 water tanks, 10 chain saw kits and 9,600 cotton
blankets.
   A portion of the assistance was flown by the military from a
U.S. stockpile in Panama on Wednesday.
   Partners of the Americas, a group of 60 countries including the
United States and nations in Latin America and the Caribbean,
announced it had set up a special relief fund to help the people of
Jamaica and Mexico's Yucatan Peninsula.
   The group is seeking cash donations to purchase ``roofing
materials, plastic sheeting, strong soaps, disinfectants,
mattresses, beds and bed linens,'' said William Reese, president of
the group which was established in 1964 as part of the Alliance for
Progress.
   The group is not in a position to accept clothing or food
donations, Reese said.
   Individuals interested in contributing to either relief effort
can do so through their local Red Cross chapter or send donations
to:
   _The American Red Cross, P.O. Box 37243, Washington, D.C. 20013
and
   _Partners of the Americas, Hurricane Gilbert Relief Fund, 1424 K
St., N.W., Suite 700, Washington, D.C. 20005.
</TEXT>
