<FILEID>AP-NR-09-15-88 1259EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w AM-ToyDanger     09-15 0188</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Toy Danger,190</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Customs-CPSC Seize Dangerous Toys</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   With the Christmas season approaching federal
officials said Thursday that they are intensifying their efforts to
block the importation of dangerous toys.
   The crackdown is a joint effort of the Consumer Product Safety
Commission and the Customs Service.
   ``We are serving notice to importers and foreign toy
manufacturers that the commission and the Customs Service will not
tolerate violative toys being shipped into U.S. commerce,'' said
Terrence M. Scanlon, chairman of the safety agency.
   So far this year the two agencies have blocked the entry of
478,000 toys with a retail value of $1.37 million, Scanlon reported.
   Most imports enter the country in September through November in
anticipation of the holiday toy-buying season, he said. Thus, the
two agencies are looking closer at imported toys during this
season, with a particular emphasis on toys with small parts that
may present a choking hazard and high lead levels in paint.
   The joint operation is concentrated in major importing ports,
officials said, including Atlanta, Baltimore, New York, Chicago,
Los Angeles, Miami, San Francisco, Seattle, Charleston, S.C. and
Savannah, Ga.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
