<HEAD>Judge to Hear Arguments over Cheever Stories</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Opening statements began today in a contract
dispute over publication of a collection of short stories by the
late John Cheever.
   A federal judge in New York last month halted publication of the
book, ``Uncollected Short Stories of John Cheever,'' pending
resolution of the dispute between Cheever's widow, Mary, and the
publisher, Academy Chicago Ltd.
   Academy is asking state court to uphold its 1987 contract with
Mrs. Cheever, who contends the publisher misled her on who would
have control over the book's contents.
   Mrs. Cheever, who lives in Ossining, N.Y., a New York City
suburb, was not on hand for opening statements. Judge Roger Kiley
is presiding in the non-jury trial.
   Mrs. Cheever says the book would have horrified her husband, who
won the 1979 Pulitzer Prize for fiction, because it includes early
work that was not up to his later standards. Cheever died in 1982.
   The book includes 68 stories written between 1930 and 1981.
