<FILEID>AP-NR-09-15-88 1318EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w AM-FactoryUse     09-15 0438</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Factory Use,380</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Industrial Operating Rate Rises with Summer Surge at Utilities</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Economy Bjt</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserGraphic</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVE SKIDMORE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The U.S. industrial operating rate rose for
the fifth consecutive month in August, but economists played down
the inflationary effect of the increase because it was entirely
attributable to a temporary summer surge at utilities.
   The Federal Reserve Board said Thursday that the nation's
factories, mines and utilities operated at 83.7 percent of capacity
last month, a 0.1 percentage point increase over July, when the
rate had risen a sharp 0.6 percent.
   It was the fifth consecutive increase and the highest rate in
more than eight years. Industry last operated at 83.7 percent of
capacity in March 1980.
   Economists believe an overall operating rate approaching 85
percent signals higher prices as industry strains to meet demand.
   The operating rate at utilities jumped by 1.7 percentage points
in August to 82.4 percent. The rate at plants churning out
electricity to meet the demand of air conditioners during the
summer heat wave soared 1.9 percentage points to 86.9 percent, the
highest since 1979.
   However, analysts expect the strain on utilities to ease as the
weather cools and they pointed to a slight decline in the operating
rate in the closely-watched manufacturing sector _ the first since
February _ as the more significant number in Thursday's report.
   Overall, the manufacturing rate eased from 83.9 percent in July
to 83.8 percent in August.
   The rate at factories making durable goods, ``big ticket'' items
expected to last three or more years, held steady at 82.3 percent
in August, while the rate at factories producing non-durable goods
fell from 86.1 percent in July to 85.9 percent.
   ``I think industrial capacity has peaked. That's the highest
it's going to get for awhile,'' said Michael K. Evans, a private
economist in Washington. ``That's good news for inflation
fighters.''
   Evans said the export boom of the past year, which has pushed
manufacturing operating rates up by 2.3 percentage points since
August 1987, is starting to wane.
   ``Exports are still growing, but at a more normal pace,'' he
said.
   Durable goods manufacturing held steady despite a 0.5 percentage
point jump in operating rates at steel and other metal
manufacturing plants. The August level, 91 percent, was 8
percentage points higher than a year ago.
   However, rates at auto plants fell to 70.4 percent last month,
down from 71.4 percent in July and a peak this year of 75.3 percent
in June.
   The rate for the mining sector, which includes oil and gas
drilling, fell from 83.0 percent in July to 82.9 percent.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
