<1ST_LINE>u p PM-Bush 4thLd-Writethru a0617 09-15 0821</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Bush, 4th Ld-Writethru, a0617,770</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Bush Calls Dukakis `Olympic' Spender</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: INSERT new grafs 13-14 to restore Field poll, bgng ``A
newly...; Note a0617 should have been designated 3rd Ld-Writethru</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By RITA BEAMISH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SAN FRANCISCO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Republican George Bush today ripped into
Michael Dukakis' economic record as governor and said the
Democrat's pledge to do for the nation what he did for
Massachusetts sounds ``like a threat.''
   Bush told a packed ballroom breakfast at the Commonwealth Club
that Dukakis has presided over an era when Massachusetts ``taxing
and spending has increased more than in any other state.''
   ``My opponent still says he wants to `do for the nation what he
has done for Massachusetts.' That slogan is beginning to sound more
and more like a threat,'' he said.
   Bush challenged Dukakis to state whether he would repeal the
Reagan administration's 1981 tax cuts.
   `If he thinks they were such a bad idea, does he plan to repeal
the 25 percent tax cuts which I supported for the American people?
I think the American people have a right to know,'' Bush said.
   Bush ridiculed the Dukakis claim of an economic Massachusetts
miracle, saying the state ``has turned a surplus into a growing
budget deficit.''
   ``If this were the Olympics, his composite score would make him
the gold medal winner in the tax-and-spend competition,'' Bush said.
   On Wednesday night, Bush told a $1,000-a-person fund-raiser that
he he is the candidate capable of bringing the nation's current
peace and prosperity into the next decade.
   ``It is legitimate to ask what is the end purpose of economic
growth. Is it just to be rich? What a shallow ambition. Is there
really any satisfaction to be had in being the fattest country?''
   He said prosperity would bring ``greater strides in the arts and
sciences and things of the spirit but it also means just giving a
helping hand to a fellow citizen who needs it.''
   In unusually poetic comments, Bush sought to elaborate on his
vow to make America ``a kinder, gentler nation,'' a phrase he used
in his acceptance speech at the Republican National Convention last
month.
   He told the gathering he is ``almost haunted by the lives being
lead by the children of our inner cities.'' But he said government
can't solve their problems and that he hoped as president he could
be ``a gentle persuader to rally our people to help our children.''
   A newly published poll completed Sept. 12 showed that Bush had
overcome a deficit of 16 percentage points in late July and was
running neck-and-neck with Dukakis in California.
   According to the California Poll released Thursday, Dukakis'
lead of 52 percent to 36 percent over Bush six weeks ago had shrunk
to 46 percent to 45 percent, which is a tie within the poll's 4
percent margin of error. Poll director Mervin Field called it ``a
phenomenal reversal'' but cautioned that ``people can easily change
their minds.''
   As he spoke at the fund-raiser held at the luxury St. Francis
hotel, about 400 demonstrators gathered across the street in Union
Square. Some pushed over police barricades, spilling out into the
street, stopping automobile traffic and the city's famed cable cars.
   The protesters chanted ``Where's George'' and ``Money for AIDS,
stop the war, U.S. out of El Salvador.'' Police said at least one
person was arrested.
   At a colorful rally in Chinatown earlier in the evening, Bush
said voters must decide whether ``to keep going with the policies
that have launched the longest period of economic growth in history
or you can choose to go backward.''
   ``Only one man is pledged to build a better America through low
taxes and high opportunity, and only one man wants laws against
crime, tougher laws, and creative programs for our schools,'' Bush
told the raucous crowd. ``Only one person _ only one person can
carry America's peace and prosperity into the 1990s.
   ``I am here to tell you that I am that man,'' Bush said.
   The vice president received a blessing from a Buddhist monk
described as ``the Great Master,'' and watched as young men dressed
in costumes of yellow and red dancing dragons made their way
through the city streets.
   Bush supporters outnumbered the noisy hecklers, who chanted
``down with Bush,'' and carried signs opposing offshore oil
drilling. Some Democrats in the crowd distributed fortune cookies
with messages reading, ``Vote Dukakis,'' and ``Where was George?''
_ a refrain from the Democratic National Convention.
   California, with the largest number of electoral votes _ 47 _ is
a key battleground, and Bush is spending two and a half days
campaigning in the state.
   Earlier, at a rally in Fresno at Sun-Maid Growers, a cooperative
of 1,500 raisin growers in the San Joaquin Valley, Bush accused
Dukakis of using the phrase ``economic patriotism'' as ``a code
word for protectionism.''
   ``We will not have it,'' he told the rally of several hundred
people.
</TEXT>
