<HEAD>Escaping East German Shot After Swimming To West</HEAD>
<DATELINE>HANOVER, West Germany (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An escaping East German man was
shot and critically wounded Thursday after he reached West German
territory by swimming the Elbe River, police said.
   It was not immediately known who fired the shot, which wounded
the man in the chest as he reached the riverbank.
   Although communist East German border troops have fired on
people fleeing to the West, there have been no recent shooting
incidents along the heavily fortified border.
   Police said the man escaped near the town of Alt Garge, about 30
miles southeast of Hamburg, where the Elbe river forms the border
between the two German states.
   West German border police in Hanover said in a statement that
the 19-year-old man was already on West German territory when he
felt something hit his chest.
   Residents living near the scene told police they heard two shots
fired at about 8:15 a.m. They took the injured man to a nearby
hospital where he was listed in critical condition.
   The man's name and other details were not released in accordance
with West German practice.
   Police said the prosecutor's office in the nearby district
capital of Lueneburg began an investigation.
   More than 300 East Germans have escaped across
communist-constructed border fortifications into West Germany or
West Berlin this year.
</TEXT>
