<DOCNO> AP880915-0121 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-09-15-88 1352EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-FiringLawsuits     09-15 0393</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Firing Lawsuits,0403</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Wrongful Termination Lawsuits Increasing, Think Tank Study Says</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SANTA MONICA, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Employees are more likely to sue now
when they've been fired than they were at the start of the decade,
according to a study released Thursday.
   The average employee's initial demand was slightly less than the
average payment after trial, and businesses, considering legal
expenses only, would be better off paying initial demands rather
than going to trial, the study said.
   The study was conducted by James N. Dertouzos, Elaine Holland
and Patricia Ebener of the Rand Corp.'s Institute for Civil
Justice. Rand is a non-profit, private think-tank that analyzes
national security and public welfare issues.
   The researchers reviewed nationwide case law and trial patterns
through January 1987, sampled Los Angeles Superior Court filings
since 1980 and analyzed California trials from 1980 to 1986.
   Trials were 2{ times more likely in California, Indiana,
Massachusetts, Montana and North Dakota, which Rand described as
the five states with the most liberal interpretations of the law.
   The study found that in Los Angeles Superior Court alone,
wrongful termination lawsuits grew from 90 in 1980 to 600 in 1986.
   The researchers found in the California cases that initial jury
awards averaged $650,000 but that figure was inflated by a few
multimillion-dollar judgments. The median award was $177,000.
However, post-trial reductions in jury awards to successful
plaintiffs averaged 45 percent.
   The typical California plaintiff was: 45 years old, eight years
of seniority and yearly earnings of $36,000. More than 89 percent
of plaintiffs were white, and nearly 69 percent were men. Middle
managers accounted for 39.8 percent of filings compared to 13.6
percent by executives.
   In 80.6 percent of firings the employers claimed inadequate
performance. External economic factors were cited in the other
discharges.
   Jury awards rose with the plaintiff's age, peaking at age 50.
Women's awards appeared to be ``considerably lower'' than men's,
the study found.
   Dertouzos concluded: ``Unless you have a very good case, don't
bother. Very few people are getting big payments. If you deserve to
be fired, the likelihood of getting big money is very small.''
   Attorneys collected 40 percent of plaintiffs' winnings, the
study found, and in California that meant the average lawyer's
share was $81,000. Lawyers for both sides collectively pocketed 60
percent of the money changing hands in wrongful discharge cases,
the study said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880915-0122 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-09-15-88 1412EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Burma     09-15 0547</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Burma,0568</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Militant Students Ask American Embassy For Arms</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SEIN WIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>RANGOON, Burma (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Tens of thousands of demonstrators crowded
the streets of the capital Thursday to demand democracy. Sources
said the U.S. Embassy refused student leaders' requests for weapons
but offered moral support.
   Hundreds of soldiers joined the protesters, who included
homeless and handicapped people and demonstrators on hunger strikes.
   Police shot at looters and killed two people, official Radio
Rangoon said. Food is in diminishing supply as trasportation
strikes restrict deliveries to the capital.
   The almost daily protests have been peaceful since hard-line
President Sein Lwin resigned Aug. 12 and security forces returned
to their barracks. But in recent days, protesters have become more
aggressive, shouting death threats at officials of President Maung
Maung's government.
   ``(Government officials) run or we will kill you!'' some
protesters shouted on Wednesday when more than 100,000 people took
to the streets.
   The government said it would end one-party rule and hold the
first multiparty elections since 1960, possibly as soon as late
October. The opposition rejected the proposal, saying it needed
time to organize and raise funds and did not trust the government
to run fair elections.
   Among the protesters Thursday was a one-legged man with a crutch
who led about 50 other ill-clad men carrying a banner that read:
``Pavement Dwellers, Suicide Squad.''
   ``We are prepared to die for democracy. We have nothing to
lose,'' he told a reporter.
   The students who went to the American Embassy Wednesday said
5,000 protesters were ready to take up arms, said sources who spoke
on conditon of anonymity. An embassy official told the students the
United States could offer them only moral support, said the
sources. The embassy had no comment.
   At least 500 soldiers joined the demonstrators Sept. 9, some
disillusioned with the high standard of living of senior officers
and the army's outdated weapons.
   Rangoon newspapers said Capt. Sai Win Kyaw of the 22nd Light
Infantry Brigade told reporters Wednesday that the government
exploited the army, and he called on all soldiers to resign.
   About 75 people ended a 48-hour hunger strike Thursday morning
outside city hall, and more than 90 others began a 72-hour fast.
More than 1,000 schoolchildren completed a 36-hour hunger strike on
Monday night.
   State-run Radio Rangoon said one person was killed late
Wednesday when guards fired on about 150 people looting a rice
warehouse in the city's port area. Another person was killed early
Thursday when he joined a group trying to break into a medical
school in Rangoon.
   Guards have killed several other people in recent weeks as food
and other supplies continue to dwindle and looting has increased.
   Burma's last multiparty elections, on Feb. 6, 1960, swept former
Prime Minister U Nu to power.
   U Nu was toppled in the 1962 coup led by Ne Win, who outlawed
all political parties except his Burma Socialist Program Party and
pursued policies that made resource-rich Burma one of the world's
poorest nations.
   Massive protests began after Ne Win resigned July 23 and the
party named hardliner Sein Lwin his successor. Sein Lwin resigned
17 days later after rioting killed at least 112 people in Rangoon.
On Aug. 19, Maung Maung became Burma's first civilian leader since
U Nu.
</TEXT>
