<HEAD>McCarthy Calls For Abolition of Vice Presidency</HEAD>
<DATELINE>FARMINGTON, Maine (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Former Sen. Eugene McCarthy, D-Minn., a
perennial presidential contender, says the vice presidency should
be abolished because the office ``clutters up the campaign.''
   MCarthy, speaking at the University of Maine at Farmington on
Wednesday, said the vice presidency puts people in line for the
presidency who don't belong there, such as Dan Quayle, Richard M.
Nixon and Spiro Agnew.
   McCarthy accused Quayle, the current Republican vice
presidential candidate, of ``double hypocrisy'' for serving in the
National Guard during the Vietnam War. He said Quayle was a
``militarist hiding out in the military.''
