<HEAD>A Record 13,000 Acres Of Smuggler's Land Seized</HEAD>
<DATELINE>INDIANTOWN, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The government says it has confiscated
more than 13,000 acres of ranch land belonging to a drug smuggler
in the biggest such seizure in U.S. history.
   The land seized Wednesday was valued at $35 million and was
owned by Frank Brady, whom investigators have linked to the
Medellin cartel of Colombia responsible for 80 percent of the
cocaine brought into the United States.
   ``All the properties seized today were utilized in drug
trafficking,'' said U.S. Attorney Dexter Lehtinen. He said the
seizure is the country's biggest.
   U.S. marshals seized three central Florida tracts of more than
4,300 acres each.
   One tract has an airstrip with radio-controlled lights to
acccommodate landings at night or in bad weather.
   Brady was sentenced to 10 years in prison in 1986 for smuggling
3,000 pounds of marijuana through his private resort in the Bahamas
and property in Astatula, near Orlando.
   He was once one of the FBI's Ten Most Wanted but became an
informant who helped convict 11 people of smuggling drugs through
his ranch here.
   Brady earlier forfeited at least $5.6 million in cash and
property.
