<1ST_LINE>r a AM-Hurricane-Cattle     09-15 0258</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Hurricane-Cattle,0266</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Cattlemen Move Pure-Breds to Higher Ground</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GUY COATES</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CAMERON, La. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   It was an impromptu cattle roundup, pitting
stubborn steers against cattlemen eager to get their most valuable
assets out of town, away from Hurricane Gilbert's fury.
   As Gilbert crossed into the Gulf of Mexico, the cattle drive
began in earnest. The caravan jammed two-lane Louisiana 27, the
major highway leading out of coastal Cameron Parish, with trucks
ranging from pickups carrying two animals to 18-wheelers hauling
double-deck trailers with 50 head.
   Even Francis Bride, a Lake Charles physician, got into the act
Wednesday, helping to shove the rump of a balky steer into the rear
of an already crowded trailer.
   But that's how important cattle are in the parish, a thin layer
of lush marsh just above sea level in western Louisiana that has
been a frequent front door for hurricanes over theyears. The parish
boasts about 5,000 head of cattle, many of them registered
pure-breds.
   ``We've learned and now we move the registered stuff as the
hurricane season starts each year, and don't bring them back until
the season ends,'' said Jamey Guthrie, a cattleman also helping
Bride and others.
   It was a 1957 hurricane, Audrey, that taught the parish that
valuable lesson. Audrey left over 400 people dead and wiped out the
region's cattle industry.
   Bride, who also owns cattle in Cameron, said most of the stock
being moved at the last minute was ``commercial stuff.''
   ``We'll be working all night to get them out,'' he said.
</TEXT>
