<1ST_LINE>r i AM-BankHostages     09-15 0415</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Bank Hostages,0425</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Bank Hostages Freed In Britain, Robbers Escape</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PRESTON, England (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Armed robbers abducted a bank manager
and his family, locked more than 60 people in the bank's vaults and
escaped with hundreds of thousands of dollars Thursday, police said.
   Police marksmen, unaware the robbers had fled, burst into the
National Westminster Bank in this northwestern town at noon and
freed the unharmed employees, said Chief Inspector Bill Caine of
the Lancashire Constabulary.
   Police launched a national search for the four robbers.
   Twenty police marksmen ringed the four-story bank building in
the town's center for more than two hours, backed up by 100 other
officers and a fleet of 12 ambulances. Businesses in the area were
ordered closed and evacuated.
   ``We believed the gang was armed and (we) surrounded the
building with armed officers,'' Caine said. ``No shots were fired
at any time during the incident.''
   Detective Superintendent Barrie Walmsley told a news conference
that bank manager Roger Ball, 43, his wife, Jean, and their
13-year-old daughter Vanessa were abducted and held hostage for
more than 16 hours.
   Walmsley said the ordeal began at 6 p.m. Wednesday when Ball
left the bank. He was grabbed by two masked men, blindfolded, bound
and gagged and thrown into the back of a van.
   Ball was driven to his home where four men held him, his wife,
and daughter until 4 a.m. Thursday. The three were then bound,
gagged and hooded, put in the trunks of two vehicles and driven to
the town center, where they were held in an empty store near the
bank, Walmsley said.
   Shortly after 9 a.m., Ball was told to enter the bank, inform
the 60 employees that a robbery would soon took place, and order
them to gather in underground vaults, Walmsley said.
   Ball told them his family was being threatened, and the
employees complied, police said. Gang members armed with sawed-off
shotguns and hand guns held the employees ``at threat,'' while
others stole the money, police said.
   Caine said police learned of the robbery when Mrs. Ball managed
to smash a window in the store where she and her daughter were
being held and alert passersby at about 9:45 a.m. He said customers
and security staff also contacted police when the bank did not open
as scheduled at 10 a.m.
   Caine said police marksmen entered the building, believing the
robbers were still inside, about 12:30 after obtaining a duplicate
set of keys from the bank's head office.
</TEXT>
