<1ST_LINE>u i PM-Pope 3rdLd-Writethru   09-15 0747</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Pope, 3rd Ld-Writethru,a0608,0763</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Pope Resumes Schedule with Beatification Ceremony</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS with 3 grafs to CORRECT that passenger, not bus driver,
died today. Pick up 4th graf pvs: `The pope...'</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By DENNIS REDMONT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MASERU, Lesotho (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Pope John Paul II said today he was
saddened by the bloodshed that occurred during a shootout between
police and guerrillas that ended the hijacking of a busload of
pilgrims on their way to see him.
   All four gunmen and two of the hostages on the bus _ a
14-year-old girl and a 55-year-old man _ died from the Wednesday
night gun battle, the state-run South Africa Broadcasting Corp.
said.
   Three gunman and the schoolgirl died during the shootout, while
the fourth hijacker and the other passenger died today from
injuries, the SABC reported. Twenty pilgrims, including two nuns,
were injured in the shooting, papal officials said.
   The pope made his first public comment on the incident at the
end of a Mass he celebrated today to beatify a French evangelist.
Two million worshipers had been expected to attend the Mass at a
race course, but only 50,000 turned up in damp chilly weather.
   ``I have come to southern Africa as a pilgrim of peace, bearing
with me a message of reconciliation,'' the pontiff said. ``I am
saddened to learn that others on their way to join me in this
pilgrimage have been the victims of a hijack that caused such
anguish and ended in bloodshed.''
   Later the pope visited the Queen Elizabeth II hospital and met
with several of the injured.
   One of the hostages, French-Canadian nun Favrea Blanche told The
Star, a Johannesburg daily, that the shootout lasted 15 minutes and
that the hijackers had behaved politely and said they wanted peace
in Lesotho.
   The gunmen were from the dissident Lesotho Liberation Army and
had demanded a meeting with the pope and Lesotho's King Moshoeshoe
II, officials said.
   ``They spoke gently with us,'' said Sister Blanche, 63, who has
lived in Lesotho for 37 years. ``They even had pills to treat
people with headaches and tummy problems.''
   The pope resumed his five-nation southern Africa tour after a
dramatic day in which bad weather forced the papal plane to divert
to Johannesburg in South Africa, which the pontiff had been trying
to avoid.
   A heavily guarded 10-vehicle convoy took the pope to Lesotho by
road through South Africa, where racial issues had led Catholic
bishops to advise against a papal visit. Minutes after John Paul
reached Maseru, shooting broke out between police and gunmen
holding about 70 Catholic pilgrims hostage in a bus in the capital.
   ``One of our students is dead,'' said Sister Rita Brassard, an
American with the Papal Visit Office.
   ``Survivors said there were bullets everywhere. These little
grenades went off. They tried to jump through the windows,'' she
said.
   South African police, invited by Lesotho's military government,
led the assault against the gunmen after the hijackers started
shooting and tried to drive the bus into the grounds of the British
High Commission, or embassy. One gunman was taken alive. The
hijackers had complained that Britain was training Lesotho's
security forces.
   Vatican spokesman Joaquim Navarro said the pope learned of the
shooting after he returned from an evening Mass in a small church
at the tomb of the Rev. Joseph Gerard, at Roma outside Maseru.
   The ceremony to beatify Father Gerard, the first step toward
sainthood, took place under a cliff overlooking a large meadow at
the edge the city. Cows grazed in some areas cordoned off for
worshipers.
   Catholic officials said they believed cool and cloudy weather,
news of the bus hijack and the cost of temporary housing in Maseru
had cut the numbers of pilgrims far below expectations. Some tents
erected for worshipers were rented for $20 a night _ a huge sum for
many Africans.
   Father Gerard was a missionary in southern Africa in the 19th
century and was the first to take the Catholic faith to the Basotho
people. Before his death in 1914, he met little success in changing
tribal customs of polygamy and traditional medicine. He failed to
convert Moshoeshoe I, the Basotho king.
   Miracles were reported after Gerard died in 1914. A young girl
placed soil from his grave around her neck and reportedly was cured
of blindness in 1928. King Moshoeshoe II, whom John Paul was to
meet later Thursday, is a Catholic and 40 percent of Lesotho's 1.6
million people are Catholics.
</TEXT>
