<1ST_LINE>r p AM-Carter-Pledge     09-15 0297</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Carter-Pledge,290</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Carter Says Pledge Of Allegiance Flap is Non-Issue</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Former President Jimmy Carter, taking issue with
Republican campaign attacks centered on the Pledge of Allegiance,
says he respects the flag but probably would refuse to recite the
pledge if ordered to do so by the government.
   Republican presidential nominee George Bush has criticized
Democratic nominee Michael Dukakis, the governor of Massachusetts,
for vetoing a proposed law that would have required teachers to
lead students in the flag pledge.
   Carter, in remarks to students Wednesday night at Emory
University where he is a professor, said the issue is an important
one for Dukakis.
   ``I think Dukakis was taken aback, caught by surprise, that he
didn't know what to do. I think he is in a hole now,'' said Carter,
a co-chairman of Dukakis' Georgia campaign. ``If he can explain it
away, it could give him a victory or it could cost him.''
   As for the issue itself, Carter said, ``I have great respect for
the flag, (but) if the government ... passed a law saying that I
had to pledge allegiance to the flag, I don't think I would do it.''
   He continued: ``I have always felt that I lived in a country ...
where if I wanted to worship God as a Baptist I could do so. If I
were an atheist, I could be one. If I wanted to be a Catholic but
was born a Jew, there's no condemnation ... from a government
authority.''
   Carter also expressed displeasure over the decision of his
former national security adviser, Zbigniew Brzezinski, to join the
Bush campaign as an adviser.
   ``I don't like it at all,'' Carter said, but he praised
Brzezinski for not criticizing Carter's policy after Carter left
the White House.
</TEXT>
