<1ST_LINE>r a AM-OlympicsReax     09-15 0355</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Olympics Reax,0371</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Surprise and Disappointment Give Way To Olympic Optimism</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PAUL JENKINS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ANCHORAGE, Alaska (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Anchorage learned Thursday it won't be
host for the 1994 Winter Olympic Games, but the city's failed bid
didn't stop some from dreaming about 1998.
   Hundreds of people jammed the Egan Civic & Convention Center to
watch the televised announcement of Lillehammer, Norway, as the
1994 host city.
   Anchorage finished third out of four competing bids. Two years
ago, the city finished sixth in a field of seven competing for the
1992 Games.
   ``We knew getting the bid would not be an easy task. We knew
that going in, but it would have been nice to have seen us place a
little higher,'' said Dennis Branson, a member of the Anchorage
Organizing Committee's executive panel.
   Branson said he hoped the committee will reorganize and prepare
for a 1998 Winter Olympic proposal.
   ``The third time's the charm,'' he said.
   Alaska Sen. Frank Murkowski, who headed the delegation lobbying
on Anchorage's behalf before the International Olympic Committee,
said in a telephone interview from South Korea that the city's two
bids would pay off.
   ``Anchorage is an odds-on favorite next time,'' he predicted.
``I think it's an investment. I'd be terribly disappointed if there
was any thought to not going full speed ahead in 1998.''
   Gov. Steve Cowper said he would make a push for a 1998 bid.
   ``Alaskans aren't quitters. We've got what it takes to make
dreams come true. Now let's get ready for 1998,'' he said.
   Anchorage voters last month voted 2-1 in favor of the city
assuming financial responsibility for the 1994 Winter Olympics.
   But not everybody was disappointed with the choice of
Lillehammer.
   Doug Bartko of Palmer is a spokesman for Alaskans Concerned
About The Proposed Winter Olympics, which doesn't oppose the
Olympics, only their being in Alaska.
   He said his group philosophically opposes the selection of
Anchorage. ``People live here to get away from the commercialism
and hype and there is a lot of that involved in the Olympics,'' he
said.
   ``I think Lillehammer is an excellent choice,'' Bartko said.
</TEXT>
