<1ST_LINE>u a AM-NewlywedsKilled     09-15 0298</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Newlyweds Killed,0309</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Guilty of Criminally Negligent Homicide</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MINEOLA, N.Y. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A man whose car crashed at high speed into
a wedding limousine, killing the bride, groom and best man, was
found guilty Thursday of three counts of criminally negligent
homicide.
   The victims' families burst into applause as the verdict was
read.
   Vincent Laezza, 21, of Selden, had also been charged with
manslaughter in the April 3, 1987, collision, but was acquitted of
that more serious charge.
   In addition to the criminally negligent homicide counts, Laezza
was convicted of one count of second-degree assault for seriously
injuring the bride's sister and attendant.
   He was acquitted of assault in the injuring of the limousine
driver.
   The maximum sentence for criminally negligent homicide is one
and one-third to four years in prison. The sentence for assault can
be 2{ to seven years.
   The crash killed Carol Zagorski Phillips and Peter Phillips less
than an hour after they were married, and Phillips' brother and
best man, John Phillips.
   Debra Zagorski, the bride's sister, and Thomas Quinn, the
limousine driver, were injured.
   The jury had listened to two weeks of testimony and had begun
deliberations Thursday morning.
   Laezza allegedly was drag racing at up to 100 mph in Lido Beach,
on Long Island, when his car hit the limousine broadside as it was
turning into the Sands Catering Hall for the wedding reception.
   The speed limit on Lido Boulevard was 35 mph, according to
prosecutor George Peck.
   Laezza was remanded to the Nassau County Jail, until his Oct. 14
sentencing. During trial, he had been free on $750,000 bail.
   During closing arguments Wednesday, Laezza's attorney, Eugene
Shaffer, had told the Nassau County jury that the limousine driver
caused the accident by making a sudden turn left, cutting across
Laezza's pathway.
</TEXT>
