<1ST_LINE>r i AM-AirShowCrash     09-15 0155</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Air Show Crash,0157</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Ramstein Disaster Toll Rises to 63 with Death of 64-Year-Old
German</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MAINZ, West Germany (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A 64-year-old West German man died
from severe burns, raising the death toll from last month's
Ramstein air show disaster to 63, a state official said Thursday.
   The victim died in a Stuttgart hospital late Wednesday, said
Juergen Dietzen, spokesman for Rhineland-Palatinate state.
   Dietzen said 153 people remained hospitalized in 46 hospitals as
a result of the Aug. 28 accident. He said at least 25 were in very
serious to critical condition.
   The accident occurred during a 10-airplane Italian Air Force
stunt team performance in which three of the jets collided. One of
the planes plowed into the crowd and exploded, and the other two
crashed a short distance away.
   The dead are 56 West Germans, a U.S. soldier and her 9-year-old
son, one French citizen, one Dutch citizen, and the three Italian
pilots.
</TEXT>
