<1ST_LINE>u p AM-Bentsen     09-15 0625</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Bentsen,590</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Bentsen Says GOP Barbs Are Backfiring, Democrats on Upswing</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Political Rdp Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By STEVEN KOMAROW</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SHREVEPORT, La. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Sen. Lloyd Bentsen said Thursday the
Republicans' negative campaign is backfiring and that the Democrats
are on the upswing.
   The Democratic vice presidential nominee, on a Southern campaign
swing through his native Texas, Louisiana and Tennessee, told a
rally in Shreveport, La., that GOP nominee George Bush had done
nothing for oil-producing states during his eight years as vice
president.
   ``In all candor, their energy policy is the political equivalent
of a dry hole,'' Bentsen said.
   Reciting several anti-energy positions taken by Bush and his
running mate, Dan Quayle, Bentsen mentioned Quayle's opposition to
an oil import fee, which Democratic nominee Michael Dukakis has
also opposed.
   A new Washington Post-ABC News poll showed the Democratic ticket
leading the Republicans nationwide by 48 percent to 45 percent.
Although the lead was within the survey's margin of error, Bentsen
said it reflected the Democrats' success in countering Republican
charges that they were unpatriotic and weak on defense.
   ``We've seen in the last four or five days, as we've taken these
issues on, on defense, and these ... outrageous charges on
patriotism, that the polls have turned around,'' Bentsen told
reporters. ``It's obvious that we have bottomed out and we're
beginning to come back up.''
   The Democrats grabbed a big lead in the polls after their
nominating convention in Atlanta in mid-July, but that lead
evaporated and they fell behind the Bush-Quayle ticket in some
recent polls.
   Bentsen said Republicans were trying to ``impugn the loyalty and
patriotism of the candidates'' but they had ``overreached and they
are getting a backlash.'' Bentsen said.
   ``I think they've got the problem now,'' said the senator, who
elicited a chorus of boos from his Shreveport audience when he
mentioned the GOP campaign.
   Bentsen was heckled Wednesday when he told defense workers near
Dallas that Bush had unfairly accused Dukakis of opposing most
defense programs.
   On the gun control issue, Bentsen defended Dukakis' position
while seeking to minimize his own differences with the
Massachusetts governor.
   Bentsen said he would vote against a proposed national,
mandatory seven-day waiting period for handgun purchases, which
Dukakis supports.
   ``I think that has some validity to it, but I believe it ought
to be done on a state-by-state basis because you have a great deal
of difference in the urbanization of various states,'' Bentsen told
reporters.
   ``What you might apply in Montana could be quite different from
a heavily urbanized, industrialized state that has different crime
problems,'' he said.
   Bentsen refused to say what he would do if he were elected vice
president and, as president of the Senate, had to break a tie floor
vote on the issue.
   But he said Dukakis was not the anti-gun fanatic that
Republicans claim he is.
   Although Dukakis supports gun registration and other
restrictions, ``he's a man who believes you ought to be able to own
a gun within the laws of your particular state'' to protect the
home and for hunting and recreational purposes, Bentsen said.
   ``The idea that he is going to confiscate guns without
compensation, as I read one of the charges _ that's ridiculous,''
he said.
   Bentsen's plan was to campaign in North Carolina and Florida on
Friday and Saturday and then return to Washington, but he might
alter his schedule because Hurricane Gilbert was headed toward the
Gulf Coast of Texas.
   He said he ruled out visiting Galveston, Texas, on Thursday to
view emergency preparations for the hurricane's arrival because he
did not want to contribute to the burden of local officials. But he
said he might return to his home state after the storm to assess
relief needs.
</TEXT>
