<1ST_LINE>r w AM-US-Soviet     09-15 0462</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-US-Soviet,450</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>U.S. Faults Soviets For Slow Progress Toward Arms Reduction
Negotiations</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BARRY SCHWEID</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Diplomatic Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The State Department acknowledged Thursday
that after 19 months of trying to set up negotiations to reduce
NATO and Warsaw Pact forces in Europe differences with Moscow over
human rights were blocking progress.
   The preliminary talks in Vienna were designed to overcome a
stalemate over conventional cutbacks in troops and armor in Central
Europe. At the same, the geography was expanded to cover the
continent all the way from the Atlantic Ocean to the Ural Mountains
in the Soviet Union.
   The talks opened in February 1987 with a new sense of optimism
both in Washington and in Moscow that East-West tensions could be
reduced through sizable reductions in the forces the two military
alliances have concentrated in Europe since World War II.
   But Charles E. Redman, the State Department spokesman, said U.S.
hopes that the Soviets would be willing to give equal consideration
to improvements in human rights conditions at home had not been
borne out.
   ``We have to have this balance between the arms control aspects
of this,'' the U.S. official said. ``Until we get this there is no
prospect we are going to conclude negotiations.''
   Next month will mark 15 years of inconclusive negotiations with
the Soviets over reducing non-nuclear forces in Central Europe. The
talks in Vienna were designed to break the stalemate. Hopes for
success were heightened as the United States and the Soviet Union
successfully concluded a treaty last year to abolish their
intermediate-range nuclear weapons.
   But Redman said apart from human rights there were ``still a few
areas to be nailed down,'' including technical details of the broad
area to be covered by the negotiations.
   The U.S. official declined to describe the Vienna talks as
stalemated. ``I would not say that,'' Redman said. ``It's a very
active negotiations.''
   Redman said the U.S. delegation in the Austrian capital would
keep pushing for an ``early conclusion'' to the talks. But, he
said, ``it takes two sides to make this work.''
   The spokesman declined to predict whether negotiations between
the North Atlantic Treaty Organization and the Warsaw Pact would be
opened before President Reagan leaves office in January.
   ``There are no artificial deadlines,'' he said. ``There are just
some very important considerations that need to be met.''
   He stressed the disagreement over human rights was the principal
roadblock. ``We've been pushing hard to get this wrapped up and to
get these talks under way, if that's possible, but without
sacrificing this crucial aspect of balance,'' Redman said.
   The slow progress in Vienna is bound to be on the agenda when
Secretary of State George P. Shultz meets here next week with
Soviet Foreign Minister Eduard A. Shevardnadze.
</TEXT>
