<1ST_LINE>r a AM-ErrantSatellite 1stLd-Writethru a0629 09-15 0280</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Errant Satellite, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0629,240</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Engineers Will Try to Put Errant Satellite into Proper Orbit</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS 2nd graf to add launch date</NOTE>
<DATELINE>McLEAN, Va. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A communications satellite launched for an
American company aboard the European Ariane rocket has failed to
achieve a usable orbit and efforts will be made to nudge it into
its proper place.
   ``We are trying to move the satellite into its orbital
location,'' said Barbara Foelber, spokeswoman for GTE Spacenet
Corp., which owns the GSTAR 3 satellite. The spacecraft, launched
Sept. 8, was to have been used for private business communications.
   She said engineers don't know the cause of the problem. The
satellite reached the 22,300-mile altitude required and the rocket
motor fired to put it into a circular orbit. The firing apparently
was not long enough and the satellite was put into an egg-shaped
course around the Earth.
   The spokeswoman said engineers will attempt to fire small
thrusters, normally used to keep the satellite from drifting out of
position, to gently push the satellite into a path where its speed
matches the rotation of Earth. That maneuver has been performed
successfully before, notably with the Tracking and Data Relay
Satellite launched by NASA in 1983.
   The satellite, which cost $85 million to $100 million to build
and launch, was insured for $60 million, Ms. Foelber said.
   ``We currently have five satellites in orbit,'' she said. ``We
will be able to provide ... services needed'' by the company's
customers, she added.
   GTE has another in the series of GE Astro satellites scheduled
for launching in April 1991 and Ms. Foelber said the company will
try to move its launch date ahead.
</TEXT>
