<FILEID>AP-NR-09-15-88 1815EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-Hurricane-SpaceCenter     09-15 0457</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Hurricane-Space Center,0470</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Space Center Shuts Down Because of Threat of Hurricane Gilbert</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Hurricane Gilbert Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LAURA TOLLEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>HOUSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   NASA's Johnson Space Center all but shut down
Thursday, with most employees sent home to prepare for a possible
assault by Hurricane Gilbert.
   The center, normally open for visitors every day but Christmas,
was closed at noon. All but a core group of employees were allowed
to go home and told they didn't have to come back until Monday,
spokesman James Hartsfield said.
   If the hurricane causes little or no damage at the space center,
Hartsfield said, it would probably have no affect on the expected
launch of the first post-Challenger flight at Cape Canaveral, Fla.,
later this month.
   There are more than 9,000 workers at the space center, including
government employees and people who work for private companies that
have contracts with the National Aeronautics and Space
Administration.
   NASA officials wanted to allow employees time to secure their
homes, get supplies or leave the area if they chose to do so
because of the threat Gilbert posed to the Texas coast. The space
center is about 25 miles from the coast.
   A core group will remain throughout the weekend at Mission
Control, the strongest building at the center and the place where
shuttle missions are controlled, Hartsfield said. Mission Control
has concrete walls and no windows.
   ``If the storm hurts that, we're really in trouble,'' he said.
   Past storms have caused flooding at the center, disrupting
communications and computer operations.
   The long-awaited launch of Discovery is expected to take place
sometime in late September, but NASA officials said Wednesday they
would wait to set an exact date until they knew more about where
the storm would go. They may announce a launch date Friday.
   At Cape Canaveral on Thursday, engineers corrected a tiny leak
in Discovery's engine system. The leak, traced to a valve, was the
only unresolved technical problem when more than 150 shuttle
managers and engineers concluded a flight readiness review on
Wednesday.
   If a later hurricane headed for the Space Center area during a
shuttle flight, NASA is prepared to fly a group of flight
controllers to White Sands Missile Range, N.M., so the shuttle
could be controlled from there. The flight controllers could get to
White Sands within a few hours.
   Hurricane Gilbert was in the Gulf of Mexico on Thursday and
seemed headed for the south Texas coast, but weather forecasters
warned it could turn northward and hit the Galveston area. The
space center is located between Galveston and Houston.
   Even if the storm did not hit the Galveston area, there still
could be heavy rains and winds in the area and possible flooding.
</TEXT>
