<HEAD>Arthur Ashe Released From Hospital</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: spelling of Ewanciw, ProServ are correct.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Former tennis champion Arthur Ashe was released
from a hospital Thursday after undergoing tests for a condition his
agent described as a ``severe bacterial infection'' in his head.
   The infection put pressure on nerves, causing numbness in Ashe's
arm, according to Ted Ewanciw, a spokesman for ProServ, Ashe's
agent. The 45-year-old former Wimbledon and U.S. Open champion
underwent treatment with antibiotics, which ``relieved the pressure
considerably,'' Ewanciw said.
   A spokeswoman for New York Hospital, Myrna Manners, declined to
comment except to say Ashe had been released Thursday after a
one-week stay, and that his condition had been satisfactory
throughout.
   Ashe retired from professional tennis in 1980, the year after he
underwent quadruple bypass surgery following a heart attack. He had
another heart attack and double bypass surgery four years later.
   In a telephone interview from his hospital room Monday, he said
the tests he was undergoing were unrelated to his earlier heart
problems.
