<1ST_LINE>r a AM-NicotineGum     09-15 0545</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Nicotine Gum,0561</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Study: Many Internists Misinform Patients on Nicotine Gum Use</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Embargoed for use at 5:30 p.m. EDT.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By WILLIAM C. HIDLAY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Nicotine gum can help smokers quit, but many
doctors give patients wrong instructions for its use, researchers
say.
   ``There is a widespread need for physician education about how
to use nicotine gum more effectively,'' said one of five studies on
smoking in Friday's Journal of the American Medical Association.
   Nearly 40 percent of the internists surveyed for the study said
they would prescribe nicotine gum to help patients cut down on
smoking, violating a key guideline for use of the gum.
   The first instruction on the gum package says, ``Starting now
you must give up smoking completely. Gradually cutting down on your
tobacco consumption will not work.''
   The study, based on a random survey of 208 internists in the San
Francisco Bay area, found that doctors' misconceptions about the
gum hurts efforts by smokers to quit.
   ``Misuse of the gum is most detrimental because the patients get
discouraged and don't think it works and then aren't able to quit
smoking,'' said Dr. Steven R. Cummings, an assistant medical
professor at UC-San Francisco. Cummings conducted the study with
colleagues at the University of California Medical School in San
Francisco.
   Incorrect advice from doctors also poses potential health risks,
the Cummings study concluded.
   Smoking while chewing the gum ``may produce higher serum
concentrations of nicotine than smoking alone, and this might
increase the risk of nicotine-related adverse effects,'' the report
said, while swallowing juices from the gum could increase ``the
chance of gastrointestinal side effects.''
   Most internists prescribe nicotine gum to fewer than 25 percent
of patients who try to quit smoking, the study found.
   But the gum _ a prescription drug marketed under the trade name
``Nicorette'' by Lakeside Pharmaceuticals of Cincinnati _ can be an
effective tool for some people trying to quit smoking, particularly
heavy smokers, conclude three other studies in the journal.
   One study found, however, that of 538 patients given nicotine
gum to help them quit smoking, 34, or 6.8 percent, were still
chewing it after a year.
   Those long-term gum chewers, generally heavy smokers, also
represented one-quarter of the patients who quit smoking for a
year, said the report by researchers at the University of London.
   A researcher in another study said the gum shouldn't be viewed
as a panacea.
   ``I don't think physicians ought to supply it just
willy-nilly,'' said Dr. Stephen P. Fortmann, an assistant professor
at the Stanford University School of Medicine.
   ``The gum shouldn't be seen as either a miracle or as a
necessity, but as a useful adjunct,'' Foreman said. He led a study
that found the drug effective and also that ``a large majority'' of
smokers trying to quit want self-administered, minimal-contact
treatment.
   A fifth study suggested that nicotine gum might help smokers who
consume more than 25 cigarettes daily overcome withdrawal symptoms
caused by their physical addiction.
   The manufacturer estimates 2 million people have quit smoking
using nicotine gum since it introduced in 1985. Bill Donaldson, a
spokesman for Lakeside, a division of Merrell Dow Pharmaceuticals
Inc., said the company had no reports of patients becoming addicted
to nicotine from the gum itself.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
