<1ST_LINE>r a AM-Gilbert-Airspace     09-15 0391</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Gilbert-Airspace,0401</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>U.S., Soviets Taking Joint Look At Fierce Storm</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Hurricane Gilbert, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By A.J. DICKERSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   U.S. and Soviet planes jointly studied Hurricane
Gilbert on Thursday, ending concern that the two nations were
competing for airspace over the storm as it moved off Mexico's
Yucatan Peninsula.
   ``After the confusion, we have a coordinated, international
effort to take a hard look at the insides of this very dangerous
storm,'' said Don Witten of the National Weather Service office in
suburban Coral Gables. ``That's the resolution.''
   A Soviet AN-12 took off from Cuba and made contact with American
pilots to work out a deal for probing Gilbert as it headed over the
Gulf of Mexico, Witten said.
   He said the Soviet plane was operating at 12,000 feet, an Air
Force plane was at 10,000 and a civilian aircraft from the National
Oceanic and Atmospheric Administration, the weather service's
parent agency, was at 5,000 feet.
   In the earlier confusion, forecasters at the National Hurricane
Center in the Coral Gables weather service office, believed the
Soviet Union had permission for exclusive use of much of the
airspace over Gilbert, and center Director Bob Sheets feared U.S.
planes might not be able to gather needed advisory information.
   ``We don't know if they got their permission from Mexico, but
that would be the logical place,'' Witten said.
   There is no higher international authority for arbitration when
two planes want to fly the same international airspace, said Roger
Myers of the Federal Aviation Administration in Atlanta.
   Because of the Soviet flight, the Air Force plane withdrew from
the hurricane's eye sooner than planned, but it stayed in the area
to try to make radio contact with the Soviet plane, said Pentagon
spokesman Lt. Col. Jim Jannette.
   Contact was made, and the U.S. and Soviet flight crews
``negotiated proper vertical and horizontal separation limits so
that both their missions could continue,'' Jannette said.
   The planes were studying the meteorology of the storm. The Air
Force reconnaissance plane was also gleaning needed data for
hurricane warnings, such as Gilbert's barometric pressure and top
wind speeds, said forecaster Max Mayfield.
   Gilbert, the most intense hurricane of the century until it
weakened over Mexico on Wednesday, had maximum winds of 120 mph at
noon Thursday, and was about 410 miles southeast of Brownsville,
Texas.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880915-0161 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-09-15-88 1849EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-HurricaneDaredevil     09-15 0485</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Hurricane Daredevil,0498</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Oceanographer Prepares For Flight Into Eye Of Killer Hurricane</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By IAN DONNIS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Thousands of people fleeing Hurricane Gilbert's
path Thursday might wonder at George Zamiar and his two colleagues:
They were headed toward the storm, steeling themselves for a flight
into the hurricane's eye.
   Zamiar, an oceanographer with Marion-based Horizon Marine Inc.,
will be measuring Gilbert's effect on ocean currents for oil
companies with offshore rigs in the Gulf of Mexico.
   Despite some jitters, Gilbert ``doesn't scare me at all'' after
flying into Florence, his first hurricane, last week, Zamiar said.
``I'm concerned, but this is what I want to do. I need the job.''
   ``It's a dangerous thing,'' he said. ``There's no doubt about
that. Everybody kind of looks at you with the `you must be crazy'
look.''
   Zamiar will joined on the mission by John Marwitz, an
atmospheric scientist at the University of Wyoming and ex-Marine
George Bershinsky, who compared flying in extreme weather to combat
missions in Vietnam.
   ``It's not that much different,'' Bershinsky said. ``You develop
an extreme degree of alertness before you go into this. I don't see
any major difficulties. We're keeping our options open, so if it
gets too rough we can get out.''
   The three men planned to converge at Addison County Airport in
Dallas to plot the course of the storm before taking off early
Friday morning in a twin-engine Beech Aircraft King Air.
   The specially equipped plane rented from the University of
Wyoming is large and sturdy enough to get through the hurricane,
called one of the strongest ever, Zamiar said.
   Water and lightning from Gilbert are a greater threat than the
hurricane's top winds of 175 mph, he said.
   ``I'm certainly not a believer in when your number's up ... I'm
a believer of that school that you have to watch out for yourself
all the time, or else you'll force your number to be up.''
   Zamiar will drop 25 probes, known as expendable current
profilers, to measure the voltage induced in the water as Gilbert
passes through the Earth's magnetic field.
   The probes will be dropped on a series of runs just before,
during and after the hurricane hits the Continental Shelf, where
the gulf floor suddenly plummets to far greater depths.
   A radio component will remain above the water and send data from
the probes, which drop to the bottom of the water and develop a
water current profile reflecting speed, temperature and direction.
   The information is useful for oil companies and other groups
building projects in the gulf that must withstand extreme weather.
The 1,000-mile trip is expected to take about three hours.
   The Air Force and National Oceanographic Atmospheric
Administration fly into hurricanes to gain atmospheric data, but
``as far as I know, we are the first private company to fly into a
hurricane for purposes of research,'' Zamiar said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
