<DOCNO> AP880915-0163 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-09-15-88 1925EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r p AM-RhodeIslandPrimary 1stLd-Writethru a0690'-preparedness
09-15 0564</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Rhode Island Primary, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0690,0571</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Kennedy's Critics Have Disappeared</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Adds 3 graf on St Germain race, gubernatorial primary.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By KIMBERLY M. SHEARIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PROVIDENCE, R.I. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Democratic Party leaders who once
dismissed Patrick Kennedy as too young and inexperienced to be
state representative said Thursday they were just being loyal to
the incumbent he defeated.
   ``I don't think anybody was against Kennedy,'' said House
Majority Leader Thomas A. Lamb, a Democrat from West Warwick. ``I
think the leadership was certainly in favor of Jack Skeffington. We
just think the world of Jack.''
   Lamb said Kennedy won't get the cold shoulder from his fellow
legislators, but said he still has an uphill battle to win their
respect.
   ``I think that he has to come to the House and he has to prove
himself,'' Lamb said. ``I hope that now they will have a
representative from the 9th District who will represent that
district well. The people will decide if he's doing a good job.''
   Skeffington, a five-term incumbent, assembled a powerful array
of General Assembly and party leaders to endorse him against the
21-year-old Kennedy, a Providence College junior and son of
Massachusetts Sen. Edward M. Kennedy.
   But Kennedy, making his first foray onto the political scene
where his famous family has long been prominent, handily defeated
Skeffington, 50, a funeral director in the 9th Representative
District, located in the heavily Irish and Italian neighborhood of
Mount Pleasant.
   Kennedy, who received 1,324 votes or 57 percent, to
Skeffington's 1,009 votes, or 43 percent, automaticaly wins the
office because there is no Republican opposition in November.
   House Speaker Joseph DeAngelis, a Democrat from Smithfield, said
he tried to talk Kennedy out of running last June because ``we felt
loyal towards Jack and we were going to do everything we could to
help Jack face a stiff primary.''
   But DeAngelis predicted that when the Legislature opens in
January there won't be ``animosity or resentment'' toward young
Kennedy.
   During the campaign, Skeffington rattled off a list of
supporters, including Secretary of State Kathleen Connell,
Providence Mayor Joseph R. Paolino Jr. and Lt. Gov. Richard Licht.
But Licht and Ms. Connell said they supported Skeffington because
he was endorsed by the party.
   ``It was a classic story of a young man taking on a veteran, and
in this instance, the energy and the excitement that Kennedy
brought to the contest won,'' Ms. Connell said.
   Skeffington blamed his defeat on the fanfare over the Kennedy
name and the campaign waged on Kennedy's behalf by numerous family
members, including Kennedy's father; his cousin, Massachusetts Rep.
Joseph Kennedy, and cousin John Kennedy Jr., the son of the late
president.
   In other results of Wednesday's Democratic primary, Rep. Fernand
J. St Germain, the House Banking Committee chairman who has served
14 terms, narrowly survived a challenge from Scott Wolf, a
political consultant making his first try for office. St Germain
got 55 percent of the vote.
   State and national Republican officials said they were
optimistic about their candidate Ronald K. Machtley's prospects
against St Germain in November. ``We'll throw everything we can in
it,'' said Rich Galen, spokesman for the National Republican
Congressional Committee in Washington. ``He is at the top of the
list of vulnerable Democrats.''
   And businessman Bruce G. Sundlun won the right to oppose
Republican Gov. Edward D. DiPrete in November.
</TEXT>
