<1ST_LINE>r a AM-Ellington     09-15 0258</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Ellington,0272</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>`Sophisticated Ladies' To Open in U.S.S.R.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   ``Duke Ellington's Sophisticated Ladies'' will
become the first American-Soviet co-production of a Broadway
musical, officials announced Thursday.
   The music and dance revue of songs by the late Duke Ellington
opened on Broadway in 1981. A new, $5 million production opens Oct.
1 in Moscow for two weeks, and then will tour.
   ``Ellington's music is very popularand very familiar to our
audiences,'' Eugene Tomach, director of the Soyuzteatr organization
in Moscow, said at a news conference.
   Duke Ellington led his band on a Soviet tour in the early 1970s.
   Mercer Ellington, who now leads the Ellington Band, helped
choose 16 Soviet musicians for the show's 20-piece orchestra.
American Frank Owens will conduct and play piano. Trumpeter Jon
Faddis and saxophonist Norris Turney, who played in his band before
Duke Ellington's death in 1974, also will be in the show's band.
   The cast will include tap dancers Hinton Battle and Gregg Burge
from the original Broadway cast and Donna Wood, a former dancer in
the Alvin Ailey American Dance Theater.
   One Soviet dancer is being trained to be in the 19-member cast.
   The Americans provide cast, director, choreographer, staff and
crew. A Soviet fashion designer will create costumes. Sets will be
designed by a Paris-based artist and constructed in Tbilisi in the
Soviet Union.
   After Moscow, the show will perform in Leningrad and Tbilisi,
then Paris, Brazil, Argentina, Venezuela, Australia, New Zealand,
Singapore, Hong Kong and, in 1990, San Francisco, Los Angeles,
Washington, New York and London.
</TEXT>
