<2ND_LINE>AM-Mark Hoffmann,0222</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Retransmits to fix typo in slug</HEAD>
<HEAD>Convicted Bomber In Critical Condition After Apparent Drug
Overdose</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SALT LAKE CITY (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Convicted bomber and Mormon documents
forger Mark Hofmann was in critical condition Thursday from an
apparent drug overdose, a hospital official said.
   Utah Health Sciences Center spokesman John Dwan said a medical
helicopter was rushed to Utah State Prison on Thursday afternoon
after Department of Corrections officials said they had a
critically ill inmate.
   Dwan said Hofmann was in ``critical and unstable condition and
comatose.''
   Hofmann also suffered ``minor to moderate burns'' on his right
forearm and chest, he said. He said the cause of the burns was not
immediately known, but they were not considered serious.
   Hofmann, 33, is serving a five years to life prison term
following his a January 1987 plea agreement. Hofmann admitted
killing two people with homemade pipe bombs on Oct. 15, 1985, to
cover up his secret career as a forger of Mormon and other
historical documents.
   Juan Benavidez, state Department of Corrections spokesman, said
officers were called to Hofmann's cell about 12:40 p.m. by his
cellmate, who could not wake him up for their noon meal.
   Benavidez said Hofmann had been prescribed a sleeping
medication, but he did not know what it was, or the dosage.
</TEXT>
