<1ST_LINE>r w AM-ManassasBattlefield     09-15 0329</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Manassas Battlefield,330</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Senate Panel Votes To Acquire Site Near Civil War Battlefield</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RICHARD KEIL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Senate panel on Thursday voted to seize a
development site adjacent to the Manassas National Battlefield Park
in suburban Virginia, rejecting a compromise under which only part
of the parcel would be acquired.
   The Energy and Natural Resources Committee voted 11-8 to approve
a measure that would authorize Congress to acquire the 542-acre
William Center Development tract, close two heavily-traveled
commuter routes through the Civil War battlefield and pay up to $30
million to build new roads around the park.
   The measure, introduced by Sen. Dale Bumpers, D-Ark., is
identical to a bill that passed the House last month.
   It prevailed over a compromise measure by Sen. John Warner,
R-Va., that would have acquired just 80 acres of the tract. Warner
said his proposal would preserve the most important historical
aspects of the site at a lower cost.
   However, Bumpers maintained the entire tract was historically
significant.
   ``If we don't act to preserve that property, you can go down
there three weeks from now, and it will be gone, for all intents
and purposes,'' Bumpers said. ``It'll be a shopping mall.''
   Committe chairman Sen. J. Bennett Johnston, D-La., said he hoped
the bill would reach the Senate floor by next week. President
Reagan has threatened to veto any legislation similar to the
Bumpers bill.
   Developer John T. Hazel is planning to build a 1.2 million
square-foot shopping mall, 1.7 million square feet of office space,
and 560 homes adjacent to the 4,200-acre park.
   Historians claim the development would ruin the historic
integrity of the still-rustic ground on which the First and Second
Battles of Manassas were fought.
   In addition, the development site includes a hill from which
Confederate Gen. Robert E. Lee commanded his troops in Second
Manassas. Historians also claim that Union and Confederate dead lie
in unmarked graves scattered throughout the development area.
</TEXT>
