<1ST_LINE>r w AM-TerritorialLimit     09-15 0468</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Territorial Limit,460</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>House Committee Approves Expanded Territorial Limit</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LES BLUMENTHAL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The House Merchant Marine and Fisheries
Committee approved legislation Thursday that would extend the U.S.
territorial limit to 12 nautical miles, the first change since 1793
when President Thomas Jefferson declared a three-mile protection
zone along the U.S. coast.
   The committee also approved legislation that would require that
foreign fishing vessels stow their gear when passing through the
200-mile U.S. economic zone and carry transponders so satellites
could track their location.
   Those proposals were attached to a new U.S.-Soviet fishing
treaty and were sought by Washington state lawmakers after seven
Japanese trawlers were videotaped fishing in American waters off
Alaska in January.
   Along with the change in the territorial limit, the measure also
includes an expansion of the so-called U.S. contiguous zone from 12
nautical miles to 24 nautical miles.
   The measure was approved on a voice vote.
   Rep. Mike Lowry, D-Wash., sponsor of the bill, said the
expansion of the territorial limit will allow the United States to
exercise complete control over a broader area and was essential for
national security reasons.
   The new limit will force foreign intelligence vessels to stay
further offshore, said Lowry.
   ``By moving our territorial sea from three miles to 12 miles,
the ability of Soviet ships to monitor and detect the movement of
U.S. submarines is lessened,'' said Lowry.
   The expansion of the contiguous zone will allow the United
States to enforce such things as its customs laws and pollution
regulations over a broader area, said Lowry.
   Lowry said the expansion would ``enhance our nation's ability to
intercept and board vessels which may be carrying contraband or
drugs off our coast.''
   ``With a 24-mile contiguous zone, the Coast Guard would be able
to board a foreign-flag vessel out to 24 miles, without seeking the
consent of the foreign flag nation. This would clearly enhance our
nation's drug enforcement authority,'' he said.
   Lowry said that both zones would be ``consistent with customary
international law'' and that the Reagan Administration was
considering such changes through an executive order.
   The new requirements for foreign fishing vessel passing through
the U.S. economic zone were approved just weeks after reports in
the Japanese press of a organized black market in Japan for fish
caught illegally in American waters.
   American fishermen estimate that Japanese trawlers have caught
illegally more than 100,000 tons of fish worth an estimated $250
million off Alaska since the first of the year.
   Rep. Don Bonker, D-Wash., said present law allows the Coast
Guard to take action against foreign trawlers only if they are
caught illegally fishing in U.S. waters.
   ``Many of these vessels are alerted to the presence of the Coast
Guard and haul up their nets before they are discovered,'' said
Bonker.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
