<1ST_LINE>r a AM-DrugAgentSlain     09-15 0523</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Drug Agent Slain,0537</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Prosecution Conjures Bloody Images as DEA Agent Murder Trial Nears
Climax</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LINDA DEUTSCH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Three men accused of murdering a U.S. drug
agent will have bloodstained hands forever, haunted by their guilt
like Shakespeare's Macbeth, a prosecutor told jurors Thursday.
   In the culmination of an eight-week trial, Assistant U.S.
Attorney Jimmy Gurule began his closing argument with a quotation
from the play, declaring: ``Will all great Neptune's ocean wash
this blood clean from my hand?''
   The defendants are charged with the slayings of Enrique Camarena
and his associate, Alfredo Zavala Avelar.
   In a hushed courtroom, Gurule methodically laid out the case the
government has made in eight weeks of testimony against Raul Lopez
Alvarez, 28, and Rene Verdugo Urquidez, 36, both charged with
murder; and Jesus Felix Gutierrez, 38, charged as an accessory
after the fact.
   Felix is accused of helping Mexican drug kingpin Rafael Caro
Quintero flee to Costa Rica after Camarena and Zavala were killed.
   ``It is as a result of their participation whether direct or
indirect ... that their hands remain stained with the blood of
these two individuals,'' the prosecutor said.
   He spoke of Camarena as ``a hero whose only fault was that he
did his job too well.''
   ``He paid the ultimate price,'' said Gurule. ``He gave his life
for his job, for his country. He paid the price in the most savage,
barbaric, unbelievable manner. Beaten and beaten and beaten until
his life slowly slipped away, drained from his body.''
   Caro, who is jailed in Mexico, has been portrayed as the
mastermind behind Camarena's torture murder. Camarena was abducted
outside the U.S. Consulate in Guadalajara on Feb. 7, 1985. The
bodies of him and Zavala were found a few weeks later, buried on a
remote ranch.
   Gurule suggested to jurors that Caro marked Camarena for death
after a Drug Enforcement Administration raid on one of Caro's
marijuana plantations cost the drug baron $55 million and a second
raid netted 10,000 pounds of marijuana worth up to $5 billion.
   ``He has to blame somebody. DEA is responsible for these
losses,'' said Gurule. ``Somebody had to pay, and in this case it
was DEA agent Enrique Camarena.''
   With little physical evidence in the case, Gurule used charts to
outline circumstantial proof that the defendants were connected to
the deaths, noting evidence, for example, that put one defendant
near the scene of Camerena's abduction.
   Attorneys for the three defendants have contended they had no
role in the killings. If they discussed it with others, they said,
it was only because they read about it in the newspapers.
   Key pieces of evidence in the case were two tapes _ an audio
recording of Camarena being tortured and a videotape of Lopez
describing the Camarena killing to an undercover DEA agent who
posed as a drug dealer.
   Gurule dwelled on the brutal nature of the killings, describing
Camarena's crushed skull and Zavala's fractured ribs.
   ``It was as if someone was jumping up and down on his (Zavala's)
chest and crushed his chest cavity into his lungs,'' he said of
Zavala.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
