<1ST_LINE>r a AM-DelawareRecount     09-15 0402</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Delaware Recount,0413</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Beard Concedes Delaware Senate Primary</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By THERESA HUMPHREY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WILMINGTON, Del. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The stunning reversal of Delaware's
Democratic Senate primary ended Thursday as Samuel S. Beard, who
had already begun campaigning as his party's nominee, conceded
defeat to Lt. Gov. S.B. Woo.
   Beard, who appeared to have won Saturday's primary by nearly
3,000 votes, pledged his support of Woo at a news conference
shortly after the recount gave Woo a 71-vote victory, 20,225 to
20,154.
   Woo faces Republican incumbent William V. Roth Jr., who is
seeking a fourth term and did not have primary opposition.
   ``I am happy to be here today to concede to S.B.,'' Beard said,
pledging his support to the party and Woo's campaign.
   ``Together, we're going to go out and beat Bill Roth,'' said
Beard, who was named an honorary co-chairman of the campaign.
Explaining how he planned to go out and thank the voters, Beard's
voice cracked and his eyes filled with tears.
   ``Saturday night, I know that I gave the most upbeat concession
speech in the history of American politics,'' said Beard, a
millionaire civic activist.
   Woo joked that he had lived up to his nickname of ``Landslide
Woo,'' noting that when he was elected lieutenant governor four
years ago, he won by less than 500 votes in a race that also
required a recount.
   ``Sam, no one knows more than I the emotional roller coaster
your family has been through in the past few days,'' Woo said.
   He called Beard a ``formidable opponent,'' adding he would be
``even more formidable as an ally.''
   Both requested the recount Monday after a computer keypunch
operator mistakenly gave Beard 2,800 votes too many. Beard thought
he had won with 22,418 votes to Woo's 19,624.
   The 2,800-vote error occurred in a voting district of New Castle
County, where about 280 Democrats are registered. Beard received 28
votes in the district, but the votes were recorded as 2,828 in the
computer at the county's department of elections, according to Paul
T. Hart, county elections director.
   Woo, a 51-year-old physics professor at the University of
Delaware, was a political newcomer when elected lieutenant govenor
four years ago. He became a champion of Asian-Americans nationwide.
   Beard, a 49-year-old activist who inherited his wealth, had the
backing of party loyalists and labor. Beard has served as chairman
for job creation commissions under the past four presidents.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
