<1ST_LINE>r w AM-Deaver 1stLd-Writethru a0655 09-15 0854</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Deaver, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0655,800</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Lawyers Say Alcoholism Impaired Deaver's Memory</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Updates thruout with more testimony</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By JAMES ROWLEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Lawyers trying to minimize the perjury
sentence Michael K. Deaver faces contended Thursday that alcoholism
impaired the former presidential aide's memory during sworn
testimony about his lobbying.
   Defense lawyer Randall J. Turk said there was medical evidence
that ``at all times relevant to this case'' Deaver was an alcoholic
and that the disease impaired his memory.
   It clouded Deaver's memory both at the time of the lobbying
contacts and when he was later questioned about them under oath by
a grand jury and a House subcommittee, Turk said.
   The former deputy White House chief of staff and close friend of
President Reagan and his wife, Nancy, faces a possible five-year
term and a $6,800 fine for each of three perjury convictions.
   Deaver was found guilty late last year of lying by saying he
couldn't recall certain contacts with former Reagan administration
officials for high-paying lobbying clients.
   Sentencing is scheduled for Sept. 23. The evidence was offered
to give ``the court understanding of the offense behavior for which
Mr. Deaver was convicted,'' Turk said. Medical testimony about
Deaver's condition was not offered during the trial because the
defense rested without calling any witnesses.
   More testimony was scheduled on Friday.
   Turk said doctors would testify that Deaver's memory might have
been impaired because he took a Valium tablet before questioning in
May 1986 by the House Energy and Commerce investigations
subcommittee. The panel and a grand jury investigated Deaver's
lobbying for possible ethics-law violations.
   Deaver's willingness earlier that year to pose holding a
telephone in a rented limousine near the U.S. Capitol for a Time
magazine cover photo for a story about his lobbying shows how
alcohol had impaired his judgment, Turk said.
   The cover headline said: ``Who's this man calling? Influence
peddling in Washington.''
   ``His trust of Time magazine staggers the mind,'' Turk said,
noting that Deaver would not have allowed Reagan to expose himself
to the press that way.
   Dr. William Argy testified Deaver had been drinking up to a
fifth of Scotch whisky a day before his first treatment for
alcoholism in June 1985 at Georgetown University Hospital. The
alcohol detoxification occurred several weeks after Deaver left the
White House staff.
   Deaver remained sober for five months but began drinking in
December 1985 and his daily consumption had reached as much as a
pint of vodka or a bottle of wine before his second hospitalization
in October 1986, Argy said.
   Deaver's wife, Carolyn, told the doctor her husband consumed
``bottles and bottles of wine'' the weekend before the first
treatment in 1985 _ an episode that confirmed her belief he had a
drinking problem, Argy testified.
   A Roman Catholic priest who operates an alcoholism treatment
center in Havre de Grace, Md., testified that the former
presidential aide complained of blackouts when he was admitted for
a month's stay in 1986 following his second hospitalization.
   But on cross-examination by prosecutors, the Rev. Joseph Martin
noted that treatment records showed Deaver ``enjoyed a nightly game
of Trivial Pursuits'' _ a board game that tests players' memory on
a broad range of subjects.
   The priest praised Deaver's successful two-year fight against
alcoholism, saying: ``I don't know if I could sit in the chair
where he is, facing what he is facing with the serenity and
equanimity'' that he has.
   ``He will weather what happens and he will continue going to AA
(Alcoholics Anonymous) until he dies,'' said the priest, the first
of several witnesses Deaver's lawyers planned to call during the
two-day proceeding.
   The defense is trying to convince U.S. District Judge Thomas
Penfield Jackson that alcoholism should be a mitigating factor in
determining Deaver's sentence.
   But independent counsel Whitney North Seymour Jr. argued that
Deaver's treatment records show ``nothing to support any finding
that his memory was impaired.''
   ``Mr. Deaver's ability to recall was absolutely functioning, it
was just that he decided to select what he wanted to recall,'' said
Seymour.
   Among other things, the former White House aide was convicted of
perjury when he told a grand jury he couldn't recall contacting
government officials such as then-Transportation Secretary
Elizabeth Dole and others on behalf of private lobbying clients.
   The telephone contacts with Mrs. Dole and White House aide Roger
Porter occurred when Deaver was in the hospital ``while he was
going through acute alcohol withdrawal and while he was sedated''
with tranquilizers, Turk said.
   The doctors would say that Deaver's subsequent ``failure to
recall what he was doing at the time was quite understandable,'' he
added.
   But Seymour was able to show that the call to Mrs. Dole took
place only 45 minutes after Deaver had received his first
tranquilizer _ a 25-milligram dose of Librium.
   A telephone log produced at the trial showed Deaver spoke with
Mrs. Dole at 5 p.m. that day. Deaver took the Librium at 4:15 p.m.
and a 20-milligram dose of Valium at 5:45 p.m., said Argy, reading
from treatment records.
   Porter spoke with Deaver the next day, according to trial
testimony.
</TEXT>
