<FILEID>AP-NR-09-15-88 2003EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w AM-BRF--MilitaryMoves     09-15 0175</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-BRF--Military Moves,170</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>New Air National Guard Director Named</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Air Force Secretary Edward C. ``Pete'' Aldrige
has selected Brig. Gen. Philip G. Killey to become the next
director of the Air National Guard, the Pentagon said Thursday.
   Killey, 46, is currently the adjutant general for South Dakota,
a position he has held since March 1987. He will replace Maj. Gen.
John B. Conaway, who recently was elevated to the post of vice
chief of the National Guard Bureau at the Pentagon.
   A native of Monmouth, Ill., Killey is a fighter pilot who flew
129 combat missions over North Vietnam. He left the active Air
Force in 1969 to become an airline pilot and joined the South
Dakota Air National Guard in 1970.
   Killey has received numerous awards and decorations, including
the Distinguished Flying Cross, the Meritorious Service Medal and
the Air Medal with 13 Oak Leaf Clusters.
   The one-star general will move from Rapid City, S.D., to
Washington to assume his new post. The four-year term does not
require Senate confirmation.
</TEXT>
