<HEAD>Clews Blames Commissioner For Problems</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RANDOLPH E. SCHMID</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Carter Clews, a Federal Trade Commission
staffer fired and then re-hired in a dispute over political
activity, on Thursday blamed his troubles on Commissioner Andrew
Strenio.
   Clews was returned to the FTC payroll Wednesday, after
complaining that his resignation a week earlier had not been
submitted voluntarily. That departure came in the wake of a dispute
over letters the press aide sent out critical of Democratic
presidential nominee Michael Dukakis.
   Clews was given a choice of resigning or being fired when
concerns were raised that the letters may have violated the Hatch
Act, which bans political activity by federal workers.
   But Commission General Counsel Robert Paul said Clews was
reinstated on Wednesday, at least until an investigation could be
completed into the facts surrounding the letters.
   Clews, meanwhile, issued a statement blaming Strenio, a
Democrat, for his problems.
   He charged that Strenio was engaged in a witch-hunt and was
trying to turn the commission into a ``covert arm of the Dukakis
campaign.
   ``If he had one iota of honor he would admit his culpability and
resign from office,'' Clews said.
   Strenio, in a statement issued by his office, said, ``Mr. Clews
claims that his dismissal or resignation from the Federal Trade
Commission somehow was caused by pressure from me. That is
incorrect.
   ``I did not propose, nor was I consulted about, dismissing Mr.
Clews or demanding his resignation. Indeed, I did not learn of his
departure until after he left.
   ``I am concerned about certain letters sent from the office of
public affairs and have requested an investigation. However, I am
reserving judgment on what action, if any, is appropriate until
after that investigation is completed,'' the statement said.
   Paul had reported that Clews was being returned to the payroll,
but would remain on administrative leave until the matter could be
settled.
   That prompted Clews to announce that he would not accept the
pay, instead saying he would divide the money among charities until
the matter can be settled.
   Commission Chairman Daniel Oliver and the other commission
members will likely have to make a final decision on the case.
</TEXT>
