<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Israel-Hungary 1stLd-Writethru a0622 09-15 0612</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Israel-Hungary, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0622,0632</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Shamir Says Hungary To Resume Ties, Others in Soviet Bloc May
Follow</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: New material and editing throughout, UPDATING with quotes
from Shamir. ADDS byline. No pickup</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By DANIEL IZENBERG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TEL AVIV, Israel (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Hungary has agreed to renew full
diplomatic ties with Israel after a 21-year-old break, Prime
Minister Yitzhak Shamir said upon his return from Budapest Thursday.
   He suggested others in the Soviet bloc may follow suit.
   Shamir also said the Soviet Union has diverged from its
staunchly pro-Arab position in the Middle East conflict and was
``looking for solutions that would take (Israel's) needs into
consideration as well.''
   The statement marked a turnabout for the hardline Israeli
leader, who has accused Moscow of scheming to trap Israel by
pushing for an international Middle East peace conference. Shamir
opposes such a conference, and Israeli officials have said that
even if one was convened, Moscow could not take part until it
renewed diplomatic relations.
   Shamir, head of the right-wing Likud bloc, met in Budapest with
Prime Minister Karoly Grosz and other leaders. His two-day private
visit was the first to Hungary by an Israeli premier.
   Before leaving, Shamir held an emotional meeting with Hungarian
Jews and pledged ``very close contacts'' with members of Central
Europe's largest Jewish community.
   Shamir told reporters upon arriving in Israel, ``The Hungarian
prime minister concluded that we are approaching normal relations
at a very fast pace.''
   He said no timetable was set for restoring ties but that ``we
are heading for positive developments in the near future.''
   Hungary and all other Soviet bloc nations except Romania cut
diplomatic ties with Israel after it captured lands of the bloc's
Arab allies in the 1967 Middle East war. For years, Israel has
worked quietly to restore the links.
   Shamir said Grosz told him the issue of ties with Israel
frequently came up in his talks with other East European officials,
including Soviet leader Mikhail Gorbachev.
   Shamir suggested that other East European nations may upgrade
their ties with Israel, saying in response to a reporter's
question, ``You should not be suprised if there will be news.''
   Israeli officials said Budapest could not have acted without
Soviet approval and that the step appeared to signal a new stage in
the warming of relations with the Soviet bloc.
   This year the Soviet Union met a key Israeli demand in
permitting a growing number of Jews to leave the country.
Emigration figures in August reached an eight-year monthly high,
with 1,864 Jews allowed to leave. Moscow also has begun allowing
Soviet Jews to visit relatives in Israel.
   The Kremlin has exchanged consular delegations with Israel and a
Soviet chamber orchestra now is touring Israel as part of improved
cultural links between the two countries.
   A year ago, Hungary followed Poland in setting up an interest
section in Tel Aviv, establishing the lowest possible level of
diplomatic relations.
   Shamir said Grosz briefed him on Soviet positions on the Mideast
and other issues.
   In Hungary, official reports made no reference to any planned
restoration of diplomatic ties between Israel and Hungary.
   Hungary's official news agency MTI said the two leaders reviewed
bilateral ties ``and possibilities for the further development of
contacts.''
   MTI quoted Deputy Foreign Minister Laszlo Kovacs as saying one
reason for ``increasingly higher level contact'' with Israel was
the desire to promote Middle East peace.
   Israel promised to assist Hungary in economic and industrial
development, Israel radio said.
   Inflation in Hungary reached 18 percent this year, and the
country has a foreign debt of $18 billion.
   Hungary's Jewish community numbers about 80,000, and about
240,000 Jews of Hungarian origin live in Israel.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880915-0176 </DOCNO>
