<HEAD>Abie Nathan Handed Police Summons For Meeting Arafat</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Four grafs SUB for grafs 4-7 pvs, In the ... in jail.''
UPDATING with additional casualties, Shamir comment. PICKS up 8th
graf pvs, The official ...</NOTE>
<HEAD>LaserPhotos TLV2, TLV3</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KARIN LAUB</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TEL AVIV, Israel (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Peace crusader Abie Nathan landed in
Israel Thursday after meeting illegally with PLO chief Yasser
Arafat in Tunis, and authorities greeted him with a police summons.
   Nathan, 61, was ordered to report to police for questioning
Friday for violating a law banning contacts with PLO officials. The
activist insisted the trip had the blessing of the Israeli army.
   ``Come to see me tomorrow if I'm in prison,'' Nathan told dozens
of reporters as he arrived at Ben Gurion International Airport near
Tel Aviv.
   In the occupied West Bank and Gaza Strip, troops shot and
wounded nine Palestinians during clashes, Arab doctors said. The
army said troops fatally shot an 11-year-old Arab boy overnight
after a patrol was attacked by a firebomb in Gaza City.
   The death brought to 266 the number of Palestinians killed since
the uprising against Israeli occupation began Dec. 8. Six Israelis
also have died.
   Nathan said he did not carry a message from Arafat to Israeli
leaders but would request meetings with Prime Minister Yitzhak
Shamir and Foreign Minister Shimon Peres to brief them on the
session with the PLO chief in Tunis this week.
   Shamir accused Nathan of violating Israeli law, and a Foreign
Ministry official reacted sarcastically to Nathan's remark, saying
such a meeting ``would have to be done in jail.''
   The official, speaking on condition of anonymity, also accused
Nathan of helping Arafat ``in his public relations campaign.''
   He apparently was referring to a Wednesday news conference in
Strasbourg, France, during which the PLO leader surprised his
audience by wishing Israelis a peaceful New Year, repeatedly using
the Hebrew phrase ``Shana Tova.'' The Jewish New Year began Sunday.
   Nathan said he urged Arafat to make the gesture, but he said the
PLO chief's willingness to comply was a symbol for his readiness to
recognize and negotiate with Israel.
   ``Who would ever have dreamed that anyone could convince Arafat
to say `Shana Tova'?'' Nathan told reporters. ``It was my idea. I
told him how to say it.''
   Nathan also said he presented Arafat with the names and photos
of five Israeli soldiers missing in action and was given assurances
that the PLO would try to help bring about their release.
   Nathan said Israeli army officials provided the list after he
told them he would try to meet Arafat in Tunis.
   Deputy army spokesman Col. Raanan, responding to Nathan's claim,
said the names of missing soldiers are available to anyone who
asks. ``I don't think he got any special blessing from the army.''
   Nathan also presented Arafat with a peace plan calling for
mutual recognition between Israel and the PLO. The peace activist
said Arafat promised to study the proposal.
   During an address to socialist members of the European
Parliament in Strasbourg on Tuesday, Arafat said the PLO accepted
all U.N. resolutions, including 242 and 338, which recognize
Israel's right to exist.
   But Peres, speaking to reporters in London at the end of a
two-day visit, said the PLO was in a ``confused state,'' torn
between proponents of compromise with Israel and rejectionists who
still dreamed of the destruction of the Jewish state.
   Peres did not spell out whether Israel now agreed to talk to the
PLO and accept an independent Palestinian state. Israel has refused
to negotiate with the PLO, saying it is a terror organization.
   A 1986 Israeli law bans meetings with representatives of terror
groups, including the PLO, and Nathan could face up to three years
in prison for meeting with Arafat.
   In 1966, Nathan flew a private plane to Port Said, Egypt, in an
unsuccessful attempt to hold peace talks with Egyptian President
Gamal Abdel Nasser. At the time, Israel and Egypt were still
officially at war.
   Nathan served as a fighter pilot during the 1948 Middle East war
and owns the Voice of Peace, a pirate radio station broadcasting
from the Mediterranean.
</TEXT>
