<1ST_LINE>r w AM-Obit-Wallich     09-15 0219</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Obit-Wallich,200</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Former Fed Governor Henry Wallich Dies</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Henry C. Wallich, a governor of the Federal
Reserve Board from 1974 to 1986, died Thursday. He was 74.
   An announcement released by the Federal Reserve said he died at
George Washington University Medical Center following an extended
illness.
   Appointed by President Richard Nixon on March 8, 1974, Wallich
was regarded as the seven-member board's expert on international
economics. During the Carter and Reagan administrations, he was
considered an ally of then-Chairman Paul Volcker. Wallich resigned
Dec. 15, 1986, citing ill health.
   Under President Dwight Eisenhower, he served from 1958 to 1959
as an assistant to Treasury Secretary Robert B. Anderson and from
1959 to 1961 as a member of the President's Council of Economic
Advisers.
   Born June 10, 1914 in Berlin, Wallich was educated in Germany
and Oxford University in England and he earned a doctorate in
economics at Harvard University.
   During the 1930s, he was a securities analyst in New York City
and was in the export business in Argentina and Chile.
   From 1941 to 1951, he was on the staff of the Federal Reserve
Bank of New York before becoming a professor of economics at Yale
University from 1951 to 1974. He took a leave of absence for his
appointments in the Eisenhower administration.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
