<1ST_LINE>u w AM-Cavazos     09-15 0334</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Cavazos,330</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Senate Panel Approves Reagan's Nominee For Education Secretary</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JENNIFER DIXON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Reagan's choice of Lauro F. Cavazos
of Texas to become the nation's next secretary of education was
approved Thursday by a Senate committee, clearing the way for
expected easy confirmation by the full Senate.
   ``I expect him to be confirmed unanimously,'' said Sen. Phil
Gramm, R-Texas. ``I would be very surprised if anybody voted
against Larry.''
   The Labor and Human Resources Committee recommended unanimously
that the Senate confirm Cavazos, who would become the first
Hispanic ever to serve in a presidential cabinet. A Senate vote was
likely early next week, staff members said.
   Sen. Edward M. Kennedy, D-Mass., the committee chairman, praised
Cavazos after the panel voted. He said the Texan would bring
``fresh leadership and a new dedication to excellence in education
_ and a less-confrontational approach to this all-important issue.''
   If confirmed, Cavazos, who has been president of Texas Tech
University in Lubbock since 1980, would succeed William J. Bennett
in the Cabinet post and would serve until the president elected in
November takes office in January.
   Gramm said he believed Cavazos would be retained in the Cabinet
if Vice President George Bush, the Republican presidential nominee,
wins the November election. If that is the case, said Gramm, the
Texan would ``clearly have an opportunity to have great impact on
every school child in America.''
   Cavazos told the Senate panel last week that he would push for
increased education spending and focus on meeting the educational
needs of all Americans.
   ``It is vital we have a Department of Education that speaks up
for every citizen in the area of education,'' he said.
   Reagan disclosed his selection of Cavazos on Aug. 9. Bennett had
announced May 9 that he would resign from the Cabinet in
mid-September. Bennett took office as education secretary in
February 1985, succeeding T.H. Bell, who had been in the Reagan's
original Cabinet and served from 1981 through 1984.
</TEXT>
