<1ST_LINE>r a AM-WeatherpageWeather     09-15 0360</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Weatherpage Weather,0371</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Rain Over Central U.S., Gilbert Churns in Gulf</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Rain fell Thursday on much of the central United States, and
Hurricane Gilbert sent clouds and showers to the central Gulf of
Mexico coast.
   Showers and thunderstorms continued into mid-afternoon from
Oklahoma across eastern South Dakota, from southwest Minnesota
across northwest Arkansas and eastern Florida.
   Rain from Hurricane Gilbert reached from Louisiana to the
Florida panhandle.
   Heavier rainfall Thursday included 1.75 inches at Kansas City,
Mo., nearly 1{ inches at Sioux Falls, S.D., nearly 1\ inches at
Oklahoma City and more than an inch at New Orleans.
   Hurricane warnings remained in effect along the lower Texas gulf
coast from Port O'Connor to Brownsville. A hurricane watch was
posted from Port O'Connor to Port Arthur.
   A frost warning was posted for northeast New York and much of
Vermont for Thursday night.
   The low temperature in the nation Thursday was 21 degrees at
Gunnison, Colo. Temperatures around the nation at 3 p.m. EDT ranged
from 51 degrees at Limestone, Maine, to 103 degrees at Palm
Springs, Calif.
   Orlando, Fla., reached 96 degrees, breaking a record for the
date set in 1987.
   The outlook for Friday called for rain with lower temperatures
in Montana, where rain will become snow in the mountains;
rainshowers and thunderstorms will extend from the southeast half
of Texas across the central Gulf of Mexico coast to the Florida
Panhandle, the upper Great Lakes, the lower Ohio Valley, western
Tennessee and western Alabama.
   Skies will be cloudy over the northern Plains and the northern
Pacific coast. Skies will be generally sunny over the remainder of
the nation.
   High temperatures will be in the 50s for northern Maine and
northeast Minnesota; in the 60s and 70s from southern Maine across
North Carolina, the Great Lakes, the Mississippi Valley and much of
the northern half of the plains, the Rocky Mountains, the Pacific
Northwest and the California coast.
   High temperatures across southern Texas will be in the mid to
upper 70s; in the 90s for the lower two-thirds of the Florida
peninsula and from northeast and southwest Texas; and near 105 in
the desert Southwest.
</TEXT>
