<FILEID>AP-NR-09-15-88 2059EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w AM-Schools-Unions     09-15 0419</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Schools-Unions,400</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Board Association Panel Calls For Alternatives to Collective
Bargaining</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MATT YANCEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Labor Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Local school boards should find supplements or
alternatives to collective bargaining with teacher unions to bring
about education reforms, a National School Boards Association panel
said Thursday.
   ``While most public school systems participate in collective
bargaining with their teacher organizations, the adversarial nature
of these discussions has worked against cooperation and candor in
some instances,'' the panel said in a 44-page report.
   The panel was convened last year by the association's
then-President Jonathan T. Howe, who is a local school board member
in Northbrook, Ill., ``to look into how we get into these
situations'' of strikes at the opening of school terms each
September.
   The report comes on the heels of Carnegie Foundation survey
released this week showing that teachers believe they have little
role in key classroom decisions and want more authority and
responsibility.
   Howe said he agreed with the foundation's conclusions that
teachers should have more to say about such things, but not through
collective bargaining by their unions.
   ``Collective bargaining today is what I call P-M-P _ power,
money and process,'' he said. ``These are the three items that
normally get discussed at the bargaining table. It is nearly
impossible to discuss working cooperatively for the benefit of
school children after hours of debate solely on pay scales,
benefits and length of contract.''
   Howe said union-heralded education reform efforts in Dade
County, Fla., and Rochester, N.Y., ``came about not through
collective bargaining but through a waiver of collective bargaining
to bring about change.''
   Albert Shanker, president of the American Federation of
Teachers, said Howe's conclusion that collective bargaining entails
only power, money and process contradicts examples of reforms cited
in the report in school systems in Dade County, Rochester, Toledo
and Pittsburgh.
   ``The idea that innovative education reform initiatives in
Rochester and Miami could have taken place without the strong
backing of local AFT affiliates or a strong contract is just plain
wrong,'' Shanker said.
   He called collective bargaining the best way for communicating
between teachers and school administrators because it ``insures
that whatever dialogue occurs is held on equal ground.''
   The association's report said the two major themes surfacing in
several recent calls for education reform are restructuring schools
and ``empowerment of teachers.''
   But it defines ``empowerment'' as sharing information _ not
power _ with teachers, designing instructional programs in
cooperation with them and assigning them a share of the
responsibility for fostering excellence.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
