<1ST_LINE>r i AM-SouthKorea     09-15 0227</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-South Korea,0233</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>48 People Reported Injured In Campus Clashes</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SEOUL, South Korea (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Protesters armed with clubs and
firebombs battled riot police Thursday at an anti-government
demonstration, and at least 48 people were injured, reports said.
   The melee started when riot police stopped about 600 students
and dissidents from marching off the campus of A-ju University in
Suwon, 25 miles south of Seoul, the Korean news agency Yonhap
reported. It said four students were arrested.
   Protesters shouted slogans opposing a government ban on what
they called legal demonstrations when the Olympic Games open in
Seoul Saturday.
   Yonhap said police refrained from using tear gas because Suwon
is designated as a ``Peace Zone.'' Police and school authorities
declined to comment.
   Authorities have banned all street demonstrations in ``peace
zones'' in Seoul and other cities, which have Olympic venues and
related facilities.
   Yonhap said demonstrators organized the rally at the A-ju campus
to protest an earlier police action in which a student was
seriously injured after being hit by a tear gas canister Sept. 7
during an anti-Olympic, anti-government demonstration at a nearby
university campus.
   Protests during the past week have been small and attracted
little support, with the great majority of South Koreans and most
students ignoring demands the Olympics be shared with communist
North Korea to help promote reunification of the divided Korean
peninsula.
</TEXT>
