<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Gibraltar-IRA     09-15 0724</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Gibraltar-IRA,0758</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>British Shooter Says IRA Member Died For Ignoring Warning To Stop</HEAD>
<DATELINE>GIBRALTAR (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   One of four British commandos who shot and
killed three unarmed IRA guerrillas in March told a coroner's
inquest Thursday that one of the three made a suspicious movement
and then failed to heed a warning to stop.
   Another soldier, who took no part in the actual shooting, backed
up the first witness' account that the man, Sean Savage, 24, looked
like he was reaching for a weapon.
   The Special Air Services commando who shot Savage said the Irish
Republican Army member would still be alive if he stopped when
warned.
   The commando, identified only as ``Soldier D'' for security
reasons, said Savage instead moved his hand aggressively toward a
jacket pocket, spurring him and his partner to fire.
   ``We gave Savage an option,'' said the commando, hidden from
view by a curtain during his testimony.
   ``If he had stopped, I'm telling you he would be alive now. He
was given more than enough time. We had no need to give him a
warning _ we gave him the benefit of the doubt.''
   He was cross-examined by Patrick McGrory, the attorney for the
IRA members' families.
   A third soldier said he saw Mairead Farrell, 31, fall to the
ground, but saw no move on her part _ such as lifting her arm in
the air _ to surrender.
   News reports and a documentary by Independent Television in
Britain have quoted witnesses to the March 6 shooting in Gibraltar
as saying Farrell tried to surrender but was shot down.
   The testimony came on the eighth day of an inquest by Gibraltar
Coroner Felix Pizzarello and an 11-man jury into the shooting
deaths of Savage, Farrell and Daniel McCann, 30, by the elite
anti-terrorist unit of the British military.
   Critics of British Prime Minister Margaret Thatcher's government
claimed the deaths were evidence of an unofficial shoot-to-kill
policy against IRA members on missions against British targets.
   The IRA has acknowledged the three were members of its
organization and that they were on active service when killed.
   A senior British intelligence officer testified earlier that the
soldiers believed the three were planning to set off a car bomb in
this fortress colony with a remote-control radio device.
   ``Soldier D'' said he shot Savage nine times in all, the last
two into Savage's head. He denied shooting Savage repeatedly in the
head after the IRA man fell to the ground or putting his foot on
Savage's chest and shooting him.
   McGrory suggested such action would be ``sheer murder.''
   ``Well, it wouldn't be a nice thing to do,'' the soldier said,
prompting laughter.
   ``Is that the best thing you can say? That it wasn't a very nice
thing to do?'' McGrory asked.
   ``Well, it wasn't, was it,'' the soldier responded.
   Soldier D denied being ``in a frenzy'' at the time.
   ``I carried on shooting until he was no longer a threat,'' he
testified.
   ``Soldier M,'' another witness, said he saw McCann, Farrell and
Savage together before Savage separated himself from the others
minutes before the shootings.
   He said he noticed two soldiers closing in on McCann and
Farrell, then heard gunfire and saw Farrell falling to the ground.
   John Laws, the attorney for the Crown and Gibraltar Police
Commissioner Joseph Canepa, asked Soldier M whether he saw Farrell
raise her hand to surrender.
   Soldier M said he had not.
   Another surveillance team member, identified as ``H,'' said he
saw McCann and Farrell in front of a filling station after they
separated from Savage.
   ``They stopped and appeared concerned,'' H said. ``Soldiers A
and B went into a rigid pose and there was firing. I moved behind
soldiers C and D.''
   Soldiers A through D did the actual shooting.
   ``Savage stopped and spun around and there was an expression of
surprise in his face,'' H told the inquest.
   ``I feared he would be armed and that he would use his weapon
indiscriminately at myself and other bystanders.''
   ``I then heard shots fired by soldiers C and D.''
   The two shooting sites are within a clear line of sight about
200 feet apart near the British colony's border with Spain.
   H said he ``had no doubt that the move made by Savage
constituted a threat to soldiers C and D.''
   The inquest will resume Friday.
</TEXT>
