<1ST_LINE>r w AM-Cosmetics-Congress 1stLd-Writethru a0723 09-15 0380</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Cosmetics-Congress, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0723,380</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Government Moving Toward Final Ban on Hairspray Propellant</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: INSERTS 2 grafs after 7th graf pvs, bgng: ``The cosmetics
...'' to UPDATE with industry comment.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The head of the Food and Drug Administration
told Congress on Thursday that his agency was moving toward banning
a chemical that once was used widely as a propellant in hairsprays.
   Dr. Frank E. Young stopped short of saying his agency definitely
would make final a three-year-old proposal to prohibit use of the
product, methylene chloride.
   But he told the House Small Business Committee's regulation
subcommittee that based on the data his agency has gathered so far,
``We feel all the evidence indicates it is a hazardous substance.''
   The FDA should announce its final decision on the substance by
the end of the year. Other government agencies also would have to
consider the proposal before it becomes official.
   The FDA, believing the substance is a carcinogen, proposed
banning use of the product in 1985.
   ``Just the introduction of this for just a few seconds in the
air in the bathroom every morning'' is a risk, Young told the
lawmakers.
   The cosmetics industry has conceded that the chemical is
hazardous for cosmeticians who might use it several times a day,
but has argued that it is safe for consumers. But since the
government first proposed to halt the substance's use, the industry
has reduced dramatically its reliance on it.
   The Halogenated Solvents Industry Alliance, representing 200
companies that use, distribute and produce chlorinated solvents,
issued a statement saying the FDA overestimates the potential
health risk presented by exposure to methylene chloride.
   Alliance President Paul A. Cammer said a recently updated study
of Eastman Kodak Co. workers exposed to the substance for an
average of 22 years found no increase in overall cancer mortality
resulting from exposure to the chemical.
   Heinz J. Eiermann, director of the FDA's Division of Color and
Cosmetics, said that ``less than 2 percent or 1 percent'' of the
hairspray now in use contains the product.
   ``For all practical purposes, it has been eliminated,'' he said
during a break in the subcommittee meeting.
   Eiermann said the agency was moving toward issuing a final rule
on the product to prevent its use in the future.
</TEXT>
