<1ST_LINE>r a AM-GilbertInsurance 1stLd-Writethru a0729 09-15 0370</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Gilbert Insurance, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0729,0377</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Would-Be Insurance Buyers Too Late For Protection From Gilbert</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: UPDATES throughout with insurance companies also preparing
for numerous claims; no pickup.</NOTE>
<HEAD>PRECEDE New Orleans</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Hurricane Gilbert Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   While coastal residents either move to higher ground or shore up
their homes to ride the storm out, insurance companies are bracing
for an onslaught of claims in the wake of Hurricane Gilbert.
   Temporary catastrophe offices will be opened in Texas to help
residents and businesses begin the process of adjusting and paying
losses, according to the Insurance Information Institute.
   ``The catpool will also have personnel in the field,'' said Don
Manthe, chairman of the Texas Catastrophe Property Insurance
Association, or TCPIA, known as catpool. ``We will move our mobile
office to the landfall area jut as soon as it's safe.''
   The catpool provides windstorm and hail coverage for many
coastal residents. It paid $156 million in losses in 1983 as a
result of Hurricane Alicia.
   In Louisiana, where some home owners sought additional storm
coverage and new flood insurance this week, it was too late for
many to buy protection against the hurricane.
   Most insurance companies stopped writing storm-damage coverage
by Wednesday morning. And homeowners gave up the idea of buying new
flood insurance after learning that a new policy would not take
effect for five days.
   ``I personally turned down a half-million-dollar risk,'' said
Randy Maddox, president of Morrison Insurance Agency in New
Orleans. The independent agency represents Aetna and the Hartford
and a number of other companies.
   Maddox said he even turned down his own father's request for
additional coverage. ``It doesn't matter who it is,'' he said.
   Several large companies, including State Farm and Allstate,
stopped doing new business at 10 a.m. Wednesday. Others stopped
Tuesday afternoon.
   Gabrielle Rostran, office manager at the Angelo Leone State Farm
agency, said 30 or 40 customers called Wednesday seeking additional
storm coverage or flood insurance.
   The information institute said flood damage as a result of
hurricanes is covered under special flood insurance policies issued
under the National Flood Insurance Program, which is operated by
the federal government.
   Hardship cases will be settled first, the institute said in a
statement.
</TEXT>
