<FILEID>AP-NR-09-15-88 2112EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-BoatKickbacks     09-15 0203</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Boat Kickbacks,0207</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Electric Boat Buyer Charged With Taking Kickbacks</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BRIDGEPORT, Conn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A buyer for a government defense
contractor was indicted Thursday on charges he accepted kickbacks
in return for helping a Massachusetts company obtain an inflated
contract for Trident nuclear submarine parts.
   U.S. Attorney Stanley A. Twardy Jr. said Robert P. Wasco, 58, of
East Lyme, was charged with two counts of mail fraud and one count
of violating the federal anti-kickback law.
   Electric Boat, a division of General Dynamics Corp., is the only
contractor that makes the multimillion-dollar Trident nuclear
submarines for the U.S. Navy.
   The federal grand jury indictment alleges Wasco recommended that
the contract for a submarine part be awarded to Vorias Engineering
of Middleton, Mass., at more than three times what Electric Boat
usually paid for it.
   Soon after Vorias was awarded the $350,000 contract in January
1983, the company paid for vacations for Wasco and his wife in the
Caribbean and in Hawaii, the indictment said.
   If convicted on all three counts, Wasco could be sentenced to up
to 20 years in jail and fined up to $750,000, Twardy said. Wasco is
scheduled for arraigment Sept. 27 in U.S. District Court in New
Haven.
</TEXT>
