<1ST_LINE>r a AM-VodkaKilling     09-15 0278</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Vodka Killing,0284</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Friend Says Homeless Couple Loved Each Other</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PITTSBURGH (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A homeless woman accused of shooting to death
her companion over a bottle of vodka truly loved the man, a drifter
friendly with the couple testified Thursday.
   Robert and Kathlynn T'Souvas had ``a lot of arguments, but they
would end affectionately,'' David M. Bozic, 42, told an Allegheny
County coroner's hearing into the shooting death of T'Souvas.
   T'Souvas, 39, was shot once in the head along the Monongahela
River on Sept. 3. His 36-year-old companion, who took his name but
was not married to him, is charged with criminal homocide in his
death.
   As a 19-year-old soldier from San Jose, Calif., T'Souvas was
accused of taking part in the 1968 My Lai massacre. He was charged
but never tried in the deaths of two Vietnamese civilians.
   Bozic, who was with the T'Souvases on the day of the slaying,
said he allowed the couple to move into his makeshift ``lean-to''
shelter under the Smithfield Street Bridge.
   He said he believed the couple was ``really close _ they loved
each other.''
   Bozic said he doesn't believe Kathlynn T'Souvas shot T'Souvas,
as police charge. However, police said the woman told them she shot
T'Souvas after an argument over a bottle of vodka he held between
his legs.
   Police said T'Souvas' blood alcohol level was 0.26, more than
twice the level of 0.10 for legal intoxication. Police said Ms.
T'Souvas said the couple were drinking all day with Bozic as they
used his .22-caliber revolver to shoot at cans and rats along the
riverbank.
   Bozic said he and the woman waited overnight before reporting
T'Souvas' death to authorities.
</TEXT>
