<FILEID>AP-NR-09-15-88 2111EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Lebanon-Hostages     09-15 0623</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Lebanon-Hostages,0643</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Hostage-Holders Say They May Free Three Americans, Indian</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto BEI4</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DONNA ABU-NASR</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BEIRUT, Lebanon (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Moslem kidnappers holding four educators
issued a photograph Thursday of two of their American hostages with
a handwritten statement setting out conditions under which their
captives might be freed.
   The offer, from the Islamic Jihad for the Liberation of
Palestine organization, was in a note delivered to a Western news
agency in Beirut. The note included a Polaroid picture of Alann
Steen, 49, of Boston, and Jesse Jonathan Turner, 41, a native of
Boise, Idaho. The men have been held for nearly 20 months.
   The picture showed Steen and Turner, smiling broadly, resting on
a mattress with a flowered pattern and a violet pillow. Each was
holding a cigarette. Both wore navy blue outfits and had long hair.
Steen was clean-shaven while Turner had a bushy beard.
   Steen; Turner; Robert Polhill, 54, originally of New York City,
and Mithileshwar Singh, 60, an Indian who is a legal resident alien
of the United States, were kidnapped on Jan. 24, 1987, from the
campus of the U.S.- affiliated Beirut University College by gunmen
posing as riot police.
   The statement, written in Arabic, hinted that the Moslem group
would free its hostages if the U.S. administration undertook an
initiative within one week in support of the Palestinian uprising
in Israeli-occupied territories. The uprising began Dec. 8.
   Official U.S. policy is that Washington will not bargain under
such conditions.
   The hostages' wives, who still are living at the campus, were
not available for immediate comment on the new statement. Telephone
calls at the college go through a switchboard, which closes at 11
p.m., an hour before the statement was delivered.
   Islamic Jihad for the Liberation of Palestine is believed to be
sympathetic to the Palestinians as well as Iran's revolutionary
patriarch Ayatollah Ruhollah Khomeini.
   The four educators are among 17 foreigners missing and believed
held hostage in Lebanon. The 17 include nine Americans, three
Britons, an Indian, an Irishman, an Italian and two unidentified
men.
   The longest held is Terry Anderson, chief Middle East
correspondent of The Associated Press, who was kidnapped in Beirut
on March 16, 1985.
   The statement said, ``Our organization plans to undertake a
positive initiative to ease the issue of the hostages. But it needs
adequate reactions by international forums toward the rights of our
Moslem (Palestinian) people in their struggle against the Zionist
enemy.
   ``The U.S. administration should be the first among the
governments that should declare a clear, positive stance toward the
rights of our people in harmony with its claims of defending human
rights.''
   It concluded, ``At this sensitive stage of the uprising led by
comrade strugglers in the interior (of the occupied territories),
we offer this intiative and expect from the governments concerned a
response within one week of the publication of this statement. We
then will be ready to advance further in this initiative.''
   The term ``ease the issue of the hostages'' usually indicates
willingness to free the captives.
   The statement said the group's offer was timed to coincide with
the 10th month of the uprising against Israeli occupation of the
West Bank and the Gaza Strip.
   ``Every day and every month of the history of this uprising is
proving that the element of faith is growing greater,'' the
statement said.
   ``From this concept, the organization of Islamic Jihad for the
Liberation of Palestine declares its blessing for all the factions
of the Moslem Palestinian people as well as the entire Islamic
nation.''
   Steen was a communications instructor when kidnapped from the
college and Turner a visiting professor of mathematics and computer
science. Polhill lectured in accounting and Singh was a visiting
professor of finance.
</TEXT>
