<1ST_LINE>r p AM-BRF--KentuckyPoll     09-15 0172</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-BRF--Kentucky Poll,180</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>For Release 12:30 a.m. EDT, TIME set by source.</NOTE>
<HEAD>Bush, Dukakis Tied in Kentucky</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOUISVILLE, Ky. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Republican George Bush and Democrat
Michael Dukakis are in a virtual dead heat in Kentucky's
presidential race, according to a new poll.
   However, the Bluegrass State Poll published in Friday's
Louisville Courier-Journal also showed that Bush is attracting the
kind of support that has resulted in Republican victories in six of
Kentucky's last eight presidential elections.
   Bush edges Dukakis 47 percent to 45 percent in the poll
conducted Sept. 6-10, but the vice president's lead is rendered
meaningless by the poll's four-point margin of error.
   Nearly 80 percent of likely Republican voters said they intend
to vote for the vice president and nearly one-third of likely
Democratic voters said they plan to support him.
   The newspaper interviewed 586 likely voters by telephone who
either said they would vote for a candidate or were uncertain but
leaning toward a candidate.
   Kentucky offers nine electoral votes in the Nov. 8 general
election..
