<DOCNO> AP880915-0198 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-09-15-88 2243EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-Hurricane-Louisiana     09-15 0596</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Hurricane-Louisiana,0614</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Louisianans No Strangers to Hurricanes</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Hurricane Gilbert, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   You don't have to tell Louisiana old-timers what to do when a
hurricane begins brewing in the Gulf of Mexico.
   ``Because of the size and strength of this storm, we didn't have
to be told to leave,'' said Linda Toupuisaid, who along with her
husband runs the T&T Grocery in Holly Beach, La., where by mid-day
Thursday fewer than 25 of the coastal town's 100 residents were
still around. ``It could take a northerly course. If it's any time
to pack up for one, this is the one.
   ``This is the first time we've packed up in years,'' said Mrs.
Touchet, whose living quarters are in the rear of the grocery.
   Their back yard is beach and the Gulf of Mexico, where Hurricane
Gilbert, packing winds of 120 mph, was moving slowly toward the
north-northwest.
   Isolated squalls from Gilbert's northern edge knocked out power
Thursday morning in parts of Grand Isle, a resort community on a
barrier island of the Louisiana coast. Mayor Andy Valence warned
some 2,000 residents who evacuated Wednesday not to return too soon.
   ``We're asking all of those people to stay put where they are
because Grand Isle won't be a very nice place to be today,'' said
Valence.
   Tides were expected to reach 5 feet above normal all along the
coast and Valence said Louisiana 1, the only route from Grand Isle
to the mainland, was certain to flood.
   Some 20,000 people had been ordered to evacuate the state's
coast by Thursday afternoon, but many hadn't waited for marching
orders.
   And in Cameron, Hayes Picou felt no more pressure in making an
evacuation decision for the hurricane-savvy parish.
   ``You just take the data available and like any other job, you
make a decision,'' the 39-year-old parish civil defense director
said as he ordered what he called a precautionary evacuation of the
remainder of the population of 10,000.
   ``Sixty-five percent have already gone,'' he said. ``That's
enough data right there. Should you second-guess 65 percent of the
people?''
   By 6 p.m., about 75 percent of the population had left. Most of
the others said they would stay put unless the storm takes a turn
to the north.
   Picou said it was as total an evacuation as he'd seen in this
coastal parish since Hurricane Audrey swept a tidal wave through
the marsh, killing 500 people.
   Audrey is burned into the minds of the population and people are
educated to the danger of hurricanes from birth, said Picou.
   In fact, Hurricane Gilbert became a classroom exercise for the
eighth grade at Grand Caillou Middle School this week.
   ``We're teaching it while it's here,'' said teacher David
Duplantis, who took advantage of the weather to teach how air
currents develop into hurricanes.
   ``Everybody's saying it's the worst one yet,'' said Melissa
Guidry, 13, who lives in a trailer along Bayou Grand Caillou in
Dulac. ``If it's worse than Juan, then I guess I'm scared.''
   ``There was one parent who just left here, she said they were
taking their children to Tennessee,'' said Principal Danny Smith,
who used a hurricane tracking map to plot Gilbert's progress.
   Others plan ahead for these things, including one man who told
school secretary Joyce Trahan he was putting his pirogue _ a
flat-bottom canoe _ on top of his car.
   ``He said, `I'm gonna drive north and when I get to someplace
where somebody asks me what that is on top of my car, I'll know
I've gone far enough,''' the secretary said.
</TEXT>
