<1ST_LINE>u p AM-NYPrimary 1stLd-Writethru a0707 09-15 0841</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-NY Primary, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0707,0861</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Corruption Issue Highlights New York Primary</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Leads with 17 grafs to UPDATE with final results from NY
races; includes primary developments in Massachusetts, Rhode Island
and Delaware; picks up 9th graf: `In neighboring ...; matter below
dash will stand.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By MARC HUMBERT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Mario Biaggi, the popular Bronx congressman who
gave up his seat after his racketeering conviction, was handily
defeated by a state assemblyman Thursday in one of three primary
races overshadowed by political corruption charges.
   Biaggi, implicated in the far-reaching Wedtech scandal, resigned
from Congress too late to have his name removed from the ballot in
a three-way race with state Assemblyman Eliot Engel and former
Assemblyman Vincent Marchiselli.
   With 473 of 494 precincts reporting, Engel had 12,731 votes, or
50 percent; Marchiselli had 6,407 votes, or 25 percent; and Biaggi
had 6,370 votes, or 25 percent.
   The name of another Bronx congressman, Robert Garcia, came up in
testimony in the Wedtech case, but he has not been charged with any
wrongdoing. In a district where winning the Democratic nomination
is tantamount to election, Garcia easily defeated opponents Pedro
Espada and Ismael Betancourt.
   With 347 of 360 precincts reporting, Garcia had 15,855 votes, or
60 percent; Espada had 7,165 votes, or 27 percent; and Betancourt
had 3,340, or 13 percent.
   State Senate Minority Leader Manfred Ohrenstein, a 28-year
veteran of the Legislature, held off a well-financed Democratic
primary challenge in Manhattan from Joseph Rose, 29, the son of a
wealthy developer.
   With 99 percent of the precincts reporting, Ohrenstein had
11,270 votes, or 53 percent, and Rose had 10,056 votes, or 47
percent.
   Ohrenstein has been charged with illegally putting campaign
workers on the Senate payroll during the 1986 elections.
   In other races, in suburban Westchester County, former Cuomo
administration official Nita Lowey defeated Hamilton Fish 3rd and
businessman Dennis Mehiel for the right to oppose Republican Rep.
Joseph DioGuardi in November.
   With 464 of 493 precincts reporting, Lowey had 9,730 votes, or
44 percent; Fish had 7,988 votes, or 36 percent; and Mehiel had
4,580 votes, or 21 percent.
   In the Buffalo area, Jack Kemp gave up his congressional seat to
make his unsuccessful bid for the Republican presidential
nomination. In the Democratic primary there, David Swarts, the Erie
County clerk, defeated businessman George Hasiotis.
   With 463 of 490 precincts reporting, Swarts had 9,596 votes or
70 percent, and Hasiotis had 4,197 votes or 30 percent.
   Massachusetts also had a primary Thursday, but there were few
statewide races. On Cape Cod, Republicans Jon L. Bryan defeated
Martha P. Keyes competed for the right to challenge Democratic Rep.
Gerry Studds, who along with Massachusetts Rep. Barney Frank, is
one of the two openly homosexual members of Congress.
   With 57 of 189 precincts reporting, Bryan had 2,390 votes, or 56
percent, to Keyes' 1,844 votes, or 44 percent, according to
unofficial returns.
   Bryan, a USAir pilot who teaches management and marketing at
Bridgewater State College, and Keyes, an English teacher, made
their first political race. In neighboring Rhode Island, Patrick
Kennedy, 21-year-old son of Massachusetts Sen. Edward M. Kennedy,
won election Wednesday to the state House by defeating five-term
Rep. John Skeffington. There was no Republican candidate.
   And Rep. Fernand J. St Germain, the House Banking Committee
chairman, narrowly survived a Democratic primary, capturing 55
percent of the vote against Scott Wolf, a political consultant who
was making his first bid for office. St Germain will face
Republican Ronald K. Machtley in November.
   In Delaware, final results of a recount showed that Lt. Gov.
S.B. Woo won last Saturday's Democratic Senate primary by 71 votes
over civic activist Samuel S. Beard. Initially, a clerical error in
the vote tally had shown Beard winning. Woo will face three-term
Republican Sen. William V. Roth Jr. in November.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   Biaggi, first elected to Congress in 1968, was convicted of
various charges in two federal cases over the past 18 months but
did not resign until after his conviction in August in the Wedtech
case. Had he remained in office, he could have faced expulsion by
his colleagues.
   By that time it was too late for candidates to get on the ballot
for the primary and it was thought Biaggi would get votes Thursday
because of his popularity and because a Biaggi victory would give
the remains of the borough's political machine the chance to pick a
successor in a special election.
   Biaggi already holds the Republican line for the November
election.
   Garcia stepped up his schedule late in the primary when it
became apparent that Espada, a community health center director,
represented a serious challenge. Betancourt had lost in two earlier
primary bids.
   In the northern suburbs of Westchester, Fish was the first
member of his politically active family to seek office as a
Democrat. Fishes have been active in the GOP since the party was
founded and Fish's father, Hamilton Fish Jr., represents a
neighboring district in Congress that had previously been
represented by the young Fish's grandfather.
</TEXT>
