<1ST_LINE>a a PM-ReligionintheNews Adv16   09-15 0644</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Religion in the News, Adv 16,0661</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$adv16</NOTE>
<NOTE>For release Fri PMs Sept. 16, or thereafter</NOTE>
<HEAD>Parallel To Elections Seen In Choices Of Jewish Holy Days</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GEORGE W. CORNELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Religion Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   These are the ``days of awe'' for Jews, and some
of their leaders compare it to the time preceding national
elections, which also involves making critical choices.
   The 10 High Holy Days commenced Sept. 12 on Rosh Hashana, the
traditional start of a new year, and last through next Wednesday,
Sept. 21, Yom Kippur, the Day of Atonement.
   It's a period of self-examination, repentence for faults and
rededication to God's goodness, compassion and justice.
   ``Behold I set before you this day life and death, blessing and
curse. Choose life, that you and your children may live.'' That
Scriptural meditation runs through the occasion.
   Theodore Ellenoff, president of the American Jewish Committee,
notes that both the United States and Israel are approaching
national elections in which they also will ``set their courses for
the future.''
   He notes that Jewish tradition says the blast of the shofar, or
ram's horn, heard in synagogues on the holy days, will also signal
the arrival of the Messiah to bring world peace and harmony.
Ellenoff adds:
   ``In the forthcoming elections, American and Israelis have the
responsibility to take the first small step toward fulfillment of
that Messianic dream.''
   The dream is expressed in the prayers of the holiday worship:
``Open for us the gates of righteousness. Open the gates that yield
... blessing and brotherhood, compassion and kindness, devotion and
dignity ... justice and joy...
   ``Hasten the advent of Messianic redemption.''
   Rabbi William Berkowitz, national president of the American
Jewish Heritage Committee, suggested that Jews engage in a
``spiritual election campaign'' about basic decisions for their own
lives.
   ``We can take inspiration from this year's presidential election
campaign, which confronts fundamental issues and demands clear
choices,'' he said.
   ``So too, must American Jewry engage in a kind of spiritual
election campaign in which they confront the fundamental issues
facing the Jewish community and in turn engage in some basic
choices.''
   The Rabbinical Council of America, representing Orthodox
Judaism, said the forthcoming presidential election involves the
economy, human rights and defense, and urged Jews to vote in it.
   Rabbi Moses A. Birnbaum, president of the New York Board of
Rabbis, says Jews have ``always cherished one ideal'' _ the
``obligation upon us literally to `repair the world,' the vision of
a world healed _ by us.''
   ``As we wish each other life, let us wish each other the courage
and strength to turn the vision into reality,'' he said.
   Citing the recurrent prayer at holiday services, ``Inscribe us
into the Book of Life, O You who delight in life,'' Birnbaum said
``no prayer is more important'' for Jews and all humankind.
   ``But we live in days when life is often cheap, more often
corroded by cynicism and corruption. We see _ if we have the
courage to look _ so many countless lives made unlivable by poverty
and disease and homelesness.
   ``We see _ if we do not turn away _ lives inflamed by prejudice
and hatred and fantaticism. We witness millions of lives snuffed
out by senseless wars and bloody persecution.''
   He said surmounting these anti-life conditions demands not only
prayer but ``our unflagging determination to work for justice and
equality for all God's children.''
   Mazon, a Jewish hunger reponse, urged Jews to donate money saved
by fasting on Yom Kippur ``to feed those who fast not on account of
faith, but because of famine.''
   Saying 40,000 children will die of hunger on the day of Yom
Kippur, as happens daily, the organization said that when ``we are
given the opportunity to sustain life itself, it is not only an
opportunity, it is a mandate.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv Fri PMs Sept. 16.</NOTE>
</DOC>
