<2ND_LINE>PM-Business Highlights, 2 Takes,0554</2ND_LINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The U.S. merchandise trade deficit showed the
biggest improvement in almost six years in July, the government has
reported.
   The Commerce Department said the merchandise trade gap shrank to
$9.53 billion in July from a revised June deficit of $13.22 billion.
   The Reagan administration lost no time in hailing the huge
decline as proof its economic strategy of fighting soaring trade
deficits with devalued dollar was paying off.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   U.S. industrial production rose a modest 0.2
percent in August, the smallest gain in five months, following a
much larger July advance, the government says.
   The Federal Reserve reported Wednesday that the August increase,
the 11th consecutive month without a decline, followed a revised 1
percent July advance, which had been the strongest showing since
last October.
   The August increase was in line with expectations and analysts
said it should calm fears that the economy is overheating.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Senate has voted overwhelmingly to confirm
investment banker and former Sen. Nicholas F. Brady as Treasury
secretary in time for a major international meeting next week in
West Berlin.
   Brady, 58, who was confirmed Wednesday by a 92-2 vote, will be
attending his first meeting of the Group of Seven, composed of
finance ministers from the United States, Japan, West Germany,
Britain, France, Italy and Canada.
   Senators from both parties wanted a strong show of confidence to
strengthen their Republican former colleague's hand at the
gathering.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Oil futures prices have continued a rally that
began late Monday and that has pushed futures prices up about $1.65
a barrel since they briefly touched a two-year low.
   On the New York Mercantile Exchange Wednesday, the contract for
October delivery of West Texas Intermediate, the benchmark grade of
U.S. crude oil, soared 84 cents a barrel to close at $15.40.
   Separately, the American Petroleum Institute said U.S. oil
production declined again in August and imports remained strong as
uncertainty over prices left little incentive for boosting domestic
output.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>DETROIT (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Sales of U.S.-made cars and trucks fell 9 percent
in early September, but incentives continued to color the
year-to-year comparisons, automakers' figures showed.
   Companies making cars and trucks in the United States on
Wednesday reported sales of 243,337 vehicles during the Sept. 1-10
period, down from 267,397 vehicles during the same period last year.
   But from the last quarter of 1987 to now, big incentives have
shrunk, making comparisons a little fuzzy, analysts said.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Federal Reserve Board Chairman Alan Greenspan
has told Congress he sees no need for a blanket ban on mergers of
the biggest banks and securities firms, but is going along with
such a ban in order to win passage of legislation permitting banks
to underwrite securities.
   Greenspan said Wednesday that he and fellow Fed governors ``see
no threat to the system if those (merger) activities were to take
place.''
   But he said they did not believe it was wise to press the issue
for fear of hurting chances for repealing the Glass-Steagall Act,
which separated commercial from investment banking in 1933.
</TEXT>
