<DOCNO> AP880915-0223 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-09-15-88 0106EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f PM-OilProduction     09-15 0430</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Oil Production,0446</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>U.S. Oil Production Continues Decline In August</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   U.S. oil production declined again in August and
imports remained strong as uncertainty over prices left little
incentive for boosting domestic output, according to the American
Petroleum Institute.
   Meanwhile, deliveries of refined petroleum products rose 2.2
percent from a year earlier, the largest yearly increase since the
first three months of the year, the trade group said Wednesday.
   Refineries reached 88 percent of capacity, the highest monthly
utilization rate in nearly 10 years.
   Some analysts said the surprising number in the trade group's
monthly report was the healthy 11.7 percent increase in deliveries
of distillate fuel oil, which includes home heating oil and diesel
fuel, despite the severe summer drought in the nation's midsection.
Analysts said much of the demand was channeled into inventories and
not consumed.
   Deliveries of gasoline rose 1.3 percent and of kerosine jet fuel
0.8 percent last month, while residual fuel oil deliveries fell 2.6
percent, the report said.
   Crude oil production averaged 8.1 million barrels a day, 0.8
percent less than the 8.2 million barrels produced daily in August
1987.
   Alaskan daily production remained near the 2 million barrel
level it has held since late last year, but production in the lower
48 states declined about 175,000 barrels a day from a year ago and
more than 1.1 million from early 1986, the report said.
   ``The lower crude oil prices and increased price uncertainty of
the past several months have no doubt reduced the amount of well
servicing that is economic to undertake,'' the trade group said.
   The partial recovery in well servicing that began last year
appears to be eroding, the report said, with only about half of the
wells restored following the 1986 oil price crash.
   ``When you're getting $16 to $18 for oil, you can't put as much
enhanced recovery investment into servicing,'' said Bob Baker, an
analyst with Prudential Bache Securities Inc.
   Although imports declined between 3 percent and 5 percent in the
last two months, lower production and higher consumption have
pushed imports up more than 500,000 barrels a day over the last
eight months as a whole.
   The trade group said total inventories, which include crude oil
and its refined products, were up 0.2 percent in August from July
and up 1.6 percent from a year earlier.
   Residual fuel oil inventories were down 3.5 percent compared to
last month and 15.1 percent lower than a year ago.
   Crude oil stocks were down 5.3 percent compared to July and down
0.8 percent from August 1987.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
