<FILEID>AP-NR-09-15-88 0121EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f PM-AutoSales Bjt   09-15 0469</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Auto Sales, Bjt,0483</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Inventories and Incentives Color 10-Day Sales Figures</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By FREDERICK STANDISH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DETROIT (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Early September sales of domestically-made cars
and trucks were down by 9 percent from a year earlier, according to
automakers, but analysts say last year's incentives and reports of
relatively low inventories in 1988 make year-to-year sales
comparisons difficult.
   The companies reported Wednesday they sold 243,337 vehicles
during the Sept. 1-10 sales period this year, compared with 267,397
vehicles during the same period last year. There were eight selling
days in both periods.
   ``There is so much noise in the data that it's not a terribly
meaningful comparison, this year vs. last year,'' said Mary Ann
Sudol of Fitch Investors Service Inc. of New York.
   During early September 1987, dealers were in the thick of
incentive battles, offering such enticements as 1.9 percent
financing and cash rebates to get buyers into showrooms and reduce
bulging inventories.
   ``In addition, in the last report on inventories the industry
was down a shade below 60 days,'' Sudol said. ``It could be that
there are scattered shortages in the showrooms.''
   For the early September period, car sales fell 12.6 percent to
155,131 this year, compared with 177,512 during the period last
year. There were 1.9 percent fewer trucks sold during the period
this year compared with last year _ 88,206 vs. 89,885.
   Analyst Ron Glantz of Montgomery Securities Inc. of San
Francisco said despite the coloring that last year's incentives put
on sales comparisons, sales appeared to be strong.
   ``Sales are pretty decent,'' he said. ``The sales are at the
same rate they were last month.''
   General Motors Corp. showed the largest decline in early
September sales, an 18 percent drop, falling to 74,640 cars during
the period this year compared with 91,075 cars during early
September 1987.
   Ford Motor Co. sales fell 11.6 percent to 45,318 cars from
51,243 during the same period last year. Chrysler Corp.'s decline
was 10.2 percent, to 20,357 in early September from 22,659 a year
ago.
   Chrysler had some of the biggest incentives during the August
and September last year.
   Honda of America Manufacturing Inc. showed a 41.3 percent
increase to 9,660 cars early this month from 6,835 during the same
period last year, but a dealer sales drive may have something to do
with that, Glantz said.
   ``Dealers have a sales push going on in order to be eligible for
larger quotas in the new model year,'' he said.
   For the year to date, automakers reported sales of about 8.4
million U.S.-made vehicles, 7.1 percent more than the 7.8 million
sold through Sept. 10 last year. There were 214 sales days through
Sept. 10 of this year, one more than the same time last year, so
the percentage change was for the daily sales rate.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
