<DOCNO> AP880915-0227 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-09-15-88 0123EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f PM-HarvardResearch     09-15 0755</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Harvard Research,0777</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Harvard Raising $30 Million for Companies To Commercialize
Research</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By STEFAN FATSIS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CAMBRIDGE, Mass. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A complex scheme by Harvard University
to share in profits from the research findings of its faculty
members poses an ethical obstacle course for the university,
academics say.
   Harvard's decision to seek $30 million for companies to
commercialize the school's medical research comes eight years after
the university scrapped a plan to co-invest in a professor's work
after the agreement was deemed ethically dangerous.
   Phillip Sharp, a Massachusetts Institute of Technology biology
professor who in 1978 helped found Biogen Inc., one of the first
biotechnology start-up companies, said Wednesday that Harvard needs
``lots of walls'' to guarantee that the lure of forming companies
does not impede faculty and research decisions.
   ``Does Harvard's financial expectation in starting new ventures
have a risk in influencing what goes on in terms of their search
for truth and new research?'' Sharp asked. ``If that relationship
is too strong, then it has the potential of influencing who Harvard
recruits as faculty.''
   Harvard said the new program safely distances the university
from deciding what research would be marketed.
   ``There is by definition no conflict because Harvard is not the
decision maker as to where the investments would be made,'' said
Harvard Vice President John Shattuck.
   Under the plan, Harvard would raise money from six to eight
outside corporate investors to develop health care businesses under
a limited partnership called Medical Science Partners. That
partnership would be run by another limited partnership headed by
Andre L. Lamotte, a former drug industry executive, and Ion Inc., a
Harvard subsidiary.
   Harvard would get 10 percent of any company profits, which would
be reinvested in medical research.
   Administrators said the new scheme would raise sorely needed
money to supplement Harvard Medical School's $350 million research
budget and speed up development of medical innovations.
   The new investment structure, formally established this month,
differs from those at other universities because Harvard is
involved directly in raising the money used to start up the
companies.
   Most research universities have licensing offices that patent
and market professors' work through existing companies and then
divide royalties among the university, the department and the
professor.
   Stanford University last year earned $9.1 million through
licensing fees, tops in the nation, while MIT made about $3
million. Washington University in St. Louis has a 50-50 agreement
with an outside venture capitalist who selects research with
commercial promise.
   ``We don't co-invest with our faculty in new companies because
that could raise potential conflicts if you invest in Professor A
but not in Professor B,'' Stanford spokesman Bob Beyers said.
``Let's say Professor A gets a bigger lab or higher salary or more
graduate students. There are problems there.''
   Faculty members stand to receive research support in the Harvard
deal. They are not required to use the fund to market their work.
University conflict of interest guidelines urge scientists not to
compromise their research and teaching activities in relationships
with industry, including the fund.
   ``The big difference is they're creating that very large fund
that there's going to be pressure to invest in good research,''
said Edward MacCordy, associate vice chancellor for research at
Washington University.
   ``The key to look at is what influence on the inventor is there
going to be,'' he said. ``If the inventor still pursues the
research he wants to pursue and has the alternative of seeking
support for that anywhere he wants to, then there's no impact.''
   Shattuck said the limited partnership would be run directly by
Lamotte, a former executive with the U.S. affiliate of the French
drug company Merieux. Harvard Medical School recruited Lamotte, who
would negotiate with the medical school for rights to researchers'
work.
   ``He comes to Harvard to seek to patent and purchase discoveries
just as anyone else would,'' Shattuck said. ``It is an arm's length
relationship with Medical Science Partners.''
   In 1980, Harvard agreed to form a company along with biochemist
Mark Ptashne and take about 15 percent ownership share but backed
out after university President Derek Bok said the risk of judging
researchers based on the marketability of their work was too great.
   Ptashne, who still is at Harvard, found outside venture capital
sources to form Genetics Institute Inc.
   Many present biotechnology firms also were founded by professors
who realized a lucrative market for transferring technology from
the lab to the marketplace since the early 1980s. One example is
Genentech Inc. of San Francisco, formed by University of California
professors.
</TEXT>
