<1ST_LINE>r f PM-Alcoa     09-15 0268</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Alcoa,0279</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Alcoa White-Collar Workers To Participate In Profit-Sharing</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PITTSBURGH (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Aluminum Company of America says a
profit-sharing plan involving 7,000 white-collar employees in
domestic aluminum operations will go into effect this year, a move
opposed by the United Steelworkers union.
   Officials of the Pittsburgh-based company said Wednesday that
the plan would create a profit-sharing pool when the company's U.S.
operations exceed a return of 6 percent on assets. Employees would
share 17 percent of profits above that threshold, they said.
   Alcoa officials said individual payouts would vary with profits
and the number of employees involved. The plan is retroactive to
Jan. 1, the company said.
   Alcoa said the payout could amount to about 7 percent of each
employee's base salary if second-half 1988 profits equal first-half
profits.
   In contract talks three weeks ago, the company offered a
profit-sharing plan to union employees that would amount to up to
$1,300 for blue-collar workers, based on Alcoa's expected 1988
profits.
   The United Steelworkers said it rejected the plan as inadequate
and said it opposed the company's plan to extend it to white-collar
workers.
   On Aug. 24, the USW and the Aluminum, Brick and Glass Workers
unions broke off early contract negotiations with Alcoa after
rejecting offers that included profit-sharing, an immediate
ratification bonus, lump sum bonuses annually, an improved medial
insurance option and increased pension benefits.
   USW negotiator George Becker said the talks ended because Alcoa
would not address several key issues, including wage and pension
increases.
   The unions sought new contracts to recover concessions
negotiated in 1986, when the aluminum industry faced difficult
economic times.
</TEXT>
