<1ST_LINE>r f PM-China-FinancialFraud     09-15 0175</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-China-Financial Fraud,0183</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Auditors Find Huge Amounts Of Financial Irregularities</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BEIJING (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   China's state auditors in the past five years
uncovered more than $10.8 billion in financial irregularities,
including widespread misuse and embezzlement of public funds, an
official daily said today.
   The China Daily said the nation's 50,000 auditors, who were
commissioned in 1983, found the state treasury lost about $2.8
billion as a result of improper handling of funds.
   It said that in checks of 8,000 schools and 2,000 government
offices involved in education, funds totaling $113.5 million were
diverted into non-educational uses.
   Poverty relief funds amounting to $48 million were misused or
embezzled in 995 counties and 700 export-oriented firms evaded
taxes or otherwise carried out malpractices equal to $183.7 million.
   An investigation of 12 hotel projects in Beijing found that $62
million was raised illegally.
   The report said auditors had saved the state $270 million in the
past two years by preventing money from being spent on unnecessary
projects.
   People and units violating laws have been prosecuted, the report
said.
</TEXT>
