<FILEID>AP-NR-09-15-88 0730EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u f PM-WPPSSTrial Bjt   09-15 0671</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-WPPSS Trial, Bjt,0692</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Utilities Accused Of Breaking Promises To Bond Buyers</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Trial resumes noon EDT; lede prospects uncertain. A version
moving on general news wires.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By JIM KLAHN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TUCSON, Ariz. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Directors of the Washington Public Power
Supply System were upbeat about building two nuclear plants even as
they secretly discussed abandoning the billion-dollar projects, the
jury in the WPPSS fraud trial has been told.
   ``We claim, and we will prove, that these false statements were
made fraudulently, intentionally, recklessly and negligently,''
said one of the lawyers for the plaintiffs, Tom Barr, during
opening arguments Wednesday.
   Attorneys for the 19 defendants were expected to make opening
arguments today in the lawsuit over WPPSS' $2.25 billion default in
1983 after halting the projects. It's the largest default in
municipal bond market history.
   The defendants deny fraud claims, saying poor judgment may have
been used, but that WPPSS and defendant utilities hired expert
advisers and acted in what they believed were Northwest power
consumers' best interests.
   The U.S. District Court trial, moved here from Washington state
due to pretrial publicity, is expected to take months.
   Attorney Paul Bernstein, representing some of the 24,000 bond
buyers who sued, told the 20 jurors Wednesday they would hear tapes
of WPPSS directors behind closed doors talking about terminating
the plant projects in early 1980.
   Bernstein said that Don Clayhold, a utility official who was a
WPPSS director, was taped saying, ``If we scrapped the projects, we
probably wouldn't be able to pay off the debts.''
   Another WPPSS director, the late William Hulbert, said shutting
the plants ``would break every small utility in the Northwest,''
Bernstein told the jury.
   But the same directors, talking to a representative of the bond
agency Moody's, painted a bright enough picture of the projects
that WPPSS retained its A-plus rating, he said.
   Barr said the utilities that oversaw WPPSS made promises in
official bond statements that they never intended to keep. Barr
represented Chemical Bank of New York, which sued on behalf of the
24,000 bond buyers.
   The defendants are 16 Washington state utilities, all of them
WPPSS directors, two engineering firms and a financial adviser to
WPPSS. Seven other utilities settled out of court with the
plaintiffs.
   WPPSS was formed in 1957 by public utilities to build and
operate major electric plants in Washington, Idaho and Oregon.
   In the 1970s, it embarked on an ambitious plan to build five
nuclear plants, but was plagued by cost overruns and delays. Only
one plant was completed and is operating.
   Barr said Wednesday the defendant utilities claimed there was a
need for more electricity in the Northwest when there was not, and
continually changed estimates of what building plant Nos. 4 and 5
would cost.
   Had the projects been honestly represented, he said, WPPSS would
never have been welcomed at the bond market.
   Barr said the utilities soon realized after construction of the
two plants had begun that they had acted recklessly. But, he said,
they went ahead in the belief that the federal Bonneville Power
Administration would assume debts for the plants, as it had done
for WPPSS plant Nos. 1, 2 and 3.
   That would have reduced the utilities' obligation by two-thirds,
he said.
   Barr noted that in the first of 14 bond sales, in 1977, the
plants' cost was estimated at $3.37 billion. By mid-1981, the cost
had jumped to $11.8 billion and dates for completing that plants
had slipped several years.
   Barr said the utilities' ultimate ``ace up the sleeve'' was to
litigate their way out of their predicament.
   ``They intended first to go to court and to get their state
courts to get them out of their promises,'' he said, adding that
that strategy worked.
   In 1983, the Washington Supreme Court ruled that utilities that
had signed contracts with WPPSS for construction of plants 4 and 5
lacked authority to make those agreements. The court said the
utilities could not obligate customers to pay for plants that might
never be built.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
