<1ST_LINE>u f PM-EconomyRdp 1stLd-Writethru   09-15 0492</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Economy Rdp, 1st Ld-Writethru,0508</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Trade Deficit Plunges In July; Report Cheers Markets</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS with 4 grafs to show August retail sales up; picks up
2nd graf pvs, ``The Commerce ... ''</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By PETER COY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Retail sales declined last month, providing further evidence
that the economy is slowing and inflation pressures are easing.
   The Commerce Department reported today that retail sales
declined 0.2 percent, or $330 million, to a seasonally adjusted
$133.5 billion in August, pulled down by the sharpest drop in auto
sales in 10 months.
   Sales of women's apparel and furniture also declined while food
and gasoline sales were up slightly, the government said.
   Many economists said the report indicated that growth in
consumer demand has slowed.
   Meanwhile, the lowest monthly merchandise trade deficit since
December 1984 has encouraged financial markets that the United
States is on the way to solving its trade imbalance.
   The Commerce Department's report Wednesday that the trade
deficit fell to $9.53 billion in July from a revised $13.22 billion
in June was considered significant because it included a big drop
in imports.
   On Wall Street, the Dow Jones average of 30 industrials climbed
17.60 to 2,100.64 on Wednesday, closing above 2,100 for the first
time since it stood at 2,107.40 on Aug. 8. Bond prices rose
modestly and the dollar rallied.
   A decline in the nation's demand for imports could mean the
economy is cooling off somewhat, which would reduce pressure on
interest rates. The prospect for lower rates is good for the stock
and bond markets.
   Lower rates could be bad for the dollar by reducing the returns
on dollar-denominated assets. But the dollar rose, apparently
because the drop in the deficit indicated the dollar did not need
to weaken much to help erode the trade deficit.
   The dollar's rise occurred despite the Federal Reserve's
attempts to restrain it.
   Good news on trade preceded a leap in oil prices, triggered by
mounting concern that the Organization of Petroleum Exporting
Countries would succeed in cutting its oil production.
   After touching a nearly two-year low last week, the near-month
contract for West Texas Intermediate has soared about $1.65 a
barrel, rising 84 cents on Wednesday to $15.40 on the New York
Mercantile Exchange.
   In a second report Wednesday, the government said industrial
output rose a moderate 0.2 percent in August, pushing production up
a healthy 5.3 percent over a year ago. Much of this gain reflects
the boom in export sales that American companies have enjoyed.
   In other economic news Wednesday:
   _Sales of U.S.-made cars and trucks fell 9 percent in early
September, according to figures automakers released Wednesday, but
changes in incentives made the figures difficult to compare with
those of a year earlier.
   _The Conference Board, a private research group, said consumers
felt more confident about the economy last month than in the
previous two months after a devastating drought in the nation's
farm belt came to an end.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880915-0236 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-09-15-88 0953EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f BC-Iraq-Oil     09-15 0497</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Iraq-Oil,0514</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Iraq Says It Won't Lower Oil Output; Might Increase Production</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Subroto, one name, is correct</NOTE>
<DATELINE>KUWAIT (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Iraq will not agree to lower its output of oil
even if other OPEC members ask and may even increase production,
the country's oil minister said in an interview published Thursday.
   The minister, Issam Abdul-Rahim al-Chalabi, told the Al-Watan
newspaper that Iraq would not rule out increasing its output from
2.7 million barrels a day as part of an effort to rebuild its
shattered economy after eight years of war with Iran.
   Iraq has refused to abide by a quota of 1.5 million barrels a
day set by the Organization of Petroleum Exporting Countries
because its Persian Gulf enemy has been allowed to produce 2.3
million barrels a day.
   OPEC Secretary-General Subroto has held talks with several
members of the cartel recently, including Iran, who are opposed to
raising Iraq's official quota to parity with Iran.
   However, the newspaper Thursday said Chalabi's latest statements
indicate Baghdad no longer is interested in gaining parity with
Iran or in accepting any assigned quota.
   ``We sacrificed and lost a lot in the eight years of hostilities
during which we could not produce our output quota,'' the minister
was quoted as saying.
   ``Therefore, we are not prepared to sacrifice more as we now
have our construction commitments and debt which we should repay.''
   The minister declined to estimate by how much Iraq might
increase its oil exports, saying it would ``depend to a large
extent on the state of our ports.''
   ``But our output will be larger when the second stage of the
Iraqi-Saudi pipeline is completed in September 1989,'' he said.
   The pipeline to the Red Sea and another via Turkey to the
Mediterranean were oil export outlets Iraq used after its ports
were damaged and shipments through the gulf blocked by the war.
   Oil prices have risen sharply in recent days after a steady
decline in previous weeks prompted by fears of a world oversupply
of oil. The sharp rise in prices started Monday was fueled by
reports suggesting that OPEC could be closer to limiting production.
   Chalabi dismissed as ``baseless'' charges that Iraq was
responsible for the overall decline in oil prices, saying: ``Iraqi
production did not change whereas oil prices dropped by 30
percent.''
   OPEC is producing at least 3.5 million barrels a day more than
its self-imposed collective quota of 15 million barrels. Crude is
selling between $14 and $15.50 a barrel on world markets. OPEC's
benchmark price is $18.
   The New York-based Petroleum Intelligence Weekly reported in
August that Iraq was exporting 500,000 barrels of oil a day to the
United States.
   Chalabi said that talk of a U.S. embargo of Iraqi oil because of
Iraq's alleged use of chemical weapons against Turkish refugees did
not worry him.
   ``Iraq will be able to find markets for selling its oil, and
consequently our oil exports will not be affected by any embargo,''
Chalabi said.
</TEXT>
