<DOCNO> AP880915-0241 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-09-15-88 1112EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>s f BC-IBMAdjusts Adv18   09-15 1166</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-IBM Adjusts, Adv 18,1202</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$adv 18</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Sunday Sept. 18</NOTE>
<HEAD>IBM: The Giant Of Computers Is Thinking Small</HEAD>
<HEAD>RETRANSMITTING FOR ALL NEEDING</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserGraphic</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PETER COY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The United States doesn't have the world's
biggest phone company anymore. Or the biggest banks. Or even the
world's biggest stock market.
   But it still has the world's biggest computer company.
International Business Machines Corp. towers over almost every
facet of the world information industry, which is burgeoning in
size to rival oil and autos.
   Even with the dollar at depressed levels, IBM's $54 billion in
revenue last year was more than triple that of its closest Japanese
competitor, Fujitsu Ltd., which pulled in $16 billion.
   Now, though, even Big Blue is adjusting to a new age of limits.
Like the United States as a whole, the computer giant is
discovering that the rules of the game are changing. It has
encountered fierce new competitors on unaccustomed battlefields and
found its old weapons inadequate.
   This past week, nine smaller rivals ganged up to adopt a new
data pathway for personal computers, rejecting the one IBM had
hoped to establish as an industry standard.
   In adjusting, IBM has cut jobs (without layoffs), trimmed
expansion plans and learned to be less imperious with customers.
   IBM clearly intends to stay on top of the heap, but it has
learned painfully that too-rapid growth has its drawbacks.
   ``They're being hit from all sides by the Japanese as well as
smaller American companies that are faster on their feet and don't
suffer the problem of bureaucracy,'' said Bernard Slade, a former
IBMer who is a senior management consultant with United Research
Co. in Morristown, N.J.
   Being big means IBM can afford to spend $5.4 billion a year on
research, development and engineering, more than the entire revenue
of all but 75 of the Fortune 500 companies.
   It also means IBM is the only company that offers products in
everysegment from personal computers to mainframes to software.
That gives it an advantage in the coming era of ``systems
integration,'' when customers will focus on tying their equipment
into a smoothly running whole.
   But size isn't everything, as General Motors Corp. and the
Defense Department well know.
   John F. Akers, the 53-year-old former Navy fighter pilot who
heads IBM, has been striving to streamline the company by reducing
staff and moving more people into jobs that deal directly with
customers.
   The chairman and chief executive was asked in June at a news
conference in London whether the decentralization was an
acknowledgement that being big had its problems.
   ``No question about it,'' he said.
   Akers told the London reporters he wants IBM people to take more
risks and act more like entrepreneurs at every level of the
company, ``which by its very nature suggests we are going to make
more mistakes in the future than we have in the past.''
   One sign that IBM has not entirely changed its strategy is its
continued commitment _ restated this past week _ to grow over the
long term at the same rate as the overall industry in each of the
areas in which it participates.
   ``Long term'' could be the key phrase because it gives the
company leeway to hold back on expansion when it is prudent to do
so.
   Trying to match a 20 percent industry growth spurt in a single
year could seriously discombobulate a company of IBM's size.
   IBM's profits fell in 1985 and 1986, the first case of
back-to-back earnings declines since the Great Depression, and many
analysts attributed it to overstaffing and overbuilding in the
early 1980s, when the company overestimated its growth potential.
   IBM is determined not to let that happen again, says Marc
Schulman of Salomon Brothers Inc. in a recent research report.
   ``We believe that the company has determined that it is not in
its interest to attempt to maintain or increase market share at all
times in all markets,'' Schulman wrote.
   Most observers agree IBM is nimbler than other big companies and
they praise the company's no-layoff tradition, which has endured in
spite of the effort to become leaner and meaner.
   ``It's created a higher degree of esprit de corps, a better
environment for people to work, and a higher degree of
professionalism because people have been wedded to the company,''
said Slade, who spent 16 years at the company.
   ``In essence, IBM has been warehousing employees until such time
as they become necessary,'' said Salomon's Schulman.
   Being IBM means carrying a lot of baggage_ product lines such as
mainframes that made it into the giant of today but will be
relatively less important in the future.
   ``The biggest piece of baggage they have to drag around is
compatibility with the 370 (series) mainframe user base,'' which
accounted for about $28 billion of IBM's $54 billion in revenue
last year, including related add-ons, software and maintenance,
said David H. Andrews, president of ADM Inc. in Cheshire, Conn.
   ``They can't do anything to radically disturb that (mainframe
business), but it doesn't provide much opportunity, either,'' said
Andrews, whose company provides consulting to IBM corporate
customers.
   IBM's size gives it the potential, at least theoretically, to
force competitors out of business. Indeed, the Justice Department
filed an antitrust suit against IBM in 1969 and didn't drop the
action until 1982 under the Reagan administration.
   Although IBM no longer has to tiptoe the way it once did, it is
still on warning not to emphasize its size in its advertising.
   The kind of practices that helped IBM grow in the past _ and
drew the scrutiny of antitrust lawyers _ are the same ones that are
inhibiting the company today.
   Critics say IBM intentionally segmented the market with a
variety of incompatible computers so that it could manipulate
prices, lowering them in the segments under attack from rivals
while keeping fat profit margins in segments where it faced less
competition.
   IBM says it made different kinds of computers to satisfy
different kinds of customers. In any case, the lack of
compatibility left an opening for competitors such as Digital
Equipment Corp., which uses a single operating system in its entire
Vax line.
   If IBM makes it easy for its computers to interconnect with each
other and competitors' models, it will open its sheltered accounts
to the fiercest competition ever. It is a risky strategy, but the
alternative is to stick with a steadily dwindling group of IBM
loyalists.
   IBM is taking the risk _ spending $200 million this year alone
on the AIX base software that is one key to the highly competitive
``open systems'' of the future.
   IBM's strategy of cutting costs, decentralizing and plunging
into the competitive market of open systems indicates that the
people running the giant realize they are in a new era and are
determined to adapt to it.
   ``IBM's grand plan,'' said ADM's Andrews, ``is to ensure growth
and dominance in the 1990s.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv Sunday Sept. 18</NOTE>
</DOC>
