<2ND_LINE>BC-Earns-Guinness, 1st Ld-Writethru, f0072,0344</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Guinness' Profit Up 19 Percent in First Half</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDS: SUBS 7th graf pvs to CORRECT to decline in interest charges
sted increase; SWITCHES position of 7th and 8th grafs pvs to
clarify; picks up 9th graf pvs bg'ng, ``In the ...</NOTE>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Guinness PLC said its profit after taxes rose 19
percent in the first half of 1988 from a year earlier, helped by a
large reduction in the interest charges on its debt.
   The big British liquor company reported Thursday that its profit
for the first six months of the year rose to 111 million pounds, or
about $186 million, from 93 million pounds, or $156 million, in the
same period a year earlier.
   Earnings per share increased to 13.1 pence, or 22 cents, from
11.1 pence, or 19 cents.
   For nearly two years, Guinness has been embroiled in a scandal
surrounding its 1986 takeover of Distillers Co. PLC, a British gin
and whisky maker.
   Guinness has admitted that its former management arranged for
third parties to repurchase Guinness' stock, apparently to boost
its share price and make its cash and stock offer for Distillers
more attractive than a rival bid. Seven men face criminal charges
in the case, including Ernest Saunders, Guinness' former chairman
and chief executive.
   Guinness' revenue in the first half jumped 16 percent _ to 1.14
billion pounds, or around $1.92 billion, from 986 million pounds,
or $1.66 billion.
   Interest charges paid by the company fell 33 percent in the
period, to 24 million pounds, or $40 million.
   The decline reflects the reduction in Guinness' debt as it has
received the proceeds from the sale of several peripheral
businesses outside its core spirits and brewing operations.
   ``In the first half of 1988, we made considerable progress in
furthering our declared strategy to build on our core businesses of
spirits and brewing,'' Guinness Chief Executive Anthony Tennant
said.
   The company didn't provide separate quarterly results. It isn't
required to do so under British law.
</TEXT>
