<1ST_LINE>u f PM-BoardofTrade Open   09-15 0319</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Board of Trade, Open,0331</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Crop Futures Open Lower</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Grain and soybean futures opened slightly lower
today on the Chicago Board of Trade as fears eased about Hurricane
Gilbert's potential threat to Southern soybean crops.
   Crop futures prices had risen moderately Wednesday as the raging
storm approached the Gulf of Mexico. But analysts said today it
appeared the hurricane would skirt the central section of Texas'
southern coast, reducing the potential for serious crop damage.
   Some concern remained that Gilbert would spawn storms in the
Midwest, where weekend showers moving in from the West already were
expected to slow the corn and soybean harvest _ a prospect that
should support prices, analysts said.
   ``The farmers could be out of their fields for a few days,''
said Jerry Gidel, grain market analyst with the Chicago-based G.H.
Miller division of British-owned LIT America Inc.
   The Agriculture Department's rejection of several bids for
subsidized U.S. wheat sent wheat prices lower this morning, he said.
   In early trading, wheat was 3{ cents to 4\ cents lower with the
contract for delivery in September at $4.09 a bushel; corn was
unchanged to 2} cents lower with September at $2.84 a bushel; oats
were unchanged to 3{ cents lower with September at $2.68 a bushel;
soybeans were 2{ cents to 7{ cents lower with September at $8.75 a
bushel.
   Livestock and meat futures were mostly lower in early trading on
the Chicago Mercantile Exchange.
   Live cattle were .68 cent lower to .27 cent higher with October
at 69.87 cents a pound; feeder cattle were .20 cent to .40 cent
lower with September at 79.55 cents a pound; hogs were .27 cent
lower to .20 cent higher with October at 37.95 cents a pound;
frozen pork bellies were .27 cent to .50 cent lower with February
at 47.80 cents a pound.
   Cattle futures settled higher on Wednesday while pork futures
were mixed.

</TEXT>
