<1ST_LINE>r f AM-Britain-Hamleys Bjt   09-15 0437</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Britain-Hamleys, Bjt,0453</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Famous Toy Store Put Up for Sale</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By COTTEN TIMBERLAKE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A playful bit of English tradition went on the
auction block Thursday.
   The owner of Hamleys of Regent Street, one of the world's
oldest, biggest and most famous toy shops, said the flagship store
and the Hamleys name will be sold, with hopes the new owner will
expand the business worldwide.
   ``We are selling a major piece of English heritage,'' said
Graham Watson, a spokesman. ``That history and heritage can be
exploited by the right buyers.''
   Major American retailers have expressed an interest in buying
the 228-year-old store, which holds a royal warrant as a toy and
sports merchant to Queen Elizabeth II, said the owner, Lowndes
Queensway PLC.
   The company said the sale would give a new owner the opportunity
to develop the Hamleys name by franchising or licensing it for use
in major international retailing centers; developing a Hamleys
brand of high quality toy, clothing and other products for sale
around the world; and through sponsoring prestigious events such as
the Wimbledon tennis tournament.
   Lowndes Queensway said it is selling Hamleys to concentrate on
its furniture and carpet businesses.
   The company set an Oct. 3 deadline for bids and said it expected
to announce a purchaser at the end of next month.
   ``It is a unique brand and a unique opportunity and we believe
the price will reflect that uniqueness,'' said Watson, who is a
director of Noble Grossart Ltd., the firm that is handling the sale.
   Lowndes Queensway shut down 10 other Hamley stores throughout
Britain this year after the chain's previous owner, Harris
Queensway PLC, failed in an attempt to expand domestically.
   Lowndes Ventures PLC, a holding company, acquired Harris
Queensway last month, saying it would return Harris Queensway to
its core businesses of furniture and carpet retailing. Hamleys is
the first unrelated business being sold.
   ``The future for Hamleys lies not in opening stores throughout
the U.K. (United Kingdom), but is to have Hamleys stores and
Hamleys goods in places like New York, Paris and Rome,'' Watson
said.
   Located on Regent Street, one of London's finest shopping
streets, Hamleys boasts an extensive range of merchandise _ more
than 25,000 product lines.
   Founded in 1760 by toymaker William Hamley, the retailer
currently is making a pre-tax profit equivalent to about $3.4
million on annual sales of about $31 million, Watson said.
   Watson said many of up to 40 inquiries Lowndes Queensway already
has received came from parties overseas.
   ``The ownership of Hamleys may become foreign at the end of this
exercise,'' he said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
