<HEAD>London Shares Up</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: New thruout with closing prices, comment.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Share prices rose Thursday in moderate trading on
the London Stock Exchange, as the market awaited some new British
inflation figures.
   ``We're in a period now where we're always waiting for the next
indicator so we're not seeing any real underneath interest except
in speculative situations,'' one analyst said.
   The Financial Times-Stock Exchange 100-share index edged up 4.2
points, or 0.2 percent, to 1,769.3. The index was up as much as
10.7 points at mid-morning before sliding back in a jittery market.
   Volume was 435.3 million shares, up from 394.6 million shares
Wednesday.
   Traders said shares slipped from higher levels on rekindled
worries over the possibility of rising interest rates.
   They said the market was unsettled by Chancellor of the
Exchequer Nigel Lawson's remark Wednesday that the British retail
sales price index for August, to be released Friday, will show a
``significant increase.''
   The Financial Times 30-share index rose 5.5 points to 1,422.0.
The Financial Times 500-share index rose 3.19 points to close at
1,001.80.
