<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The stock market barely budged today,
registering little response to new signs of a slowing economy.
   The Dow Jones average of 30 industrials edged up .36 to 2,101.00
by 2 p.m. on Wall Street.
   Gainers and losers ran about even in the overall tally of New
York Stock Exchange-listed issues, with 643 up, 663 down and 555
unchanged.
   The Commerce Department reported this morning that retail sales
declined 0.2 percent in August, after a downward-revised 0.1
percent increase in July.
   That buttressed recent evidence that economic growth has slowed
since midyear, apparently taking some of the pressure off the
Federal Reserve to try to restrain the pace of expansion.
   News Wednesday of a larger-than-expected decline in the nation's
trade deficit, and in particular of a decline in imports, also
prompted talk that the danger of an ``overheating'' economy was
subsiding.
   But analysts said investors still weren't inclined to commit
themselves heavily to stocks, in part because interest-bearing
investments still offer high yields relative to inflation and to
prospective returns on stocks.
   Hospital Corp. of America jumped 6~ to 44 on word that members
of its top management proposed a leveraged buyout at about $47 a
share.
   Other hospital management stocks moved up in sympathy. Humana
rose ~ to 26}; National Medical Enterprises 1[ to 21{, and American
Medical International | to 16{.
   Major retailing issues showed little effect from the August
sales report. Sears Roebuck was unchanged at 36|; K mart lost 1 to
35[, and J.C. Penney was down | at 48[.
   The NYSE's composite index of all its listed common stocks
dipped .09 to 152.04. At the American Stock Exchange, the market
value index was down .61 at 297.74.
   Volume on the Big Board came to 106.22 million shares with two
hours to go.
