<FILEID>AP-NR-09-15-88 1615EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f AM-US-BritainFutures     09-15 0182</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-US-Britain Futures,0189</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>CFTC To Share Information With British Government</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Commodity Futures Trading Commission said
Thursday it had reached agreement to share information with the
British government in an effort to better coordinate regulation of
the futures industry.
   CFTC Chairman Wendy Gramm said that the agreement reached with
the Securities and Investment Board of the United Kingdom would
allow for exchanging information about U.S. futures firms operating
branches in London and British firms which solicit American
customers.
   Among other things, she said British regulators had agreed to
accept financial data filed with the CFTC by U.S. firms and would
drop requirements for essentially duplicative filings from those
firms' London offices.
   Under the agreement, the CFTC and the American industry's own
policing organizations agreed to alert British regulators about
developments which would signal a firm could be in financial
trouble.
   British regulators agreed to share information about financial
problems detected in the London offices of U.S. firms or with
British firms soliciting business from American investors.
   The CFTC said that about 20 U.S. futures firms operate London
offices.
</TEXT>
