<2ND_LINE>BC-Board of Trade, Close,0254</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Crop Futures Close Lower After Technical Rally Fails</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Grain and soybean futures closed broadly lower
Thursday on the Chicago Board of Trade after an attempt to rally
soybean prices to last week's highs fizzled, prompting a rapid
last-minute sell-off.
   The mid-session buyers, led by brokerage-house and
commodity-fund traders, ``all ended up scattering to the winds in
the last final seconds,'' said Jerry Gidel, an analyst in Chicago
with the G.H. Miller division of the British-owned trading company
LIT America Inc.
   Gidel said fears of crop damage from Hurricane Gilbert _ a major
factor in Wednesday's price rally _ had largely dissipated on
expectations that the storm would skirt most of the Texas coastline.
   Higher cash prices for U.S. soybean meal and rumors that the
Soviet Union may have bought up to 500,000 metric tons of Argentine
soybean meal also contributed to the mid-session rally, Gidel said.
   But analysts said the midday buyers turned sellers when they
found no support for soybean prices above $8.90 for September
delivery and $9.03{ for November delivery.
   At the close, wheat was 5\ cents to 7 cents lower with the
contract for delivery in September at $4.08 a bushel; corn was 2
cents to 5{ cents lower with September at $2.82 a bushel; oats were
1 cent to 4{ cents lower with September at $2.67 a bushel; soybeans
were 5 cents to 9 cents lower with September at $8.73 a bushel.
</TEXT>
