<FILEID>AP-NR-09-15-88 1736EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f AM-Seabrook-Resignation     09-15 0436</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Seabrook-Resignation,0457</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Citing Health Reasons, Harrison Resigns As President of Troubled
Utility</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MICHAEL MOKRZYCKI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CONCORD, N.H. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The president of Public Service Company of
New Hampshire, the first major investor-owned electric company
since the Depression to seek bankruptcy protection, has resigned
due to health reasons, the utility announced Thursday.
   Robert Harrison, 56, joined the state's largest power company 31
years ago and became president in 1981.
   He had been vice president since 1973, overseeing finances for
the building of the company's $5.6 billion Seabrook nuclear plant,
which was completed two years ago but remains unlicensed because of
evacuation-planning obstacles.
   At a special meeting Wednesday, the utility's board of directors
named John Duffett, its chief operating officer and a 32-year
veteran of the company, to succeed Harrison.
   Duffett, 60, becomes the fifth president in the utility's
62-year history. The directors also named William Scharffenberger,
67, as board chairman, a position that had been unfilled.
   Scharffenberger, who is president and chief executive officer of
Wheeling-Pittsburgh Steel Corp., has ``extensive experience in
corporate reorganizations,'' Public Service said in a statement.
   Wheeling-Pittsburgh, based in Wheeling, W.Va., has been under
Chapter 11 federal bankruptcy protection since April 1985.
   Delays in licensing the Seabrook project forced Public Service
to seek protection from its creditors under Chapter 11 of the
federal bankruptcy laws on Jan. 28.
   Scharffenberger said the board expects a smooth transition of
leadership that would not delay filing of a reorganization plan
with the bankruptcy court. Public Service has until Dec. 27 to file
such a plan.
   Harrison, who has a history of heart disorders, will retire
under the company's disability benefits program, the company said.
   ``He has been under a lot of stress, and his doctor has ordered
him to relieve himself of that stress,'' a company director, Philip
Dunlap, said in an interview Thursday.
   In a statement, Harrison said he was ``deeply disappointed that
it is necessary to leave in the midst of the restoration of PSNH's
financial health.''
   Harrison was active in obtaining financing for Seabrook, which
Public Service began building in 1976.
   But as construction began, so did protests which blossomed into
mass demonstrations that made Seabrook a symbol of the nation's
anti-nuclear movement.
   Public Service's financial condition worsened as construction
continued, and in 1979 a state law went into effect that bars the
company from charging ratepayers for Seabrook before the plant
operates commercially. The utility, which originally owned 50
percent of the project, reduced its share to 36 percent after 1979.
   The first of two planned Seabrook reactor was completed but a
second officially was canceled in 1986.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
