<DOCNO> AP880915-0255 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-09-15-88 1816EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f AM-PacificGrowth     09-15 0332</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Pacific Growth,0344</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Asia-Pacific Region To Have Strongest Growth in 1990s, Study Says</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Asia-Pacific region will be the fastest
growing economic area in the world in the 1990s, a study predicted
Thursday.
   But unlike past years when exports from Japan, Korea, Taiwan,
Hong Kong and Singapore to the rest of the world fueled the
region's progress, the engine of growth in the next decade will be
trade among the area's 12 nations, the report said.
   The 60-page study was prepared by SRI International, a research
firm, and released by the worldlwide accounting firm KPMG Peat
Marwick.
   ``The United States and Western Europe will not support further
large increases in Asia-Pacific exports,'' the report said.
``Therefore, the region will have to depend to a greater extent
than in the past on trade within the region and on development of
their domestic economies.''
   It forecast the annual growth rate for the region would average
about two percentage points higher than the world as a whole over
the 1990s.
   Among the report's predictions for the region:
   _China will have the fastest growing economy, averaging 6.7
percent a year, but its per-capita income will still be the lowest
of the 12 nations.
   _The newly industrializing countries _ South Korea, Hong Kong,
Singapore and Taiwan _ will continue to experience strong growth,
but at a slower pace than during the past several decades. South
Korea is expected to have average growth of around 6.5 percent a
year, with the other three ranging between 5.5 percent and 6
percent.
   _Growth in Thailand and Malaysia will average 5 percent a year.
   _Indonesia and the Philippines will continue to have the weakest
economies, with average annual growth rates of 4 percent and 3
percent, respectively.
   _The three developed countries in the region _ Japan, Australia
and New Zealand _ will have the slowest growth rates. Japan will
lead the trio with an average annual growth rate of slightly more
than 3 percent a year.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
