<1ST_LINE>u f PM-WallStreetClosing     09-15 0147</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Wall Street Closing,0157</2ND_LINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A late bout of selling pushed stock prices lower
today as the market registered little response to new signs of a
slowing economy.
   The Commerce Department reported this morning that retail sales
declined 0.2 percent in August, after a downward-revised 0.1
percent increase in July.
   That buttressed recent evidence that economic growth has slowed
since midyear, apparently taking some of the pressure off the
Federal Reserve to try to restrain the pace of expansion.
   News Wednesday of a larger-than-expected decline in the nation's
trade deficit, and in particular of a decline in imports, also
prompted talk that the danger of an ``overheating'' economy was
subsiding.
   But analysts said investors still weren't inclined to commit
themselves heavily to stocks, in part because interest-bearing
investments continue to offer high yields relative to inflation and
to prospective returns on stocks.
