<HEAD>Dollar Mixed, Gold Down</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Precedes LONDON BC</NOTE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The dollar turned mixed Thursday against most
key currencies as dealers assessed the impact of improved U.S.
trade figures for July.
   Gold prices declined. Republic National Bank in New York quoted
bullion at $418.50 a troy ounce as of 4 p.m. EDT, down from $429.80
late Wednesday.
   Currency dealers said the dollar fluctuated within a tight range
most of the session following Wednesday's rally that stemmed from a
report showing the U.S. trade deficit fell to $9.5 billion in July
from $13.2 billion in June.
   The government attributed the improvment largely to a sharp drop
in imports.
   ``The trade numbers gave a boost to the dollar but the fact that
imports are down indicated continued evidence of a slowing down of
the economy,'' said James T. McGroarty, a trader at Discount Corp.
in New York. ``That's why we have such a mixed picture. You can say
the dollar is in a holding pattern.''
   Traders said that concerns about possible central-bank
intervention to buffet the dollar's rise also were responsible for
holding the the U.S. currency in check.
   The financial markets were closed in Tokyo for a national
holiday. But in London, the dollar fell to 133.90 Japanese yen from
134.55 yen at Wednesday's close in Tokyo. In New York, the dollar
stood at 133.775 yen, down from 134.275 Wednesday.
   The dollar rose in London against the British pound, which
slipped to $1.6675 from $1.6750 late Wednesday. Sterling fetched
$1.6790 in New York, down from $1.67935 late Wednesday.
   Other late-dollar rates in New York compared with levels late
Wednesday: 1.87475 West German marks, down from 1.8770; 1.58235
Swiss francs, up from 1.58165; 1.2225 Canadian dollars, down from
1.22415; 6.37625 French francs, down from 6.3865; and 1,398.70
Italian lire, down from 1,398.75.
   Late dollar rates in Europe, compared with late rates Wednesday:
1.8775 West German marks, down from 1.8783; 1.5820 Swiss francs,
down from 1.5835; 6.3790 French francs, down from 6.3915; 2.1160
Dutch guilders, up from 2.1155; 1.2225 Canadian dollars, up from
1.2223; and 1,398.87 Italian lire, down from 1,399.50.
   On the Commodity Exchange in New York, gold for current delivery
fell $2.70 to $418.60 a troy ounce.
   In London, gold fell to a late bid`of 6417.75 a troy ounce, down
from $421.75 late Wednesday. In Zurich, gold fell to $417.50 an
ounce from $421.50 late Wednesday.
   Earlier, in Hong Kong, gold closed at $423.45 an ounce,
unchanged from Wednesday's close.
   Silver prices were weaker. On the New York Comex, silver bullion
for current delivery fell to $6.467 a troy ounce from $6.489
Wednesday. Silver slipped to a late bid of $6.44 an ounce in
London, down from $6.53 Wednesday.
</TEXT>
