<BYLINE>By CHET CURRIER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The stock market pulled back near the close of a
drifting session Thursday, registering little response to new signs
of a slowing economy.
   The Dow Jones average of 30 industrials, which spent much of the
day hovering around Wednesday's closing levels, finished with an
8.36 loss at 2,092.28.
   Declining issues outnumbered advances by about 8 to 7 in
nationwide trading of New York Stock Exchange-listed stocks, with
665 up, 766 down and 520 unchanged.
   Volume on the floor of the Big Board came to 161.20 million
shares, down from 177.22 million in the previous session.
Nationwide, consolidated volume in NYSE-listed issues, including
trades in those stocks on regional exchanges and in the
over-the-counter market, totaled 194.60 million shares.
   The Commerce Department reported Thursday morning that retail
sales declined 0.2 percent in August, after a downward-revised 0.1
percent increase in July.
   That buttressed recent evidence that economic growth has slowed
since midyear, apparently taking some of the pressure off the
Federal Reserve to try to restrain the pace of expansion.
   News the day before of a larger-than-expected decline in the
nation's trade deficit, and in particular of a decline in imports,
also prompted talk that the danger of an ``overheating'' economy
was subsiding.
   But analysts said investors still weren't inclined to commit
themselves heavily to stocks, in part because interest-bearing
investments still offer high yields relative to inflation and to
prospective returns on stocks.
   Hospital Corp. of America jumped 6| to 43} on word that members
of its top management proposed a leveraged buyout at about $47 a
share.
   Other hospital management stocks moved up in sympathy. Humana
rose | to 26{; National Medical Enterprises 1\ to 21|, and American
Medical International } to 16|.
