<1ST_LINE>u f AM-GMRecalls     09-15 0205</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-GM Recalls,0212</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>GM Announces Recalls of Trucks, Vans, School Buses</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DETROIT (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   General Motors Corp. on Thursday recalled about
30,500 cars, trucks, vans and school buses for safety-related
inspections and repairs.
   GM said it was aware of just one accident and no injuries
involving the vehicles.
   About 8,000 1988 Buick Regals were being recalled for inspection
and possible replacement of a brake hose which could wear through
and result in a reduction of braking capability, the automaker said
in a written statement.
   GM said about 21,000 1985 and 1986 Chevrolet and GMC P-30 trucks
and G-30 vans were being recalled to repair a control arm in the
front suspension. The arm could crack, resulting in a loss of
steering control, the company said.
   The 1,500 1987 and 1988 model Chevrolet and GMC school buses,
all equipped with gasoline engines, were being recalled because of
possible problems in the location of air brake lines. The lines may
have been put too close to exhaust systems, causing wearing and a
partial or complete loss of brakes.
   The company said the only accident of which it was aware
involved a P-30 truck and did not result in an injury.
   Repairs will be performed for free.
</TEXT>
